{"title_page": "ITN", "text_new": "{{short description|British-based news and content provider}}\n{{About|the news provider in the United Kingdom|the channel in Sri Lanka|Independent Television Network|the news programme on ITV produced by the company|ITV News|other uses|ITN (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Independent Television News\n| logo = ITN logo.svg\n| logo_size = 150px\n| image = File:Holborn, ITN Building, 200 Gray's Inn Road, WC1 - geograph.org.uk - 667814.jpg\n| image_size = 230px \n| image_caption = Headquarters at 200 [[Gray's Inn Road]]\n| type = [[Private company limited by shares]]\n| genre = [[News broadcasting]]\n| hq_location = 200 [[Gray's Inn Road]]\n| hq_location_city = [[London]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United Kingdom]]\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1955|05|4|df=yes|p=y|br=y}}\n| founder = [[Independent Television Authority]]\n| key_people = Anna Mallett ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])\n| num_employees = 712\n| num_employees_year = 2018\n| revenue = {{Increase}} {{GBP|126.9 million|long=no|link=yes}}\n| revenue_year = 2018\n| operating_income = {{Decrease}} {{GBP|1.3 million|long=no|link=yes}}\n| income_year = 2018\n| net_income = {{Decrease}} {{GBP|1.2 million|long=no|link=yes}}\n| net_income_year = 2018\n| assets = {{Increase}} {{GBP|6.4 million|long=no|link=yes}}\n| assets_year = 2018\n| equity = {{Increase}} {{GBP|91.2 million|long=no|link=yes}}\n| equity_year = 2018\n| owners = {{ubl|[[ITV plc]] (40%)|[[Daily Mail and General Trust|DMGT]] (20%)|[[Thomson Reuters]] (20%)|[[Informa]] (20%)}}\n| divisions = {{ubl|Broadcast News|ITN Productions}}\n| homepage = {{URL|itn.co.uk}}\n| footnotes = <ref name=\"annual-report-2018\">{{cite book |title=ITN Annual Report 2018 |url=https://www.itn.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/ITN-Annual-Report-2018-Digital.pdf |accessdate=20 April 2020 |ref=annual-report-2018 |language=en-gb}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Independent Television News Limited |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/00548648 |publisher=[[Companies House]] |accessdate=20 April 2020 |ref=companies-house |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Independent Television News''' ('''ITN''') is a UK-based television production company. It is made up of two divisions: Broadcast News and ITN Productions. ITN is based in [[London]], with bureaux and offices in [[Beijing]], [[Brussels]], [[Jerusalem]], [[Johannesburg]], [[New York City|New York]], [[Paris]], [[Sydney]] and [[Washington, D.C.|Washington DC]].\n\nITN produces the daily news programmes for ITV, Channel 4 and Channel 5 in the UK, and in recent years has diversified to produce a wide range of content including documentaries, sports, advertising and digital material for a range of international clients.\n\nBetween 1955 and 1999, ITN was more commonly known as the general brand name of ITV's news programmes. Since 8 March 1999, ITV has used ''[[ITV News]]'' as the brand name for its news programmes, though ITN continues as the network's news provider.\n\n==History==\nITN was founded in May 1955 by a consortium of the initial four [[Independent Television Authority|Independent Television]] (later ITV) broadcasting companies, with former [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP [[Aidan Crawley]] as editor-in-chief. One of those companies, the London weekday contract-holder [[Associated-Rediffusion]] offered the new company studio space in its headquarters in [[Aldwych]], London. The first bulletin was broadcast at 10pm on 22 September 1955 on ITV's launch night. The bulletin was presented by former champion athlete [[Christopher Chataway]]. From the start, ITN broke new ground by introducing in-vision and named 'newscasters' (rather than the BBC's nameless and sound-only 'newsreaders'), and reporter packages. The unique, probing reporting style of [[Robin Day]] caused shock among politicians, finding themselves questioned continually for information \u2013 this had never been the case with the [[BBC]]. There was also some early tensions with the ITV companies. [[Associated British Corporation|ABC Television]], the ITV contractor for the north and Midlands on weekends, immediately called for shorter ITN bulletins. While the [[Independent Television Authority|ITA]] ruled on a minimum of a 20-minute bulletin, disagreements with the ITV companies over ITN's budget triggered the resignation of its news editor [[Aidan Crawley]] after just one year in 1956. He was replaced by [[Geoffrey Cox (journalist)|Geoffrey Cox]].<ref name=\"cultures\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vbLlAAAAQBAJ|title=Itv Cultures: Independent Television Over Fifty Years: Independent Television Over Fifty Years|first1=Johnson|last1=Catherine|first2=Turnock|last2=Rob|date=1 September 2005|publisher=McGraw-Hill Education (UK)|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the early years, ITN continued to develop its service to the ITV network with an agenda to firstly, fulfil its public service broadcasting requirements and secondly satisfy the ITV companies by attracting viewers. Under this method, ITN continued to differentiate itself from the BBC by conducting probing interviews, introducing more human interest stories and bringing ordinary people on to screen by using so-called 'vox pops' (interviews, usually held in the street, with members of the general public), all of which were seen as a radical departure at the time in British broadcasting.<ref name=\"cultures\"/> As the ITN reporter and later ITN political editor [[Julian Haviland]], put it: \"My view was that at ITN we must be at least as responsible and accurate as the BBC, without being so damned boring\".<ref>{{cite book|title=And Finally... The History of ITN|first=Richard|last=Lindley|publisher=[[Methuen Publishing|Politico's Publishing]]|location=London|year=2005|isbn=9781842750674}}</ref> As ITV expanded, each ITV company that made up the network's federal structure had to purchase a stake in ITN and to continue to finance the company.\n\nIn 1967, ITN was given the go-ahead by the ITA to provide a full 30-minute daily news programme at 10pm on ITV. There was further tension with the ITV executives as they were sceptical of the idea that viewers would want a full 30 minutes of news every Monday to Friday and they were also losing valuable peak time slots which could be used for the sale of commercial advertising. ''[[ITV News at Ten|News at Ten]]'' began broadcasting on 3 July 1967 with a newscaster team consisting of [[Alastair Burnet]], [[Andrew Gardner (newsreader)|Andrew Gardner]], [[George Ffitch]] and [[Reginald Bosanquet]]. It was initially given a 13-week trial run, however, the programme proved to be extremely popular with viewers and continued for a further 32 years. ''News at Ten'' was to become one of the most prestigious news programmes of its time in British history with a reputation for high-quality journalism and innovation.<ref name=\"cultures\"/> ITN's ''News at Ten'' also prompted the BBC to gradually expand it's 20:50 news bulletin from ten minutes to fifteen, twenty and then twenty-five minutes. ''[[BBC Nine O'Clock News|The Nine O'Clock News]]'' began broadcasting in 1970 as ''News at Ten's'' rival. ITN also established other programmes in the ITV schedule. ''First Report'', a lunchtime bulletin began in 1972 and by 1976, ''News at 5.45'' commenced. This was a period when ITN enjoyed its greatest plaudits, following [[Lord Annan]]'s 1977 report on the future of broadcasting, which declared: \"We subscribe to the generally held view that ITN has the edge over BBC news.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hayward|first=Anthony|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jul/20/sir-alastair-burnet|title=Sir Alastair Burnet obituary|date=2012-07-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nITN obtained the contract to produce ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' when the channel started broadcasting in 1982. The programme was launched by [[Peter Sissons]], [[Trevor McDonald]] and [[Sarah Hogg]]. The hour-long programme has been broadcast at 7pm since it started and has a reputation for high-quality journalism and thorough analysis. Further expansion came with the launch of [[Night Network|overnight television on ITV]] in 1988, with ITN providing hourly news bulletins, as well as the half-hour [[ITV News at 5:30|''ITN Morning News'']] to conclude the overnight schedules.\n\nUntil the 1990s, the individual ITV companies had an obligation to provide a national news programme, which required them to take a share in the ITN operation. Following the [[Broadcasting Act 1990]], ITN had to apply and bid for a licence to provide such services on these ITV network, and would have to fight competition in order to preserve its services, as had become the case with other ITV franchisees. The Broadcasting Act also allowed the Independent Television Commission to introduce ownership rules for news providers. The move was to transform the company from a 'cost centre' to a 'profit-making business'. The move saw 400 staff made redundant, and the closure of a number of international bureaux to claw back a \u00a310 million deficit in order to provide a competitive product to obtain the ITV news contract. Within three years the company turned to profit in 1993 with suggestions at the time that the company should be listed on the stock exchange.<ref name=\"cultures\"/>\n\nThe company launched ''[[5 News]]'' in 1997 following the foundation of [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]].\n\nThe 1990s saw major changes to the television landscape in Britain. The growth of multichannel television saw ITV's share of audience fall. Against this backdrop ITV itself became increasingly commercially aggressive. This was to be a major turning point in ITN's history which saw a reduction in the ITV news contract. By this period the main ITV companies [[Granada PLC|Granada]] and [[Carlton Communications|Carlton]] had also viewed unfavourably the scheduling of ''News at Ten'' which became a subject of dispute between ITN and the ITV companies. ITN favoured keeping the bulletin, however, the ITV companies claimed audiences were lost at 10pm as the news interrupted films and drama programming. ''News at Ten'' eventually ended in March 1999 with ITN's flagship bulletin moved to 6.30pm with a shorter late night bulletin at 11pm. Consolidation of the ITV network under a unified ITV brand also saw the removal of the on-screen ITN brand which was replaced with ''[[ITV News]]''.<ref name=\"cultures\"/> From this point, the ITN brand was gradually phased out and it is now only referenced to in the end production caption.\n\nIn 1997, ITN started producing the [[Royal Christmas Message]] every other year.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Plunkett|first=John|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jan/19/queen-christmas-message-sky-news|title=Queen's Christmas message to be produced by Sky for first time|date=2011-01-19|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nThe early years of the 21st century was to prove to be a challenging period. The axing of ''News at Ten'' caused public outcry and ITN's viewership figures fell by 13.9%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=onN_BAAAQBAJ|title=No News is Bad News: Radio, Television and the Public|first=Michael|last=Bromley|date=11 September 2014|publisher=Routledge|via=Google Books}}</ref> Political pressure and pressure from the media resulted in ITV bringing back a shorter 20 minute bulletin at 10pm three nights a week. The programme eventually lost share to the [[BBC News at Ten]] (which launched in 2000 to capitalise on ITV's move) and ITV eventually axed the programme again in 2004 and moved the bulletin to 10.30pm before bringing it back to 10pm again in 2008. The biggest challenge came in 2001 when [[British Sky Broadcasting]] bid to supply network news to ITV as part of a consortium. ITN eventually succeeded and was awarded a contract extension to 2008. In January 2005 Sky News took over supplying bulletins to [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]; ITN had produced ''[[5 News]]'' since its launch in 1997 and the contract was returned in February 2012, following a change of ownership at Channel 5.\n\nIn August 2000, ITN launched its own 24-hour news channel in the UK, broadcast on satellite, cable and digital terrestrial. It was 50% owned by ITN and 50% owned by [[Virgin Media|NTL]]. [[Carlton Communications|Carlton]] and [[Granada PLC|Granada]] gradually bought out the two stakes and renamed the channel the [[ITV News Channel]]. It closed down on 23 December 2005. Poor ratings in comparison to [[BBC News (TV channel)|BBC News 24]] and Sky News, and ITV's desire to re-use the channel's allocation on [[Freeview (UK)|Freeview]], were cited as the reasons.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Conlan|first=Tara|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/dec/14/tvnews.itv|title=ITV News Channel axed|date=2005-12-14|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2004 following its acquisition of the [[London News Network]], a company previously owned by the now merged [[Carlton Communications|Carlton]] and [[Granada PLC|Granada]], ITN began producing local news bulletins for the [[ITV London]] region. ITN produced [[More4 News]] between 2005 and 2009. In 2007 it began producing [[Setanta Sports News]]; however it closed in 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/setanta-uk-goes-into-administration-1.842268|title=Setanta UK goes into administration|last=|first=|date=23 June 2009|website=The Irish Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1996 and 2002, it also owned a share of [[London News Radio]], which was based at ITN's Gray's Inn Road headquarters and operated the [[LBC]] and [[LBC News 1152|News Direct London]] radio stations. ITN used to operate a radio news service on behalf of [[Independent Radio News]] (IRN) but on 15 October 2008, IRN announced that [[Sky News Radio]] was to replace ITN as its main supplier from March 2009.\n\nWhile news production remains the cornerstone of ITN's business model, the company has diversified from its original remit. ITN Source (originally ITN Archive) is one of the world's largest sources of historical film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itnsource.com/en/|title=The world's leading provider of archive footage|publisher=}}</ref> ITN Productions creates multi-platform content for major global brands, covering genres such as factual, entertainment, news and corporate production. Clients that commission award-winning programmes from ITN Productions include major UK and international broadcasters such as ITV, the BBC, Channel 4, Channel 5, History and Discovery, with television commissions including Climbing Great Buildings on BBC2 and Mud Men on History.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nativityfactor.com/Nativity/About|title=The Nativity Factor \u2013 About|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n[[File:ITN OB Van.jpg|thumb|250px|An ITN satellite van]]\n\n===ITV News===\n{{main|ITV News}}\n\n{{More citations needed section|date = February 2012}}\nITN has produced all national news bulletins on ITV since the network was launched on 22 September 1955. Originally the ITN logo and brand featured prominently on all news bulletins on ITV, however, since March 1999, bulletins have been branded as ''[[ITV News]]''. Trademarks of ''ITV News'' include the use of the clock-face of the [[Elizabeth Tower]] of [[Westminster Palace]], the chimes of [[Big Ben]] punctuating the days headlines and the signature theme tune; ''The Awakening'' by [[Johnny Pearson]].\n\nThroughout the early years, ITN established programmes in the ITV schedule including ''First Report'' at lunchtime, ''News at 5.45'' in the evening and the flagship ''News at Ten''. Today, ''ITV News'' on weekdays broadcasts the ''[[ITV Lunchtime News]]'' at 1.30pm, the ''[[ITV Evening News]]'' at 6.30pm and ''[[ITV News at Ten]]'' with bulletins broadcast at various times on weekends. ITN has at times interrupted the ITV schedule to provide updates on major breaking stories of national and international importance including the [[September 11 attacks]], [[7 July 2005 London bombings|London bombings, 2005]] or events involving the [[British Royal Family]]. ITN has covered every general election since 1955 for ITV, providing comprehensive coverage of the counts throughout election night and has also broadcast special programmes covering the [[UK budget]] speech given by the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]].\n\nITN's history is inextricably linked to that of ITV as prior to the [[Broadcasting Act 1990]] each of the ITV companies owned a share. In the 1990s, under new ownership, it was accused of abandoning its previous news style, which was broadsheet in style to mid-market tabloid with news stories that focused on personalities in the news rather than heavy news coverage leading to accusations of [[dumbing down]] its coverage.\n\nITN's most famous news programme, ''[[ITV News at Ten|News at Ten]]'' was also controversially replaced by an 11pm news bulletin in 1999, said to be in order to allow ITV to broadcast films without the interruption of a 10 o'clock news bulletin. ''News at Ten'' was subsequently re-instated in 2001 after heavy public criticism over the change. The restored programme was 10 minutes shorter than its predecessor and carried less in-depth news coverage. It was also broadcast at a later time at least one day a week, which meant it was often jokingly referred to as ''News at When?'' There was increasing speculation that the ''News at Ten'' would again be moved, after under-performing against the ''Ten O'Clock News'' on [[BBC One]] which broadcasts every day at 10:00pm. In October 2003, the [[Independent Television Commission]] gave ITV approval to move ''News at Ten''.\n\nThe ''[[ITV News at 10.30]]'' launched on ITV on 2 February 2004 (the day that ITV in England, Wales and Southern Scotland came under the ownership of a single [[ITV plc|company]]) and was presented by Sir [[Trevor McDonald]]. The programme was longer than its predecessor and carried an integrated regional bulletin, as well as more business stories, a nightly sports update and a preview of the following day's newspapers. [[Mark Austin (journalist)|Mark Austin]] took over main presenting duties on 16 January 2006.\n\nThe rebranded programme again saw new titles, this time featuring people walking over the face of Big Ben and has lately followed a more \"sensationalist\" approach to its main headlines. When ITV executive chairman [[Michael Grade]] joined ITV, he made it clear that he saw news as the key in defining any channel. On 14 January 2008, the ''News at Ten'' returned, presented by [[Julie Etchingham]] and McDonald returned to his duties again. [[Mark Austin (journalist)|Mark Austin]] joined Etchingham as co-presenter in 2009. As of October 2015, [[Tom Bradby]] has been the main presenter on the programme.\n\n''[[ITV News at 6.30]]'' has, since it was launched in 1999, been the network's most popular bulletin. Its presenters include [[Mary Nightingale]], [[Ranvir Singh]] and [[Charlene White]].\n\nIn March 2004, ITN took over production of [[ITV London]]'s regional news programmes, which relocated from [[The London Television Centre]] on the [[South Bank]] to ITN's [[Gray's Inn Road]] base.\n\n===Channel 4 News===\n{{Main|Channel 4 News}}\n\nITN is home to [[Channel 4 News]], having produced the programme since the channel's inception in 1982.\n\nThe Channel 4 News flagship programme is 55 minutes of in-depth news and current affairs broadcast at 7pm each weekday and at 6.30pm on Saturdays and Sundays. The weekday evening programme is anchored by [[Jon Snow (journalist)|Jon Snow]], whereas [[Krishnan Guru-Murthy]] presents the weekend bulletins.\n\nA five-minute-long news summary goes out Monday to Friday at midday. The bulletin replaced Channel 4's 30-minute ''News at Noon'' programme in late 2009, six years after its launch during the Iraq War of 2003.\n\nITN created ''[[More4 News]]'' when the digital channel [[More4]] was launched in October 2005. It ran at 8pm, immediately after Channel 4 News. It was originally presented by [[Sarah Smith (news reporter)|Sarah Smith]]; [[Kylie Morris]] took over presenting duties in June 2007 and Smith was posted to the US as Channel 4 News' Washington correspondent. In December 2009 Channel 4 cancelled ''More4 News''.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Deans|first=Jason|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/aug/05/channel-4-news-at-noon-more4-news-cuts|title=Channel 4 to axe News at Noon and More4 News|date=2009-08-05|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-20|last2=Sweney|first2=Mark|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===5 News===\n{{Main|5 News}}From the launch of [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] in 1997, ITN provided the news bulletins for [[5 News]]. However, in January 2005, ITN lost the contract, which was awarded to [[Sky News]]. In 2011 ITN regained the contract in a three-year deal to provide news for Channel 5 from early 2012, but on a much reduced budget. The deal followed an agreement by Sky and [[Northern & Shell]], the then-owner of Channel 5, to terminate the 5 News contract early.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Foster|first=Patrick|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/nov/03/itn-channel-5-news|title=ITN to regain Channel 5 news deal|date=2011-11-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===International===\nITN began its own ''[[ITN World News|World News]]'' bulletins in the late 1980s, which were shown around the world on local television channels, particularly on [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] stations in the [[United States|US]], where presenter [[Daljit Dhaliwal]] (now with [[Al-Jazeera English]]) enjoyed cult status.\n\nThese were discontinued in 2001, in the face of competition from dedicated news channels such as [[BBC World]] (now known as [[BBC World News]]), although it still provides footage to [[CNN International]] and reports often appear on ''[[PBS NewsHour]]''. Its ''ITV Evening News'' bulletin was shown on the [[Newsworld International]] cable channel in the US.\n\n===Other ventures===\nITN launched its 24-hour news channel in 2000, which was jointly bought by the main ITV companies [[Carlton Television|Carlton]] and [[Granada Television|Granada]] in 2002 and rebranded as the [[ITV News Channel]]. It was closed down in 2005.\n\n[[Setanta Sports News]] was a 24-hour sports news television channel produced by ITN and jointly owned by [[Living TV Group|Virgin Media Television]] and [[Setanta Sports]], launched on 29 November 2007. The channel ceased broadcasting on 23 June 2009, when Setanta's UK operation were placed into administration following financial difficulties.\n\nITN Consulting was the management consultancy arm of ITN, combining the resources of ITN with the consulting team's experience to advise global media companies on issues spanning all areas of strategy and operations, including financial planning, marketing, scheduling and content, recruitment, and interim management. With partner, Venture Consulting, it had offices in London, Milan, Dubai, Singapore and Sydney. It operated as a network with its consultants working on engagements globally and focused \"on how strategy can be implemented to deliver to real change\". ITN Consulting stated that \"an understanding of how global, regional and local media markets conflict and come together enables them to identify the opportunities this creates\". They took an external, outsider perspective as well as having the viewpoint of senior \"insider\" media executives. ITN Consulting was extensively involved in the development of business plans for local TV in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|title=ITN Consulting: Local TV|url=http://www.itnconsulting.co.uk/local-tv.html|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926003620/http://www.itnconsulting.co.uk/local-tv.html|archive-date=26 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It also consulted a range of national broadcasters on improving performance. The unit closed in 2012.\n\n===ITN Source===\n{{Update|section|date=April 2020}}ITN Source (formerly ITN Archive) licenses video footage from ITN's one million hours of archive content including news, drama, celebrity, comedy, music, wildlife, natural history and film. It also syndicates on-the-day news footage generated by ITN to other broadcasters and producers worldwide. The company represents the moving image libraries of [[Reuters]], ITV (including [[ITV Studios]]), [[Asian News International|ANI]], [[UTV Media|UTV]], [[Fox News]], [[Fox Movietone]], [[Gaumont British]], [[Nine Network]] and other specialist collections. Its headquarters are in London and it has sales offices in New York, Toronto, Paris, Johannesburg, Sydney and Tokyo.\n\nIn 2005, ITN became a shareholder in Espresso Group, a provider of digital content to more than 60% of primary schools in the UK and also internationally. Espresso services feature an extensive library of broadband teaching resources and student activities to motivate pupils and support teachers, including content from ITN Source. In May 2008, the Education Clip Library, a unique, video licensing service for educational publishers and broadcasters around the world, was launched. It is aimed at educational publishers and broadcasters seeking to add video to their instructional products and services. Espresso was acquired by Discovery Education (part of Discovery Communications) on 7 November 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Steel|first=Emily|url=https://www.ft.com/content/85bd8020-4736-11e3-b4d3-00144feabdc0|title=Discovery invests in digital learning with Espresso deal|date=7 November 2013|work=Financial Times|access-date=20 April 2020|url-status=live|issn=0307-1766}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2008, ITN founded digital production company [[Diagonal View]] as a joint venture together with digital entrepreneur Matt Heiman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techradar.com/uk/news/television/internet/odd-tv-clips-to-hit-youtube-and-myspace-479499|title=Odd TV clips to hit YouTube and MySpace|last=Goss|first=Patrick|date=27 October 2008|website=TechRadar|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> The company packages footage from the ITN archive and syndicates it to a range of commercial partners including [[MySpace]], [[YouTube]] and [[MSN]]. In March 2017, the company was sold to Sky, who paid \u00a32.6m for ITN's stake.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skymedia.co.uk/news/sky-acquires-leading-digital-content-producer-diagonal-view/|title=Sky acquires leading digital content producer Diagonal View - news from Sky Media|last=|first=|date=31 March 2017|website=Sky Media|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/itn-reports-increased-broadcast-news-revenues-of-88-9m-for-2018/|title=ITN reports increased broadcast news revenues of \u00a388.9m for 2018|last=Tobitt|first=Charlotte|date=2019-04-18|website=Press Gazette|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===ITN Productions===\n{{unreferenced section|date = August 2010}}\nITN Productions was formed in February 2010 and incorporates the non-news operations of ITN, including the former ITN On, ITN Factual and ITN Corporate divisions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wheeler steps down as ITN On MD following divisions merger |author=Jennifer Whitehead |newspaper=New Media Age |date=25 February 2010 |url=http://www.nma.co.uk/news/wheeler-steps-down-as-itn-on-md-following-divisions-merger/3010419.article |access-date=21 March 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929165958/http://www.nma.co.uk/news/wheeler-steps-down-as-itn-on-md-following-divisions-merger/3010419.article |archive-date=29 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nITN was one of the first companies to provide news content for 3G mobile phones, when it struck a deal to provide daily news bulletins for the 3 network in 2003.\n\nIt has since expanded its video news service providing news, sport and showbiz content to a wide range of broadcasters, newspapers and websites.\n\nShowbiz bulletins from ITN are broadcast daily on a number of television channels, including [[FYI Daily]] on [[ITV2]], [[ITV3]] and [[ITV4]], The Fix on [[4Music]] and Access on [[5Star]]. A daily showbiz breakfast show, ''The Breakfast Fix'', is broadcast on 4Music.\n\nFrom August 2013, ITN Productions was awarded the contract to produce the Premier League online and mobile highlights service for [[News UK]]. Content appears on ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' and ''[[The Times]]'' subscription websites and mobile apps.\n\nDigital content is supplied to sports news video agency SNTV.\n\nITN Productions also creates factual programming for ITV, Channel 4 and Channel 5 as well as international broadcasters, including [[Discovery Channel]], [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]], [[PBS NewsHour|PBS]] and [[National Geographic Channel]].\n\nITN has produced shows for Sky, with one of its later programmes being ''[[Harrow: A Very British School]]''.\n\nITN also supplied programming to the now-closed [[Teachers TV]] service.\n\n== Corporate affairs ==\n\n=== Headquarters and studios ===\nITN has been based at 200 [[Gray's Inn Road]] since 1991. The purpose-built headquarters were designed by architect [[Norman Foster, Baron Foster of Thames Bank|Sir Norman Foster]], and officially opened by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] on 8 May 1991.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/video/queen-opens-new-itn-hq-r08059101-1-itn-in-house-edit-of-news-footage/1154094958|title=Queen opens new ITN HQ|last=|first=|date=8 May 1991|website=Getty Images|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/thames-eyes-on-itn-the-franchise-loser-is-ready-to-step-in-if-carltons-offer-fails-writes-jason-1496215.html|title=Thames' eyes on ITN: The franchise loser is ready to step in if Carlton's offer fails|last=Nisse|first=Jason|date=1993-03-07|website=The Independent|language=en-gb|issn=0951-9467|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nPrior to redevelopment, the site was the location of [[The Times]] and [[The Sunday Times]] offices, which moved to [[Wapping]] in 1986.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rusbridger|first=Alan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/jan/27/wapping-news-international-1986|title=The anguish of swapping to Wapping|date=28 January 1986|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-21|url-status=live|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== Leadership ===\nThe Chief Executive of ITN is Anna Mallett, who joined the company in April 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itn.co.uk/about-us/senior-leadership-team/|title=Senior Leadership Team|last=|first=|date=2019-11-28|website=ITN|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.deloitte.co.uk/mediatelecomsbeyond/bio/anna-mallett.html|title=Media and Telecoms 2020 & Beyond conference|last=|first=|date=|website=Deloitte|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>  She was previously the Group Chief Operating Officer and MD, Production at [[BBC Studios]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tobitt|first=Charlotte|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/itn-announces-bbc-studios-boss-anna-mallett-as-new-chief-executive-replacing-john-hardie/|title=ITN announces BBC Studios boss Anna Mallett as new chief executive replacing John Hardie|date=20 December 2018|work=Press Gazette|access-date=20 April 2020|url-status=live|issn=0041-5170}}</ref>\n\n===Ownership===\n{{unreferenced section | date = August 2010}}\nThe current shareholders of ITN are:<ref>{{cite web |title=ITN announces new Chair |url=https://www.itn.co.uk/press-releases/itn-announces-new-chair/ |publisher=ITN |accessdate=20 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n* [[ITV plc]] (40%)\n* [[Daily Mail and General Trust]] (20%)\n* [[Thomson Reuters]] (20%)\n* [[Informa]] (20%)\n\nUpon its inception, ITN was jointly owned by all the ITV operating companies, with shareholdings split roughly in proportion to each company's advertising income. However the [[Broadcasting Act 1990]] allowed the ITC to set ownership rules. It was decided to limit the ITV companies to a maximum joint 49% stake, with no single company allowed more than a 20% holding. The powers were abolished by the [[Communications Act 2003]].\n\nITV plc's shareholding forms part of the wider ITV News Group which incorporates the regional operations in England, Southern Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland and the Channel Islands. The Director of the ITV News Group is Michael Jermey, a former editor and executive at ITN.\n\nITV's ownership of 40% of ITN (at that time equally split between Carlton and Granada) made the 2001 bid from Sky for ITV bulletins unlikely to succeed, the network having a vested interest to see ITN continue. The ITN contract for ITV News expires at the end of 2012.{{Update after|2020|4|20}} On 2 April 2007 ITN signed a deal which superseded the existing contract, worth at least \u00a342m per year, and invested more than \u00a315m to upgrade ITN's newsroom as part of the deal.\n\n==Parodies==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=June 2009}}\nITN has been spoofed several times on ITV's ''[[The Benny Hill Show]]'', namely in one 1971 show with the logo reading \"NIT\" instead of \"ITN\" and with Hill as [[Reginald Bosanquet|Reginald \"Boozenquet]]\" and [[Andrew Gardner (newsreader)|Andrew Gardner]].\n\nITN was also spoofed in a sketch in 1978 with Benny Hill as Angela O'Rippon, a parody of [[Angela Rippon]], and as Ann Afford, a parody of [[Anna Ford]]. It was also spoofed in a black and white 1971 show and a 1973 episode.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of ITV journalists and newsreaders]]\n* [[Independent Radio News]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{ITV}}\n{{ITV News}}\n{{Channel Four Television Corporation}}\n{{Channel 5 Broadcasting}}\n\n{{Daily Mail and General Trust}}\n{{Thomson Reuters}}\n{{Media in the United Kingdom|comporg}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Itn}}\n[[Category:ITN| ]]\n[[Category:Television news in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Television production companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies based in London]]\n[[Category:Media companies based in London]]\n[[Category:1955 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:International Emmy Awards Current Affairs & News winners]]\n[[Category:Daily Mail and General Trust]]\n[[Category:ITV]]\n[[Category:Thomson Reuters]]\n[[Category:Informa]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British-based news and content provider}}\n{{About|the news provider in the United Kingdom|the channel in Sri Lanka|Independent Television Network|the news programme on ITV produced by the company|ITV News|other uses|ITN (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Independent Television News\n| logo = ITN logo.svg\n| logo_size = 150px\n| image = File:Holborn, ITN Building, 200 Gray's Inn Road, WC1 - geograph.org.uk - 667814.jpg\n| image_size = 230px \n| image_caption = Headquarters at 200 [[Gray's Inn Road]]\n| type = [[Private company limited by shares]]\n| genre = [[News broadcasting]]\n| hq_location = 200 [[Gray's Inn Road]]\n| hq_location_city = [[London]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United Kingdom]]\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1955|05|4|df=yes|p=y|br=y}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Independent Television News Limited |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/00548648 |publisher=[[Companies House]] |accessdate=20 April 2020 |ref=companies-house |language=en}}</ref>\n| founder = [[Independent Television Authority]]\n| key_people = Anna Mallett ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])\n| num_employees = 712<ref name=\"annual-report-2018\">{{cite book |title=ITN Annual Report 2018 |url=https://www.itn.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/ITN-Annual-Report-2018-Digital.pdf |accessdate=20 April 2020 |ref=annual-report-2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n| num_employees_year = 2018\n| revenue = {{Increase}} {{GBP|126.9 million|long=no|link=yes}}<ref name=\"annual-report-2018\" />\n| revenue_year = 2018\n| operating_income = {{Decrease}} {{GBP|1.3 million|long=no|link=yes}}<ref name=\"annual-report-2018\" />\n| income_year = 2018\n| net_income = {{Decrease}} {{GBP|1.2 million|long=no|link=yes}}<ref name=\"annual-report-2018\" />\n| net_income_year = 2018\n| assets = {{Increase}} {{GBP|6.4 million|long=no|link=yes}}<ref name=\"annual-report-2018\" />\n| assets_year = 2018\n| equity = {{Increase}} {{GBP|91.2 million|long=no|link=yes}}<ref name=\"annual-report-2018\" />\n| equity_year = 2018\n| owners = {{ubl|[[ITV plc]] (40%)|[[Daily Mail and General Trust|DMGT]] (20%)|[[Thomson Reuters]] (20%)|[[Informa]] (20%)}}\n| divisions = {{ubl|Broadcast News|ITN Productions}}\n| homepage = {{URL|itn.co.uk}}\n}}\n\n'''Independent Television News''' ('''ITN''') is a UK-based television production company. It is made up of two divisions: Broadcast News and ITN Productions. ITN is based in [[London]], with bureaux and offices in [[Beijing]], [[Brussels]], [[Jerusalem]], [[Johannesburg]], [[New York City|New York]], [[Paris]], [[Sydney]] and [[Washington, D.C.|Washington DC]].\n\nITN produces the daily news programmes for ITV, Channel 4 and Channel 5 in the UK, and in recent years has diversified to produce a wide range of content including documentaries, sports, advertising and digital material for a range of international clients.\n\nBetween 1955 and 1999, ITN was more commonly known as the general brand name of ITV's news programmes. Since 8 March 1999, ITV has used ''[[ITV News]]'' as the brand name for its news programmes, though ITN continues as the network's news provider.\n\n==History==\nITN was founded in May 1955 by a consortium of the initial four [[Independent Television Authority|Independent Television]] (later ITV) broadcasting companies, with former [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP [[Aidan Crawley]] as editor-in-chief. One of those companies, the London weekday contract-holder [[Associated-Rediffusion]] offered the new company studio space in its headquarters in [[Aldwych]], London. The first bulletin was broadcast at 10pm on 22 September 1955 on ITV's launch night. The bulletin was presented by former champion athlete [[Christopher Chataway]]. From the start, ITN broke new ground by introducing in-vision and named 'newscasters' (rather than the BBC's nameless and sound-only 'newsreaders'), and reporter packages. The unique, probing reporting style of [[Robin Day]] caused shock among politicians, finding themselves questioned continually for information \u2013 this had never been the case with the [[BBC]]. There was also some early tensions with the ITV companies. [[Associated British Corporation|ABC Television]], the ITV contractor for the north and Midlands on weekends, immediately called for shorter ITN bulletins. While the [[Independent Television Authority|ITA]] ruled on a minimum of a 20-minute bulletin, disagreements with the ITV companies over ITN's budget triggered the resignation of its news editor [[Aidan Crawley]] after just one year in 1956. He was replaced by [[Geoffrey Cox (journalist)|Geoffrey Cox]].<ref name=\"cultures\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vbLlAAAAQBAJ|title=Itv Cultures: Independent Television Over Fifty Years: Independent Television Over Fifty Years|first1=Johnson|last1=Catherine|first2=Turnock|last2=Rob|date=1 September 2005|publisher=McGraw-Hill Education (UK)|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the early years, ITN continued to develop its service to the ITV network with an agenda to firstly, fulfil its public service broadcasting requirements and secondly satisfy the ITV companies by attracting viewers. Under this method, ITN continued to differentiate itself from the BBC by conducting probing interviews, introducing more human interest stories and bringing ordinary people on to screen by using so-called 'vox pops' (interviews, usually held in the street, with members of the general public), all of which were seen as a radical departure at the time in British broadcasting.<ref name=\"cultures\"/> As the ITN reporter and later ITN political editor [[Julian Haviland]], put it: \"My view was that at ITN we must be at least as responsible and accurate as the BBC, without being so damned boring\".<ref>{{cite book|title=And Finally... The History of ITN|first=Richard|last=Lindley|publisher=[[Methuen Publishing|Politico's Publishing]]|location=London|year=2005|isbn=9781842750674}}</ref> As ITV expanded, each ITV company that made up the network's federal structure had to purchase a stake in ITN and to continue to finance the company.\n\nIn 1967, ITN was given the go-ahead by the ITA to provide a full 30-minute daily news programme at 10pm on ITV. There was further tension with the ITV executives as they were sceptical of the idea that viewers would want a full 30 minutes of news every Monday to Friday and they were also losing valuable peak time slots which could be used for the sale of commercial advertising. ''[[ITV News at Ten|News at Ten]]'' began broadcasting on 3 July 1967 with a newscaster team consisting of [[Alastair Burnet]], [[Andrew Gardner (newsreader)|Andrew Gardner]], [[George Ffitch]] and [[Reginald Bosanquet]]. It was initially given a 13-week trial run, however, the programme proved to be extremely popular with viewers and continued for a further 32 years. ''News at Ten'' was to become one of the most prestigious news programmes of its time in British history with a reputation for high-quality journalism and innovation.<ref name=\"cultures\"/> ITN's ''News at Ten'' also prompted the BBC to gradually expand it's 20:50 news bulletin from ten minutes to fifteen, twenty and then twenty-five minutes. ''[[BBC Nine O'Clock News|The Nine O'Clock News]]'' began broadcasting in 1970 as ''News at Ten's'' rival. ITN also established other programmes in the ITV schedule. ''First Report'', a lunchtime bulletin began in 1972 and by 1976, ''News at 5.45'' commenced. This was a period when ITN enjoyed its greatest plaudits, following [[Lord Annan]]'s 1977 report on the future of broadcasting, which declared: \"We subscribe to the generally held view that ITN has the edge over BBC news.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hayward|first=Anthony|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jul/20/sir-alastair-burnet|title=Sir Alastair Burnet obituary|date=2012-07-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nITN obtained the contract to produce ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' when the channel started broadcasting in 1982. The programme was launched by [[Peter Sissons]], [[Trevor McDonald]] and [[Sarah Hogg]]. The hour-long programme has been broadcast at 7pm since it started and has a reputation for high-quality journalism and thorough analysis. Further expansion came with the launch of [[Night Network|overnight television on ITV]] in 1988, with ITN providing hourly news bulletins, as well as the half-hour [[ITV News at 5:30|''ITN Morning News'']] to conclude the overnight schedules.\n\nUntil the 1990s, the individual ITV companies had an obligation to provide a national news programme, which required them to take a share in the ITN operation. Following the [[Broadcasting Act 1990]], ITN had to apply and bid for a licence to provide such services on these ITV network, and would have to fight competition in order to preserve its services, as had become the case with other ITV franchisees. The Broadcasting Act also allowed the Independent Television Commission to introduce ownership rules for news providers. The move was to transform the company from a 'cost centre' to a 'profit-making business'. The move saw 400 staff made redundant, and the closure of a number of international bureaux to claw back a \u00a310 million deficit in order to provide a competitive product to obtain the ITV news contract. Within three years the company turned to profit in 1993 with suggestions at the time that the company should be listed on the stock exchange.<ref name=\"cultures\"/>\n\nThe company launched ''[[5 News]]'' in 1997 following the foundation of [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]].\n\nThe 1990s saw major changes to the television landscape in Britain. The growth of multichannel television saw ITV's share of audience fall. Against this backdrop ITV itself became increasingly commercially aggressive. This was to be a major turning point in ITN's history which saw a reduction in the ITV news contract. By this period the main ITV companies [[Granada PLC|Granada]] and [[Carlton Communications|Carlton]] had also viewed unfavourably the scheduling of ''News at Ten'' which became a subject of dispute between ITN and the ITV companies. ITN favoured keeping the bulletin, however, the ITV companies claimed audiences were lost at 10pm as the news interrupted films and drama programming. ''News at Ten'' eventually ended in March 1999 with ITN's flagship bulletin moved to 6.30pm with a shorter late night bulletin at 11pm. Consolidation of the ITV network under a unified ITV brand also saw the removal of the on-screen ITN brand which was replaced with ''[[ITV News]]''.<ref name=\"cultures\"/> From this point, the ITN brand was gradually phased out and it is now only referenced to in the end production caption.\n\nIn 1997, ITN started producing the [[Royal Christmas Message]] every other year.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Plunkett|first=John|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jan/19/queen-christmas-message-sky-news|title=Queen's Christmas message to be produced by Sky for first time|date=2011-01-19|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nThe early years of the 21st century was to prove to be a challenging period. The axing of ''News at Ten'' caused public outcry and ITN's viewership figures fell by 13.9%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=onN_BAAAQBAJ|title=No News is Bad News: Radio, Television and the Public|first=Michael|last=Bromley|date=11 September 2014|publisher=Routledge|via=Google Books}}</ref> Political pressure and pressure from the media resulted in ITV bringing back a shorter 20 minute bulletin at 10pm three nights a week. The programme eventually lost share to the [[BBC News at Ten]] (which launched in 2000 to capitalise on ITV's move) and ITV eventually axed the programme again in 2004 and moved the bulletin to 10.30pm before bringing it back to 10pm again in 2008. The biggest challenge came in 2001 when [[British Sky Broadcasting]] bid to supply network news to ITV as part of a consortium. ITN eventually succeeded and was awarded a contract extension to 2008. In January 2005 Sky News took over supplying bulletins to [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]; ITN had produced ''[[5 News]]'' since its launch in 1997 and the contract was returned in February 2012, following a change of ownership at Channel 5.\n\nIn August 2000, ITN launched its own 24-hour news channel in the UK, broadcast on satellite, cable and digital terrestrial. It was 50% owned by ITN and 50% owned by [[Virgin Media|NTL]]. [[Carlton Communications|Carlton]] and [[Granada PLC|Granada]] gradually bought out the two stakes and renamed the channel the [[ITV News Channel]]. It closed down on 23 December 2005. Poor ratings in comparison to [[BBC News (TV channel)|BBC News 24]] and Sky News, and ITV's desire to re-use the channel's allocation on [[Freeview (UK)|Freeview]], were cited as the reasons.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Conlan|first=Tara|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/dec/14/tvnews.itv|title=ITV News Channel axed|date=2005-12-14|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2004 following its acquisition of the [[London News Network]], a company previously owned by the now merged [[Carlton Communications|Carlton]] and [[Granada PLC|Granada]], ITN began producing local news bulletins for the [[ITV London]] region. ITN produced [[More4 News]] between 2005 and 2009. In 2007 it began producing [[Setanta Sports News]]; however it closed in 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/setanta-uk-goes-into-administration-1.842268|title=Setanta UK goes into administration|last=|first=|date=23 June 2009|website=The Irish Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1996 and 2002, it also owned a share of [[London News Radio]], which was based at ITN's Gray's Inn Road headquarters and operated the [[LBC]] and [[LBC News 1152|News Direct London]] radio stations. ITN used to operate a radio news service on behalf of [[Independent Radio News]] (IRN) but on 15 October 2008, IRN announced that [[Sky News Radio]] was to replace ITN as its main supplier from March 2009.\n\nWhile news production remains the cornerstone of ITN's business model, the company has diversified from its original remit. ITN Source (originally ITN Archive) is one of the world's largest sources of historical film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itnsource.com/en/|title=The world's leading provider of archive footage|publisher=}}</ref> ITN Productions creates multi-platform content for major global brands, covering genres such as factual, entertainment, news and corporate production. Clients that commission award-winning programmes from ITN Productions include major UK and international broadcasters such as ITV, the BBC, Channel 4, Channel 5, History and Discovery, with television commissions including Climbing Great Buildings on BBC2 and Mud Men on History.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nativityfactor.com/Nativity/About|title=The Nativity Factor \u2013 About|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nJohn Hardie is the chief executive officer of ITN, a position he took up in June 2009. Prior to this, he was executive VP and MD of Walt Disney Television EMEA.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sweney|first=Mark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/mar/17/itn-disney-john-hardie-chief-executive|title=ITN appoints senior Disney executive John Hardie as chief executive|date=2009-03-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 2018 it was announced that John Hardie was to leave ITN, and be replaced in 2019 by Anna Mallett, who was previously Group Chief Operating Officer and MD, Production at BBC Studios.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tobitt|first=Charlotte|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/itn-announces-bbc-studios-boss-anna-mallett-as-new-chief-executive-replacing-john-hardie/|title=ITN announces BBC Studios boss Anna Mallett as new chief executive replacing John Hardie|date=20 December 2018|work=Press Gazette|access-date=20 April 2020|url-status=live|issn=0041-5170}}</ref>\n\n===Studios at ITN===\n\nAs of July 2019 there are currently three main operational television studios based at ITN headquarters in 200 Grays Inn Road, London.\n\nStudios 1 and 2 are around 2,500 Sq Ft each in size with Studio 6 slightly smaller at around 2,000 Sq Ft.\n\n'''Studio 1'''\n\nStudio 1 is currently the home to all ITV national news bulletins as well as all local news bulletins made by ITN for ITV News London. The studio has also been used for ITV's general election night coverage since the 2005 general election.\n\n'''Studio 2'''\n\nStudio 2 is currently the home to 5 News, made by ITN for Channel 5.  The studio is also used every weekday morning for the Channel 5 Jeremy Vine Show.\n\n'''Studio 6'''\n\nStudio 6 is currently the home to Channel 4 News, produced by ITN for Channel 4, and has occupied this studio since it opened in 1999.\n\nThere were previous studios located in the building, however in recent years they have been decommissioned and are no longer available, with most being converted back into office space.<ref>http://www.tvstudiohistory.co.uk/studio%20history.htm#wells%20st</ref>\n\nThe atrium of ITN headquarters has been utilised by ITN for the 1997 and 2001 general election night coverage, where the atrium itself was converted into a huge studio for their general election night coverage for those two elections. The atrium view was also used by ITV News for their 2005 general election, this time superimposed into their virtual green screen news studio.  The look proved popular, that it was added to all ITV national news bulletins from January 2006 until February 2009.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n==Operations==\n[[File:ITN OB Van.jpg|thumb|250px|An ITN satellite van]]\n\n===ITN produced programmes schedule===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Programme !! Channel !! Days !! Start time !! End time !! Presenters\n|-\n| ''[[ITV Lunchtime News]]'' || rowspan=4|[[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]], [[STV (TV channel)|STV]], [[UTV (TV channel)|UTV]] || Weekdays || 13:28 || 13:50 || [[Nina Hossain]]\n|-\n| ''[[ITV Evening News]]'' || Weekdays || 18:30 || 18:54 || [[Mary Nightingale]]\n|-\n| ''[[ITV News at Ten|News at Ten]]'' || Weekdays || 22:00 || 22:30 || [[Tom Bradby]] or [[Julie Etchingham]]\n|-\n| ''[[ITV Weekend News|ITV News]]'' || Weekends ||colspan=2|Various || Various\n|-\n| ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' || rowspan=3|[[Channel 4]] || Weekdays || 19:00 || 19:55 || rowspan=3|[[Jon Snow (journalist)|Jon Snow]],<br/>[[Krishnan Guru-Murthy]],<br/>[[Matt Frei]],<br/>[[Cathy Newman]]\n|-\n| ''Channel 4 News'' || Weekends || colspan=2|Various\n|-\n| ''Channel 4 News Summary'' || Weekdays || 12:00 || 12:05\n|-\n| ''[[5 News]]'' || rowspan=7|[[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] || Weekdays || 20:58 || 21:00|| Various\n|-\n| ''5 News at 5'' || Weekdays || 17:00 || 17:30  || [[Sian Williams]]\n|-\n| ''5 News Tonight'' || Weekdays || 18:30 || 19:00 || [[Claudia-Liza Armah]]\n|-\n| ''5 News at Lunchtime'' || Weekdays || 12:10 || 12:15 || Various\n|-\n| ''5 News Weekend'' || Weekends ||colspan=2|Various || Various\n|-\n| ''5 News at 19:55'' || Weekdays || 19:55 || 20:00|| Various\n|-\n| ''5 News at 20:58'' || Weekdays || 20:58 || 21:00|| Various\n|}\n\n===ITV News===\n{{main|ITV News}}\n\n====ITN/ITV News====\n{{More citations needed section|date = February 2012}}\nITN has produced all national news bulletins on ITV since the network was launched on 22 September 1955. Originally the ITN logo and brand featured prominently on all news bulletins on ITV, however, since March 1999, bulletins have been branded as ''[[ITV News]]''. Trademarks of ''ITV News'' include the use of the clock-face of the [[Elizabeth Tower]] of [[Westminster Palace]], the chimes of [[Big Ben]] punctuating the days headlines and the signature theme tune; ''The Awakening'' by [[Johnny Pearson]].\n\nThroughout the early years, ITN established programmes in the ITV schedule including ''First Report'' at lunchtime, ''News at 5.45'' in the evening and the flagship ''News at Ten''. Today, ''ITV News'' on weekdays broadcasts the ''[[ITV Lunchtime News]]'' at 1.30pm, the ''[[ITV Evening News]]'' at 6.30pm and ''[[ITV News at Ten]]'' with bulletins broadcast at various times on weekends. ITN has at times interrupted the ITV schedule to provide updates on major breaking stories of national and international importance including the [[September 11 attacks]], [[7 July 2005 London bombings|London bombings, 2005]] or events involving the [[British Royal Family]]. ITN has covered every general election since 1955 for ITV, providing comprehensive coverage of the counts throughout election night and has also broadcast special programmes covering the [[UK budget]] speech given by the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]].\n\nITN's history is inextricably linked to that of ITV as prior to the [[Broadcasting Act 1990]] each of the ITV companies owned a share. In the 1990s, under new ownership, it was accused of abandoning its previous news style, which was broadsheet in style to mid-market tabloid with news stories that focused on personalities in the news rather than heavy news coverage leading to accusations of [[dumbing down]] its coverage.\n\nITN's most famous news programme, ''[[ITV News at Ten|News at Ten]]'' was also controversially replaced by an 11pm news bulletin in 1999, said to be in order to allow ITV to broadcast films without the interruption of a 10 o'clock news bulletin. ''News at Ten'' was subsequently re-instated in 2001 after heavy public criticism over the change. The restored programme was 10 minutes shorter than its predecessor and carried less in-depth news coverage. It was also broadcast at a later time at least one day a week, which meant it was often jokingly referred to as ''News at When?'' There was increasing speculation that the ''News at Ten'' would again be moved, after under-performing against the ''Ten O'Clock News'' on [[BBC One]] which broadcasts every day at 10:00pm. In October 2003, the [[Independent Television Commission]] gave ITV approval to move ''News at Ten''.\n\nThe ''[[ITV News at 10.30]]'' launched on ITV on 2 February 2004 (the day that ITV in England, Wales and Southern Scotland came under the ownership of a single [[ITV plc|company]]) and was presented by Sir [[Trevor McDonald]]. The programme was longer than its predecessor and carried an integrated regional bulletin, as well as more business stories, a nightly sports update and a preview of the following day's newspapers. [[Mark Austin (journalist)|Mark Austin]] took over main presenting duties on 16 January 2006.\n\nThe rebranded programme again saw new titles, this time featuring people walking over the face of Big Ben and has lately followed a more \"sensationalist\" approach to its main headlines. When ITV executive chairman [[Michael Grade]] joined ITV, he made it clear that he saw news as the key in defining any channel. On 14 January 2008, the ''News at Ten'' returned, presented by [[Julie Etchingham]] and McDonald returned to his duties again. [[Mark Austin (journalist)|Mark Austin]] joined Etchingham as co-presenter in 2009. As of October 2015, [[Tom Bradby]] has been the main presenter on the programme.\n\n''[[ITV News at 6.30]]'' has, since it was launched in 1999, been the network's most popular bulletin. Its presenters include [[Mary Nightingale]], [[Ranvir Singh]] and [[Charlene White]].\n\nIn March 2004, ITN took over production of [[ITV London]]'s regional news programmes, which relocated from [[The London Television Centre]] on the [[South Bank]] to ITN's [[Gray's Inn Road]] base.\n\n===Channel 4===\n{{Main|Channel 4 News}}\n\n====Channel 4 News====\n\nITN is home to [[Channel 4 News]], having produced the programme since the channel's inception in 1982.\n\nThe Channel 4 News flagship programme is 55 minutes of in-depth news and current affairs broadcast at 7pm each weekday and at 6.30pm on Saturdays and Sundays. The weekday evening programme is anchored by [[Jon Snow (journalist)|Jon Snow]], whereas [[Krishnan Guru-Murthy]] presents the weekend bulletins.\n\nA five-minute-long news summary goes out Monday to Friday at midday. The bulletin replaced Channel 4's 30-minute ''News at Noon'' programme in late 2009, six years after its launch during the Iraq War of 2003.\n\nITN created ''[[More4 News]]'' when the digital channel [[More4]] was launched in October 2005. It ran at 8pm, immediately after Channel 4 News. It was originally presented by [[Sarah Smith (news reporter)|Sarah Smith]]; [[Kylie Morris]] took over presenting duties in June 2007 and Smith was posted to the US as Channel 4 News' Washington correspondent. In December 2009 Channel 4 cancelled ''More4 News''.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Deans|first=Jason|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/aug/05/channel-4-news-at-noon-more4-news-cuts|title=Channel 4 to axe News at Noon and More4 News|date=2009-08-05|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-20|last2=Sweney|first2=Mark|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Channel 5===\n{{Main|5 News}}\n\n====5 News====\nFrom the launch of [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] in 1997, ITN provided the news bulletins for [[5 News]]. However, in January 2005, ITN lost the contract, which was awarded to [[Sky News]]. In 2011 ITN regained the contract in a three-year deal to provide news for Channel 5 from early 2012, but on a much reduced budget. The deal followed an agreement by Sky and [[Northern & Shell]], the then-owner of Channel 5, to terminate the 5 News contract early.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Foster|first=Patrick|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/nov/03/itn-channel-5-news|title=ITN to regain Channel 5 news deal|date=2011-11-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===International===\nITN began its own ''[[ITN World News|World News]]'' bulletins in the late 1980s, which were shown around the world on local television channels, particularly on [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] stations in the [[United States|US]], where presenter [[Daljit Dhaliwal]] (now with [[Al-Jazeera English]]) enjoyed cult status.\n\nThese were discontinued in 2001, in the face of competition from dedicated news channels such as [[BBC World]] (now known as [[BBC World News]]), although it still provides footage to [[CNN International]] and reports often appear on ''[[PBS NewsHour]]''. Its ''ITV Evening News'' bulletin was shown on the [[Newsworld International]] cable channel in the US.\n\n===Other ventures===\nITN launched its 24-hour news channel in 2000, which was jointly bought by the main ITV companies [[Carlton Television|Carlton]] and [[Granada Television|Granada]] in 2002 and rebranded as the [[ITV News Channel]]. It was closed down in 2005.\n\n[[Setanta Sports News]] was a 24-hour sports news television channel produced by ITN and jointly owned by [[Living TV Group|Virgin Media Television]] and [[Setanta Sports]], launched on 29 November 2007. The channel ceased broadcasting on 23 June 2009, when Setanta's UK operation were placed into administration following financial difficulties.\n\nITN Consulting was the management consultancy arm of ITN, combining the resources of ITN with the consulting team's experience to advise global media companies on issues spanning all areas of strategy and operations, including financial planning, marketing, scheduling and content, recruitment, and interim management. With partner, Venture Consulting, it had offices in London, Milan, Dubai, Singapore and Sydney. It operated as a network with its consultants working on engagements globally and focused \"on how strategy can be implemented to deliver to real change\". ITN Consulting stated that \"an understanding of how global, regional and local media markets conflict and come together enables them to identify the opportunities this creates\". They took an external, outsider perspective as well as having the viewpoint of senior \"insider\" media executives. ITN Consulting was extensively involved in the development of business plans for local TV in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|title=ITN Consulting: Local TV|url=http://www.itnconsulting.co.uk/local-tv.html|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926003620/http://www.itnconsulting.co.uk/local-tv.html|archive-date=26 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It also consulted a range of national broadcasters on improving performance. The unit closed in 2012.\n\n===ITN Source===\n{{Update|section|date=April 2020}}ITN Source (formerly ITN Archive) licenses video footage from ITN's one million hours of archive content including news, drama, celebrity, comedy, music, wildlife, natural history and film. It also syndicates on-the-day news footage generated by ITN to other broadcasters and producers worldwide. The company represents the moving image libraries of [[Reuters]], ITV (including [[ITV Studios]]), [[Asian News International|ANI]], [[UTV Media|UTV]], [[Fox News]], [[Fox Movietone]], [[Gaumont British]], [[Nine Network]] and other specialist collections. Its headquarters are in London and it has sales offices in New York, Toronto, Paris, Johannesburg, Sydney and Tokyo.\n\nIn 2005, ITN became a shareholder in Espresso Group, a provider of digital content to more than 60% of primary schools in the UK and also internationally. Espresso services feature an extensive library of broadband teaching resources and student activities to motivate pupils and support teachers, including content from ITN Source. In May 2008, the Education Clip Library, a unique, video licensing service for educational publishers and broadcasters around the world, was launched. It is aimed at educational publishers and broadcasters seeking to add video to their instructional products and services. Espresso was acquired by Discovery Education (part of Discovery Communications) on 7 November 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Steel|first=Emily|url=https://www.ft.com/content/85bd8020-4736-11e3-b4d3-00144feabdc0|title=Discovery invests in digital learning with Espresso deal|date=7 November 2013|work=Financial Times|access-date=20 April 2020|url-status=live|issn=0307-1766}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2008, ITN Source announced the creation of Diagonal View,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techradar.com/uk/news/television/internet/odd-tv-clips-to-hit-youtube-and-myspace-479499|title=Odd TV clips to hit YouTube and MySpace|last=Goss|first=Patrick|date=27 October 2008|website=TechRadar|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> a joint venture with Matt Heiman, a digital entrepreneur. The company packages content from ITN Source's archive and syndicates it to a range of commercial partners including [[MySpace]], [[YouTube]] and [[MSN]].\n\n===ITN Productions===\n{{unreferenced section|date = August 2010}}\nITN Productions was formed in February 2010 and incorporates the non-news operations of ITN, including the former ITN On, ITN Factual and ITN Corporate divisions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wheeler steps down as ITN On MD following divisions merger |author=Jennifer Whitehead |newspaper=New Media Age |date=25 February 2010 |url=http://www.nma.co.uk/news/wheeler-steps-down-as-itn-on-md-following-divisions-merger/3010419.article |access-date=21 March 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929165958/http://www.nma.co.uk/news/wheeler-steps-down-as-itn-on-md-following-divisions-merger/3010419.article |archive-date=29 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nITN was one of the first companies to provide news content for 3G mobile phones, when it struck a deal to provide daily news bulletins for the 3 network in 2003.\n\nIt has since expanded its video news service providing news, sport and showbiz content to a wide range of broadcasters, newspapers and websites.\n\nShowbiz bulletins from ITN are broadcast daily on a number of television channels, including [[FYI Daily]] on [[ITV2]], [[ITV3]] and [[ITV4]], The Fix on [[4Music]] and Access on [[5Star]]. A daily showbiz breakfast show, ''The Breakfast Fix'', is broadcast on 4Music.\n\nFrom August 2013, ITN Productions was awarded the contract to produce the Premier League online and mobile highlights service for [[News UK]]. Content appears on ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' and ''[[The Times]]'' subscription websites and mobile apps.\n\nDigital content is supplied to sports news video agency SNTV.\n\nITN Productions also creates factual programming for ITV, Channel 4 and Channel 5 as well as international broadcasters, including [[Discovery Channel]], [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]], [[PBS NewsHour|PBS]] and [[National Geographic Channel]].\n\nITN has produced shows for Sky, with one of its later programmes being ''[[Harrow: A Very British School]]''.\n\nITN also supplied programming to the now-closed [[Teachers TV]] service.\n\n==Ownership==\n{{unreferenced section | date = August 2010}}\nFrom its inception in 1955, ITN was originally jointly owned by all the ITV operating companies, the shares split roughly in proportion to each company's advertising income. However the [[Broadcasting Act 1990]] allowed the ITC to set ownership rules. It was decided to limit the ITV companies to a maximum joint 49% stake, with no single company allowed more than a 20% holding. The powers were abolished by the [[Communications Act 2003]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Owner\n! Shares<ref>{{cite web |title=ITN announces new Chair |url=https://www.itn.co.uk/press-releases/itn-announces-new-chair/ |publisher=ITN |accessdate=20 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[ITV plc]]\n| 40%\n|-\n| [[Daily Mail and General Trust]]\n| 20%\n|-\n| [[Thomson Reuters]]\n| 20%\n|-\n| [[Informa]]\n| 20%\n|}\n\nITV plc's shareholding forms part of the wider ITV News Group which incorporates the regional operations in England, Southern Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland and the Channel Islands. The Director of the ITV News Group is Michael Jermey, a former editor and executive at ITN.\n\nITV's ownership of 40% of ITN (at that time equally split between Carlton and Granada) made the 2001 bid from Sky for ITV bulletins unlikely to succeed, the network having a vested interest to see ITN continue. The ITN contract for ITV News expires at the end of 2012.{{Update after|2020|4|20}} On 2 April 2007 ITN signed a deal which superseded the existing contract, worth at least \u00a342m per year, and invested more than \u00a315m to upgrade ITN's newsroom as part of the deal.\n\n==Parodies==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=June 2009}}\nITN has been spoofed several times on ITV's ''[[The Benny Hill Show]]'', namely in one 1971 show with the logo reading \"NIT\" instead of \"ITN\" and with Hill as [[Reginald Bosanquet|Reginald \"Boozenquet]]\" and [[Andrew Gardner (newsreader)|Andrew Gardner]].\n\nITN was also spoofed in a sketch in 1978 with Benny Hill as Angela O'Rippon, a parody of [[Angela Rippon]], and as Ann Afford, a parody of [[Anna Ford]]. It was also spoofed in a black and white 1971 show and a 1973 episode.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of ITV journalists and newsreaders]]\n* [[Independent Radio News]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{ITV}}\n{{ITV News}}\n{{Channel Four Television Corporation}}\n{{Channel 5 Broadcasting}}\n\n{{Daily Mail and General Trust}}\n{{Thomson Reuters}}\n{{Media in the United Kingdom|comporg}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Itn}}\n[[Category:ITN| ]]\n[[Category:Television news in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Television production companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies based in London]]\n[[Category:Media companies based in London]]\n[[Category:1955 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:International Emmy Awards Current Affairs & News winners]]\n[[Category:Daily Mail and General Trust]]\n[[Category:ITV]]\n[[Category:Thomson Reuters]]\n[[Category:Informa]]\n", "name_user": "Salsareans", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(Remove table of broadcast timesWP:NOTTVGUIDE)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ITN"}
{"title_page": "Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II", "text_new": "{{short description|60th anniversary of the accession of Queen Elizabeth II}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:Spirit of Chartwell.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Left to right, atop barge: (grouped at left) the [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Duke of Edinburgh]]; the [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|Duke of Cambridge]]; the [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|Duchess of Cambridge]]; [[Prince Harry]]; [[Queen Elizabeth II]]; (grouped at right) the [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|Duchess of Cornwall]]; the [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince of Wales]], aboard the [[MV Spirit of Chartwell|MV ''Spirit of Chartwell'']] during the Thames Diamond Jubilee Pageant on 3 June 2012]]\n\nThe year 2012 marked the '''Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II''' being the 60th anniversary of the accession of [[Queen Elizabeth II]] on 6 February 1952. The only [[Diamond jubilee|Diamond Jubilee]] celebration for any of Elizabeth's predecessors was in 1897, for the 60th anniversary of the 1837 accession of [[Queen Victoria#Diamond Jubilee|Queen Victoria]].\n\nFollowing the tradition of the Queen's [[Silver Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Silver]] and [[Golden Jubilee of Queen Elizabeth II|Golden Jubilees]], commemorative events were held throughout the [[Commonwealth of Nations]]. \n\nThe Queen and the [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Duke of Edinburgh]] toured the United Kingdom and other members of the Royal Family toured the rest of the Commonwealth as the monarch' representatives. The jubilee celebrations marked the beginning of the withdrawal of the Duke of Edinburgh from public life and a more prominent role for the Duke of Cambridge and Prince Harry in commonwealth affairs.\n\nNumerous events and tributes were held over the year and throughout the Commonwealth, culminating in a jubilee pageant held in London. The Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust was set up as a charitable foundation with a mission to leave a lasting legacy across the Commonwealth. <ref>{{cite web |title=Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust |url=https://www.jubileetribute.org/ |website=Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust}}</ref> Other projects included the [[Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Wood]] and the issuing of [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal|commemorative medals]].\n\n==Commonwealth-wide and beyond==\n{{Quote box| width=250px| border=1px| align=right| quote=In this special year, as I dedicate myself anew to your service, I hope we will all be reminded of the power of togetherness and the convening strength of family, friendship, and good neighbourliness, examples of which I have been fortunate to see throughout my reign and which my family and I look forward to seeing in many forms as we travel throughout the United Kingdom and the wider Commonwealth.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2012/TheQueensDiamondJubileemessage.aspx| last=Royal Household| title=The Queen's Diamond Jubilee message| date=6 February 2012| publisher=[[Queen's Printer]]| accessdate=8 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211124329/http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2012/TheQueensDiamondJubileemessage.aspx| archivedate=11 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>| salign=right| source=Elizabeth II, 2012}}\n\nAt the [[Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting 2011|2011 Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting]] in [[Perth]], Australia, [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British Prime Minister]] [[David Cameron]] announced the creation of the Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust, which was officially launched in the UK on 6 February 2012.<ref name=TF>{{cite press release|title=The Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust |publisher=Australian Government Publishing Service |date=7 February 2012 |url=http://www.pm.gov.au/press-office/queen-elizabeth-diamond-jubilee-trust |accessdate=11 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606234311/http://www.pm.gov.au/press-office/queen-elizabeth-diamond-jubilee-trust |archivedate=6 June 2012  }}</ref> Chaired by former British prime minister Sir [[John Major]], the trust was intended to support charitable organisations and projects across the [[Commonwealth of Nations]], focusing on areas such as cures for diseases and the promotion of all types of culture and education.<ref name=TF /> In early 2012, [[Prime Minister of Australia]] [[Julia Gillard]] announced the [[Monarchy of Australia|Australian Crown]]-[[Queen-in-Council|in-Council]] would make an A$5.4 million contribution to the trust and the [[Monarchy of New Zealand|New Zealand Crown]]-in-Council later made a similar $1 million donation.<ref name=TF /><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.msn.co.nz/nationalnews/8422619/nz-to-give-1m-to-diamond-jubilee| title=NZ to give $1m to Diamond Jubilee| date=20 February 2012| publisher=MSN NZ| accessdate=20 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525161812/http://news.msn.co.nz/nationalnews/8422619/nz-to-give-1m-to-diamond-jubilee| archivedate=25 May 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Canadian government announced in April that former prime minister [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]] would be Canada's representative to the organisation.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20120430/chretien-represents-canada-on-queens-jubilee-trust-120430/| title=Charles, Camilla to visit Canada in May; Chretien named envoy| date=30 April 2012| publisher=CTV| accessdate=30 April 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501101543/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20120430/chretien-represents-canada-on-queens-jubilee-trust-120430/| archivedate=1 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, a senior advisor was quoted as saying the Queen set two guidelines for the planning of her jubilee: the use of public funds should be minimised and people should not \"be forced to celebrate\".<ref name=GlobePomp>{{citation| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/queens-diamond-jubilee-poised-to-outdo-royal-weddings-pomp/article2327411/| last=Renzetti| first=Elizabeth| title=Queen's Diamond Jubilee poised to outdo Royal Wedding\u2019s pomp| date=5 February 2012| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| accessdate=6 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206094040/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/queens-diamond-jubilee-poised-to-outdo-royal-weddings-pomp/article2327411/| archivedate=6 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The first major international event of the jubilee celebrations was the [[Diamond Jubilee Pageant]], also branded ''The World Comes to Windsor'', a cavalcade held at [[Windsor Castle]] to celebrate the Queen's visits to and tours of over 250 countries, as well as her passion for horses. The show, which featured 550 horses and 1,100 performers from around the world, was performed in the evenings between 10 and 13 May, after the daytime events of the annual [[Royal Windsor Horse Show]] had taken place. The Queen attended the final night.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-berkshire-15544379| title=Windsor reveals 'spectacular' plans for Diamond Jubilee| date=1 November 2011| publisher=BBC| accessdate=21 April 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425125244/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-berkshire-15544379| archivedate=25 April 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/queen-elizabeth-II/8862164/Queens-Diamond-Jubilee-500-horses-from-around-the-world-will-put-on-equine-display-in-Windsor.html| last=Rayner| first=Gordon| title=Queen's Diamond Jubilee: 500 horses from around the world will put on equine display in Windsor| date=2 November 2011| newspaper=The Telegraph| accessdate=21 April 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603065328/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/queen-elizabeth-II/8862164/Queens-Diamond-Jubilee-500-horses-from-around-the-world-will-put-on-equine-display-in-Windsor.html| archivedate=3 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5i-Rx6x-d9E5b1l7UR2TN_m6u1N7Q?docId=N0092271333454487401A| title=Boyle to sing for Queen's pageant| date=3 April 2012| publisher=The Press Association| accessdate=21 April 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May, the Queen hosted an informal lunch at Windsor Castle for more than twenty current or former monarchs from other countries.<ref>{{citation| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9275284/The-Queen-welcomes-monarchs-to-Diamond-Jubilee-lunch.html| title=The Queen welcomes monarchs to Diamond Jubilee lunch| newspaper=The Telegraph| date=18 May 2012| accessdate=22 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120521103855/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9275284/The-Queen-welcomes-monarchs-to-Diamond-Jubilee-lunch.html| archivedate=21 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9274691/Jubilee-monarchs-lunch-the-full-guest-list.html| title=Jubilee monarchs' lunch: the full guest list| date=18 May 2012| newspaper=The Telegraph| accessdate=22 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523022345/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9274691/Jubilee-monarchs-lunch-the-full-guest-list.html| archivedate=23 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the evening of the same day, the [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince of Wales]] and the [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|Duchess of Cornwall]] hosted a dinner that most of the monarchs also attended, although the Queen herself was not present.<ref name=Donnely>{{citation| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/9277117/A-feast-fit-for-Kings-and-Queens-hosted-by-a-Prince.html| last=Donnely| first=Laura| title=A feast fit for Kings and Queens, hosted by a Prince| newspaper=The Telegraph| date=18 May 2012| accessdate=22 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522002727/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/9277117/A-feast-fit-for-Kings-and-Queens-hosted-by-a-Prince.html| archivedate=22 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Criticism was directed at the presence of the [[Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifa|King of Bahrain]] at the lunch, because of alleged repression of [[Bahraini uprising (2011\u2013present)|protests against the government of Bahrain]] in that country in 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18099937| title=Queen's lunch for monarchs attracts controversy| date=18 May 2012| publisher=BBC| accessdate=23 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522060516/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18099937| archivedate=22 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> In London, protesters against the King assembled outside Buckingham Palace during the dinner, although he did not attend that event.<ref name=Donnely />\n\n[[File:Queen at the Diamond Jubilee.JPG|thumb|left|[[Queen Elizabeth II]] arriving at [[St Paul's Cathedral]] for the service of thanksgiving on 5 June 2012]]\nThe lighting of thousands of beacons across the Commonwealth took place on 4 June. The number of beacons was originally set at 2,012; by the closing date for registrations, approximately 4,000 had been submitted in the United Kingdom alone.<ref name=DMBeacons>{{citation| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2138239/Red-fires-night-Royal-delight-Queen-use-huge-crystal-trigger-4-000-beacons-lit-celebrate-Diamond-Jubilee.html| last=Vinter| first=Phil| title=Red fires at night, Royal delight: Queen to use huge crystal to trigger last of 4,000 beacons lit to celebrate Diamond Jubilee| date=2 May 2012| newspaper=Daily Mail| accessdate=9 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130114023552/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2138239/Red-fires-night-Royal-delight-Queen-use-huge-crystal-trigger-4-000-beacons-lit-celebrate-Diamond-Jubilee.html| archivedate=14 January 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The first beacon of the Jubilee was lit on the grounds of Apifo'ou College in [[Nuku\u02bbalofa]], Tonga, by Tongan [[World Association of Girl Guides and Girl Scouts|girl]] and [[Boy Scout]]s using coconut sheath torches.<ref name=matangi>{{cite news| title=Tonga's guides and scouts light first Diamond Jubilee beacon| url=http://matangitonga.to/2012/06/05/tongas-guides-and-scouts-light-first-diamond-jubilee-beacon| work=[[Matangi Tonga]]| date=4 June 2012| accessdate=5 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120607221840/http://matangitonga.to/2012/06/05/tongas-guides-and-scouts-light-first-diamond-jubilee-beacon| archivedate=7 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Other nations, including [[Kenya]], [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[India]], [[Seychelles]], [[Sri Lanka]], and several [[Caribbean]] states, took part in the beacon lighting. The world's most remote beacon was lit in [[Tristan da Cunha]] in the south Atlantic, using [[Invasive species|invasive, non-native plant]]s to fuel the fire.<ref name=birdwatch>{{cite news| title=Burning aliens for the Queen| url=http://www.birdwatch.co.uk/channel/newsitem.asp?c=11&cate=__12179| date=4 June 2012| publisher=Birdwatch| accessdate=5 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608114110/http://www.birdwatch.co.uk/channel/newsitem.asp?c=11&cate=__12179| archivedate=8 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=tpa>{{cite news| title=Remote islanders join Jubilee party| url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5jCSPlwfBEZNFt7f4p0iodwYCRe7A?docId=N0060401338688550812A| date=4 June 2012| publisher=Press Association| accessdate=5 June 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, British servicemen and women wounded in battle and individuals representing charities carried beacons to the summits of the UK's four highest peaks. One beacon was lit at [[Treetops Hotel]] in [[Aberdare National Park]] in Kenya, where the Queen was at the moment of her accession to the throne.<ref name=DMBeacons /> The Queen lit the beacon outside [[Buckingham Palace]] at 10:30 pm,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diamondjubileebeacons.co.uk/pages/lighting_times_173419.cfm |title=The Queen's Diamond Jubilee Beacons > Beacon Lighting Times |publisher=[[Queen's Printer]] |accessdate=9 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507050246/http://www.diamondjubileebeacons.co.uk/pages/lighting_times_173419.cfm |archivedate=7 May 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.canada.com/news/Wounded+soldiers+carry+beacons+Queen+diamond+jubilee/6073863/story.html| last=Agence France Presse| title=Wounded soldiers to carry beacons for Queen's diamond jubilee| date=30 January 2012| publisher=canada.com| accessdate=9 May 2012}}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=SheriffIsInTown |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> by inserting a large, specially made, diamond-cut crystal into a receptacle.<ref name=DMBeacons /> The lighting proceeded until the final beacon was lit in Canada eight hours later.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.canada.com/news/Diamond+Jubilee+will+globe+alight/6559106/story.html| last=Rainey| first=Sarah| title=Diamond Jubilee will set the globe alight| date=3 May 2012| publisher=canada.com| accessdate=28 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617155449/http://www.canada.com/news/Diamond+Jubilee+will+globe+alight/6559106/story.html| archivedate=17 June 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Queen's husband, [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]], was hospitalised with a [[Urinary tract infection|bladder infection]] on 4 June and thus was not able to attend any of the official events. In his speech given at the conclusion of the Diamond Jubilee Concert, the Prince of Wales commented on the sadness of his father's absence and urged the crowd to cheer loud enough for the Duke to hear in hospital.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9311477/The-Queens-Diamond-Jubilee-Concert-Loudest-cheer-for-the-Duke-of-Edinburgh.html| last=Bowater| first=Donna| title=The Queen's Diamond Jubilee Concert: Loudest cheer for the Duke of Edinburgh| date=5 June 2012| newspaper=Daily Telegraph| accessdate=24 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620033457/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9311477/The-Queens-Diamond-Jubilee-Concert-Loudest-cheer-for-the-Duke-of-Edinburgh.html| archivedate=20 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]], stated after visiting his father that the latter was watching the celebrations on television.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18331680| title=Prince Philip 'feeling better'| date=5 June 2012| publisher=BBC| accessdate=24 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617041902/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18331680| archivedate=17 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Queen visited the Duke the following day.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18342301| title=Queen visits Prince Philip in hospital| date=6 June 2012| publisher=BBC| accessdate=24 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120618003110/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18342301| archivedate=18 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThat same evening, a pre-recorded message by the Queen was released and aired on television around the world.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18333624| title=Diamond jubilee: Queen \"humbled by experience\"| date=5 June 2012| publisher=BBC| accessdate=24 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617195123/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18333624| archivedate=17 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Commonwealth realms==\n\n===Australia===\n[[Quentin Bryce]], the [[Governor-General of Australia]], announced that the Diamond Jubilee would be celebrated \"with a host of national and community events throughout the Commonwealth.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gg.gov.au/announcement.php/view/id/50/title/queens-birthday-message |last=Office of the Governor General of Australia |authorlink=Governor General of Australia |title=Queen's Birthday Message |publisher=Australian Government Publishing Service|accessdate=15 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314025232/http://www.gg.gov.au/announcement.php/view/id/50/title/queens-birthday-message |archivedate=14 March 2012 }}</ref> In a similar vein, it was said in late 2011 that the government of [[Queensland]] was planning to declare a holiday in June 2012 to mark the jubilee.\n\nThe [[Royal Australian Mint]] announced in August 2011 that it would be releasing a silver proof 50-cent coin to celebrate the Queen's Diamond Jubilee.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ramint.gov.au/media/noticeboard/2011/downloads/20110907a_checklist.pdf| last=Royal Australian Mint| authorlink=Royal Australian Mint| title=2012 Product Launch for the Royal Australian Mint| publisher=Royal Australian Mint| accessdate=18 September 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124145655/http://www.ramint.gov.au/media/noticeboard/2011/downloads/20110907a_checklist.pdf| archivedate=24 November 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Australia Post issued a series of special stamps to mark the occasion.\n\nPaying tribute to Elizabeth II as [[Queen of Australia]] in the [[Australian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] on 6 February 2012, [[Prime Minister of Australia]] [[Julia Gillard]] stated the Queen was a revered figure in Australia.<ref>Hansard, Australian Parliament, 6 February 2012</ref> Gillard also announced that she would on 4 June light a beacon atop [[Parliament House, Canberra|Parliament House]] and that a street in the parliamentary triangle in [[Canberra]] would be renamed ''Queen Elizabeth Terrace''.<ref name=TF /> Meanwhile, [[Premier of Western Australia|Western Australian Premier]] [[Colin Barnett]] announced on 28 May that a new waterfront development in [[Perth]] would be named [[Elizabeth Quay]] in the Queen's honour.\n\nA detachment of the [[New South Wales Police Force|New South Wales Mounted Police]] performed at the [[Diamond Jubilee Pageant]] held at Windsor Castle in May 2012. At the end of the same month, Prince Charles presented Diamond Jubilee medals to those in the [[Victoria Cross and George Cross Association]], including three Australian Victoria Cross recipients.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2152488/Charles-Camilla-meet-28-living-VCs-GCs-ahead-Diamond-Jubilee.html| publisher=Associated Newspapers Ltd| last=Hardman| first=Robert| title=Charles and Camilla meet 28 living VCs and GCs ahead of Diamond Jubilee| date=31 May 2012| newspaper=Daily Mail| accessdate=7 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20120601164915/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2152488/Charles-Camilla-meet-28-living-VCs-GCs-ahead-Diamond-Jubilee.html| archivedate=1 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA special [[Ecumenism|ecumenical]] service was conducted in [[St James' Church, Sydney]], at which the invited preacher was Cardinal [[George Pell]] and the [[Governor of New South Wales]], [[Marie Bashir]], was the guest of honour. The [[Anglican Church of Australia]] also held a service of prayer and thanksgiving to commemorate the Diamond Jubilee at [[St John's Cathedral (Brisbane)|St John's Cathedral]] in Brisbane, on 20 May 2012. The service was welcomed by [[Phillip Aspinall]], Anglican Archbishop of Brisbane, and the Homily was given by [[Mark Coleridge]], Catholic Archbishop of Brisbane. The guest of honour was the [[Governor of Queensland]], [[Penelope Wensley]], and [[Ian Walker (politician)|Ian Walker]] represented the Queensland Cabinet.\n\nBetween 5 and 10 November 2012, [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], and [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]], toured the country, travelling to Queensland, Victoria, South Australia, New South Wales, and the Australian Capital Territory.<ref>{{citation| last=Viellaris| first=Renee| url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/bligh-shakes-up-public-holidays/story-e6freoof-1226186716689| title=Bligh shakes up public holidays, gifts Queenslanders another day off| date=6 November 2011| newspaper=The Courier-Mail| accessdate=6 November 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420135604/http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/bligh-shakes-up-public-holidays/story-e6freoof-1226186716689| archivedate=20 April 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=BBCJplans>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16174233| title=Royal Family plans for Queen's Diamond Jubilee unveiled| date=14 December 2011| publisher=BBC| accessdate=14 December 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111214181456/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16174233| archivedate=14 December 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.thediamondjubilee.org/commonwealth-visits-2012.htm| title=Commonwealth Visits in 2012| publisher=Royal Household| date=6 June 2012| accessdate=6 June 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref><ref name=TelegraphPoW>{{citation| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/prince-charles/9552611/Prince-of-Wales-and-Duchess-of-Cornwall-to-make-Australian-visit.html| title=Prince of Wales and Duchess of Cornwall to make Australian visit| date=19 September 2012| newspaper=The Telegraph| accessdate=21 September 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921114200/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/prince-charles/9552611/Prince-of-Wales-and-Duchess-of-Cornwall-to-make-Australian-visit.html| archivedate=21 September 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Bahamas===\n[[Prince Harry]] toured The Bahamas. There, he attended a reception for youth leaders and met with [[Governor-General of the Bahamas]] Sir [[Arthur Foulkes]]. The Prince attended an outdoor ceremony where children's schools, clubs, and associations presented themselves and delivered a speech at [[Government House, The Bahamas|Government House]],<ref>{{citation| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/prince-harry/9125017/Prince-Harry-praises-Bahamas-schoolchildren-on-Jubilee-tour.html| title=Prince Harry praises Bahamas schoolchildren on Jubilee tour| date=5 March 2012| newspaper=The Telegraph| accessdate=6 March 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306043400/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/prince-harry/9125017/Prince-Harry-praises-Bahamas-schoolchildren-on-Jubilee-tour.html| archivedate=6 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> where he stated \"I stand before you with a deep sense of pride at being asked to convey to you a message of good wishes from The Queen on the occasion of her Diamond Jubilee.\" He also took part in maritime exercises organised by the [[Royal Bahamas Defence Force]] and toured [[Harbour Island, Bahamas|Harbour Island]].<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2110094/Prince-Harrys-Diamond-Jubilee-tour-Harry-meets-Miss-Bahamas-day-beauty-queen-declared-marry-him.html| last=English| first=Rebecca| title=When Harry met Miss Bahamas: Couple get acquainted a day after beauty queen declared she would marry the prince| date=6 March 2012| newspaper=Daily Mail| accessdate=6 March 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20120307095154/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2110094/Prince-Harrys-Diamond-Jubilee-tour-Harry-meets-Miss-Bahamas-day-beauty-queen-declared-marry-him.html| archivedate=7 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Barbados===\n[[File:National Heroes Square, Bridgetown.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Parliament of Barbados]], where the [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|Earl of Wessex]] read to a joint sitting of the legislature a message from [[Elizabeth II]], [[Monarchy of Barbados|Queen of Barbados]], on 23 February 2012, to mark the Queen's diamond jubilee]]\n\nTo mark Elizabeth II's 60 years as Barbados' monarch\u2014as Queen of the United Kingdom between 1952 and 1966 and as [[Monarchy of Barbados|Queen of Barbados]] thereafter\u2014the country hosted the Queen's youngest son and his wife, [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|the Earl]] and [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex|Countess of Wessex]], between 23 and 24 February 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7314| first=Sharon| last=Lynch| title=Royal Visit To Mark Queen\u2019s Diamond Jubilee| date=25 January 2012| newspaper=Barbados Government Information Service (BGIS)| accessdate=7 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129203218/http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7314| archivedate=29 January 2016| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The tour began with the Earl and Countess arriving, aboard [[RFA Fort Rosalie (A385)|RFA ''Fort Rosalie'']], at the [[Port of Bridgetown|Deep Water Harbour]] of Bridgetown,<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.trinidadexpress.com/news/Pomp_at_port__as_British__royals_roll_in-140821023.html| last=Neaves| first=Julien| title=Pomp at port as British royals roll in| date=29 February 2012| newspaper=Trinidad Express| accessdate=29 February 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302184853/http://www.trinidadexpress.com/news/Pomp_at_port__as_British__royals_roll_in-140821023.html| archive-date=2 March 2012| url-status=dead}}</ref> where Barbadian military personnel were given inspection.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.caribbean360.com/index.php/news/barbados_news/556952.html| title=Red carpet welcome for Royal Couple| date=24 February 2012| publisher=Caribbean360| accessdate=25 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302000703/http://www.caribbean360.com/index.php/news/barbados_news/556952.html| archivedate=2 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=23010| title=Barbados leg of Diamond Jubilee gets underway| date=24 February 2012| newspaper=[[The Barbados Advocate]]| accessdate=25 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202222244/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=23010| archivedate=2 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite video| people=Esther Byer-Suckoo| title=Barbadian Minister Esther Byer-Suckoo briefs Press on the Royal Visit| medium=Video| publisher=News Distribution Network| location=Bridgetown| date=21 February 2012| url=http://landing.newsinc.com/shared/video.html?freewheel=90640&sitesection=nationnewslocal&VID=23579300| accessdate=24 February 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150502134244/http://landing.newsinc.com/shared/video.html?freewheel=90640&sitesection=nationnewslocal&VID=23579300| archive-date=2 May 2015| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=22983| title=All systems go!... for whirlwind two-day official Royal visit| date=22 February 2012| newspaper=The Barbados Advocate| accessdate=24 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120721005646/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=22983| archivedate=21 July 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> To a joint sitting of the [[Parliament of Barbados]], the Earl read a written message from the Queen,<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/royal-sitting/| title=Royal Sitting| date=24 February 2012| newspaper=[[The Daily Nation (Barbados)|The Daily Nation]]| accessdate=25 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202230606/http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/royal-sitting/| archivedate=2 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> in which the monarch stated she has taken note of the level of development Barbados had achieved during its 45 years of independence and called the country a model small state for others around the world.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7553| last=Carrington| first=J.| title=Queen Elizabeth II Proud of Barbados' Achievements| date=24 February 2012| publisher=Barbados Government Information Service| accessdate=24 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506040523/http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7553| archivedate=6 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| title=Prince Edward praises island on progress| last=Parris| first=Dawne| url=http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/prince-edward-praises-island-on-progress/| date=24 February 2012| newspaper=[[The Daily Nation (Barbados)|The Daily Nation]]| accessdate=24 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227223233/http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/prince-edward-praises-island-on-progress/| archivedate=27 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Parliamentary officials responded with thanks to the Queen for her service to the country and Barbadians and invited her to the island to celebrate the 375th anniversary of the establishment of the Barbadian parliament in 2014.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7536| title=Barbados Grateful To Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II| first=Julie| last=Carrington| date=23 February 2012| publisher=Barbados Government Information Service| accessdate=24 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506040203/http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7536| archivedate=6 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| title=Queen invited for 375th milestone| last=Parris| first=Dawne| url=http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/queen-invited-for-375th-milestone/| date=24 February 2012| newspaper=[[The Daily Nation (Barbados)|The Daily Nation]]| accessdate=24 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228003010/http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/queen-invited-for-375th-milestone/| archivedate=28 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The visiting royal couple opened an exhibit at the [[University of the West Indies]], [[Cave Hill Campus]], and an official state dinner and reception was held at [[Government House, Barbados|Government House]] in the evening.<ref name=BarVisitSun>{{citation| url=http://www.bajansunonline.com/barbados-royal-visit-to-mark-queens-diamond-jubilee/| last=Lynch| first=Sharon| title=Barbados: Royal Visit To Mark Queen's Diamond Jubilee| date=27 January 2012| newspaper=Bajan Sun Online| accessdate=6 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120719162855/http://www.bajansunonline.com/barbados-royal-visit-to-mark-queens-diamond-jubilee/| archivedate=19 July 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://landing.newsinc.com/shared/video.html?freewheel=90640&sitesection=nationnewslocal&VID=23580671| title=VIDEO: The Earl and Countess of Wessex Prince Edward and his wife Sophie, visit Parliament and Cave Hill Campus| author=TRH| date=23 February 2012| publisher=[[The Daily Nation (Barbados)|The Daily Nation]]| accessdate=24 February 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150502121250/http://landing.newsinc.com/shared/video.html?freewheel=90640&sitesection=nationnewslocal&VID=23580671| archive-date=2 May 2015| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe following day, the Countess visited the Albert C. Graham Children's Development Centre at Ladymeade Gardens, while the Earl presented eight [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award|Duke of Edinburgh's Gold Award]]s to Barbadian youth at a dedication ceremony. Directly following, the couple travelled together to a ceremony to commemorate the Diamond Jubilee, where a plaque was unveiled at the [[Kensington Oval]] [[List of Test cricket grounds|cricket stadium]].<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7548| title=Royal Sitting| date=24 February 2012| newspaper=The Daily Nation| accessdate=25 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506040456/http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7548| archivedate=6 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=RV>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=23031| title=Royal Visit| date=25 February 2012| newspaper=The Barbados Advocate| accessdate=25 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202225514/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=23031| archivedate=2 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Other events included the Earl and Countess lunching with Prime Minister [[Freundel Stuart]] at his residence, [[Ilaro Court]], and touring several areas of Bridgetown that were added to [[UNESCO]]'s list of [[World Heritage Site]]s in 2011.<ref name=BarVisitSun /><ref name=RV />\n\nAs in other Commonwealth realms, a set of commemorative Diamond Jubilee stamps were released by the Barbados Postal Service.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://barbadospostal.com/home/3052.html| title=Barbados: Now Available: Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Commemorative Stamp Issue| publisher=Barbados Postal Service| accessdate=18 November 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20121118020955/http://barbadospostal.com/home/3052.html| archivedate=18 November 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> An [[ecumenical]] thanksgiving service was held at the St. Mary's Anglican Church in [[Bridgetown]] on 3 June and a beacon lighting at the [[Garrison Savannah]] the following day,<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=25108| title=Barbados gives thanks| date=4 June 2012| newspaper=The Barbados Advocate| accessdate=16 June 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130117153545/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=25108| archivedate=17 January 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=24890| title=Thanksgiving Service for Queen\u2019s Diamond Jubilee| date=24 May 2012| newspaper=The Barbados Advocate| accessdate=25 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120724192735/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=24890| archivedate=24 July 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=24902| title=Barbadians urged not miss Beacon Lighting Ceremony| date=24 May 2012| newspaper=The Barbados Advocate| accessdate=25 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120718134106/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=24902| archivedate=18 July 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> where an official [[Trooping of the Colour]] was performed by the [[Barbados Defence Force]] and [[military tattoo]] performed by the [[Royal Barbados Police Force]].<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=25129| title=Garrison Savannah a special place| date=5 June 2012| newspaper=The Barbados Advocate| accessdate=16 June 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130117135412/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=25129| archivedate=17 January 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Members of the Barbados Boys Scout Association with high honours were chosen to aid in the actual beacon lighting.<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=25128| title=Beacon lit for Queen\u2019s jubilee| date=6 June 2012| newspaper=The Barbados Advocate| accessdate=16 June 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130117165049/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=25128| archivedate=17 January 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Belize===\nIn Belize, the [[Governor-General of Belize|Governor-General]]-[[Queen-in-Council|in-Council]] and the Belize Tourism Board organised a tour of the country by [[Prince Harry]], between 2 and 3 March 2012, as part of the country's celebrations of Elizabeth II's 60th year as monarch of Belize, first as [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|Queen of the United Kingdom]] and then, after 1981, as [[Monarchy of Belize|Queen of Belize]]. Harry visited [[Belmopan]] and [[San Ignacio (town)|San Ignacio]] where ceremonies and events had less emphasis on state protocol.<ref name=Belizian>{{cite news| url=http://belizean.com/prince-harrys-belize-schedule-released-1046/| title=Prince Harry's Belize Schedule Released|date=17 February 2012| publisher=Belizian| accessdate=1 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref> In the capital, Harry unveiled a series of commemorative stamps issued by the Belize Postal Service,<ref name=BelStamps>{{citation| url=http://www.guardian.bz/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4378%3Acommemorative-stamps-for-elizabeths-60th-year-as-queen-&catid=40%3Apolitics&Itemid=90| last=Williams| first=Shane D.| title=Commemorative Stamps for Elizabeth's 60th Year as Queen| date=9 February 2012| newspaper=The Guardian| accessdate=11 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231002250/http://www.guardian.bz/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4378%3Acommemorative-stamps-for-elizabeths-60th-year-as-queen-&catid=40%3Apolitics&Itemid=90| archivedate=31 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> attended the city's street festival, and dedicated a street as ''Queen Elizabeth II Boulevard'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-17248431|title=Diamond Jubilee: Prince Harry visits Mayan ruins in Belize|date=3 March 2012|publisher=BBC|accessdate=6 March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305214530/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-17248431|archivedate=5 March 2012}}</ref> where he delivered a speech on the sovereign's behalf.\n\n===Canada===\n[[File:Can-Diamond-Jubilee-logo.jpg|thumb|right|The official emblem of the [[Monarchy of Canada|Queen of Canada]]'s Diamond Jubilee]]\n====Planning====\nForethought on the anniversary began as early as April 2007, when then-Secretary of State for Canadian Heritage [[Jason Kenney]] requested the various [[Lieutenant Governor (Canada)|lieutenant governors]] begin preparations for the jubilee.<ref>{{Citation| last=Kenney| first=Jason| author-link=Jason Kenney| date=23 April 2007| contribution=Lieutenant Governors Meeting| editor-last=Department of Canadian Heritage| editor-link=Department of Canadian Heritage| title=Speeches > The Honourable Jason Kenney| place=Regina| publication-place=Ottawa| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pc-ch/minstr/arc_disc-spch/kenney/2007/20070423-eng.cfm| accessdate=29 November 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611163321/http://www.pch.gc.ca/pc-ch/minstr/arc_disc-spch/kenney/2007/20070423-eng.cfm| archivedate=11 June 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Three years later, the question of a national holiday to mark the jubilee was raised in the media and a series of official announcements were made by the Minister of Canadian Heritage.<ref>{{Cite news| publisher=CBC| date=6 January 2010| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/pointofview/2010/01/diamond-jubilee-should-we-get-a-national-holiday.html| title=Diamond Jubilee: should we get a national holiday?| accessdate=4 June 2010| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100811045757/http://www.cbc.ca/news/pointofview/2010/01/diamond-jubilee-should-we-get-a-national-holiday.html| archivedate=11 August 2010| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Canadian Secretary to the Queen|Secretary to the Queen]], [[Kevin S. MacLeod]], was charged by the [[Queen-in-Council|Governor General-in-Council]] to head the Diamond Jubilee Committee (DJC)\u2014a 14-member group of individuals drawn from the provincial and territorial governments, non-governmental organisations, officials from the Departments of [[Department of Citizenship and Immigration Canada|Citizenship and Immigration]], [[Department of National Defence (Canada)|National Defence]], and [[Department of Canadian Heritage|Canadian Heritage]] (DCH), and the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]<ref name=CBC$>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/01/09/pol-queen-diamond-jubilee.html?cmp=rss| last=The Canadian Press| title=Conservatives balked at cost of Queen's Diamond Jubilee| date=9 January 2012| publisher=CBC| accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref>\u2014that oversaw the organisation of the country's [[f\u00eate]]s for Elizabeth II's 60 years as [[Monarchy of Canada|Queen of Canada]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=PM announces the appointment of Kevin MacLeod as Canadian Secretary to the Queen |publisher=Office of the Prime Minister |date=1 April 2009 |url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=2501 |accessdate=29 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090405014141/http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=2501 |archivedate=5 April 2009  }}</ref> Similarly, [[Premier of Alberta]] [[Ed Stelmach]] in February 2011 tasked the Alberta Chief of Protocol and the Private Secretary to the [[Lieutenant Governor of Alberta]] to form and head a committee to develop plans for the province's Diamond Jubilee celebrations.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://alberta.ca/home/NewsFrame.cfm?ReleaseID=%2Facn%2F%2F201102%2F29852ED3E4C18-FF66-8F19-0627D5EAD11E39EE.html| last=Government of Alberta| title=Planning launches for Alberta's Diamond Jubilee celebrations| date=3 February 2011| publisher=Queen's Printer for Alberta| accessdate=29 January 2012}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> As with other royal events, the DCH played a large role in organisation and planning. $7.5 million of resources, granted to the DCH in the previous budget approved by the federal parliament, was allocated for federal jubilee celebrations, education and awareness, and distribution to community groups; $2 million was for events in the Queen's honour and $3.7 million was allocated for the Diamond Jubilee medal.<ref name=CBC$ /> The total amount was reduced by [[Minister of Canadian Heritage]] [[James Moore (Canadian politician)|James Moore]] from the DJC's original estimate of $8.8 million.<ref name=CBC$ />\n\n====Pre-events====\n[[File:Diamond Jubilee of Queen Elizabeth II - Canadian Senate Foyer (14579919150).jpg|thumb|left|The Diamond Jubilee Window in the Senate foyer in the [[Centre Block]] of Canada's parliament. It depicts Elizabeth II along with [[Queen Victoria]], who also celebrated a diamond jubilee.]]\nThe Queen, on 3 July 2010, dedicated the Queen Elizabeth II Gardens outside [[Government House (Manitoba)|her official residence in Manitoba]] and there planted an Amber Jubilee [[Physocarpus|Ninebark]] shrub, the [[cultivar]] having been created specifically for the Diamond Jubilee.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.royaltour.gc.ca/itiner/itiner-eng.cfm| last=Department of Canadian Heritage| authorlink=Department of Canadian Heritage| title=2010 Royal Tour > Itinerary for 2010 Royal Tour of Canada| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=9 August 2010| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619144300/http://royaltour.gc.ca/itiner/itiner-eng.cfm| archivedate=19 June 2010| df=dmy-all}}</ref> At [[Rideau Hall]] in Ottawa, she also, on 30 June, unveiled a commemorative [[stained glass]] window depicting herself and Queen Victoria with their respective [[royal cypher]]s and renditions of the [[Centre Block]] of the [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian parliament]] during the reign of each monarch.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/About/Senate/jubilee/crown-e.htm| last=Parliament of Canada| title=The Diamond Jubilee Window: A Celebration of the Crown in Canada| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=15 April 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312084326/http://www.parl.gc.ca/About/Senate/jubilee/crown-e.htm| archivedate=12 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last=Foot| first=Richard| title=Queen Elizabeth in Halifax| publisher=Global News| date=29 June 2010| url=http://news.globaltv.com/canada/Queen+Elizabeth+tour+Canada/3208763/story.html| accessdate=1 July 2010| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607195024/http://news.globaltv.com/canada/Queen+Elizabeth+tour+Canada/3208763/story.html| archivedate=7 June 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Foot |first=Richard |title=Queen Elizabeth to skip Quebec on Canadian tour |newspaper=Montreal Gazette |date=27 June 2010 |url=https://montrealgazette.com/Queen+skip+Quebec+Canadian+tour/3208778/story.html |accessdate=1 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100630162832/http://www.montrealgazette.com/Queen+skip+Quebec+Canadian+tour/3208778/story.html |archivedate=30 June 2010 }}</ref> The window, a gift from the [[Senate of Canada|Canadian Senate]], was installed above the Senate entrance to the Centre Block and dedicated by [[Governor General of Canada|Governor General]] [[David Johnston]] on 7 February 2012.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14416| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=Governor General to Attend the Dedication Ceremony of the Diamond Jubilee Window in Senate Foyer| date=6 February 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nA [[corbel]] within the Sovereigns' Arches of the [[Centre Block#Senate foyer|Senate foyer]] was sculpted into a rendition of the Queen and unveiled on 9 December 2010 by the Governor General.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=13980&lan=eng| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| authorlink=Governor General of Canada|title=Governor General to Unveil the Corbel of Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II| date=7 December 2010| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|accessdate=7 December 2010}}</ref> The [[Royal Canadian Mint]] also issued an \"extensive set\" of coins to mark the anniversary.<ref>{{Citation|last=Canadian Press|title=Canadian mint marking royal wedding with collector coins|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=2 March 2011|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/royalfamily/royalwedding/article/947234--canadian-mint-marking-royal-wedding-with-collector-coins|accessdate=8 March 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110305044234/http://www.thestar.com/news/world/royalfamily/royalwedding/article/947234--canadian-mint-marking-royal-wedding-with-collector-coins|archivedate=5 March 2011}}</ref> Further, the [[Royal Regiment of Canadian Artillery]] (RRCA) in 2011 presented the Queen, their captain-general since 1952, with a diamond and gold brooch, made by [[Birks & Mayors]] in the form of the regiment's cap badge, and announced the creation of The Captain General's Diamond Jubilee Bursary Award for educational activities of members of the RRCA and family.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/895213/her-majesty-the-queen-receives-a-brooch-produced-by-canadian-jeweller-birks-in-honour-of-her-diamond-jubilee-as-captain-general-of-the-royal-regiment-| title=Her Majesty the Queen Receives a Brooch Produced by Canadian Jeweller Birks in Honour of her Diamond Jubilee as Captain General of the Royal Regiment of Canadian Artillery| date=14 December 2011| publisher=Canada Newswire| accessdate=15 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614170610/http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/895213/her-majesty-the-queen-receives-a-brooch-produced-by-canadian-jeweller-birks-in-honour-of-her-diamond-jubilee-as-captain-general-of-the-royal-regiment-| archivedate=14 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Diamond Jubilee Week====\nDiamond Jubilee Week began on [[Accession Day]] (6 February) 2012.<ref name=CNW>{{Citation| title=Government of Canada Unveils Plans for Her Majesty's Diamond Jubilee Celebrations| agency=Office of the Prime Minister| date=6 December 2011| url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/890901/government-of-canada-unveils-plans-for-her-majesty-s-diamond-jubilee-celebrations| publisher=Canada Newswire| accessdate=8 December 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311062132/http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/890901/government-of-canada-unveils-plans-for-her-majesty-s-diamond-jubilee-celebrations| archivedate=11 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> That day, the [[Royal standards of Canada#Sovereign's standard|monarch's personal standard for Canada]] was unfurled at Rideau Hall and on [[Parliament Hill]], as well as at provincial [[Government Houses in Canada|royal residences]] and [[Legislative Assemblies of Canadian provinces and territories|legislatures across the country]];<ref>{{cite web| url=http://lt.gov.ns.ca/news-events/entry/diamond-jubilee-events/| last=Office of the Lieutenant Governor of Nova Scotia| title=Media > News and Events > Diamond Jubilee Events| date=23 January 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Nova Scotia| accessdate=16 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304003111/http://lt.gov.ns.ca/news-events/entry/diamond-jubilee-events/| archivedate=4 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.chrisd.ca/blog/50254/manitoba-queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee-celebrations/| archive-url=https://archive.today/20120731184335/http://www.chrisd.ca/blog/50254/manitoba-queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee-celebrations/| url-status=dead| archive-date=31 July 2012| title=Manitoba Celebrating Queen's Diamond Jubilee| date=6 February 2012| publisher=ChrisD| accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=PEI>{{cite web| url=http://www.gov.pe.ca/newsroom/index.php3?number=news&newsnumber=8229&dept=&lang=E| last=Office of the Lieutenant Governor of Prince Edward Island| title=Diamond Jubilee Celebrations Begin| date=3 February 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Prince Edward Island| accessdate=29 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606125718/http://www.gov.pe.ca/newsroom/index.php3?number=news&newsnumber=8229&dept=&lang=E| archivedate=6 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=NWT>{{cite web| url=http://www.executive.gov.nt.ca/offices/protocol/NWTJubileeEvents/index.html| last=Northwest Territories Executive| title=Department of Executive > Offices of the Executive > Protocol > NWT Jubilee Events| publisher=Government of the Northwest Territories Publications| accessdate=26 July 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703065742/http://www.executive.gov.nt.ca/offices/protocol/NWTJubileeEvents/index.html| archivedate=3 July 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> permission was granted by the Queen to break the usual protocol of flying the banner only where the sovereign is physically present.<ref name=CTVJubilee /> At noon on the same day, the [[Peace Tower#Carillon|Peace Tower carillon]] played a tribute to Elizabeth II.{{refn|This included the tunes \"[[O Canada]]\", \"Westminster\" (for carillon), \"[[And did those feet in ancient time|Jerusalem]]\", \"This Canada of Ours\", \"[[Andante (tempo)|Andante]]\" (from Sonata for 47 Bells), and \"[[God Save the Queen]]\".<ref name=Music />|group=n|name=Music}}<ref name=Music>{{cite web| url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/About/House/Collections/carillon/programme-e.htm| last=Parliament of Canada| title=The House of Commons Heritage Collection > Carillon > Programme| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=6 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504144051/http://www.parl.gc.ca/About/House/Collections/carillon/programme-e.htm| archivedate=4 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Prime Minister and the leader of the [[Liberal Party of Canada]] issued statements commending the Queen for her six decades of \"dedicated service to our country, to the Commonwealth and to the world.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.liberal.ca/newsroom/news-release/statement-by-liberal-leader-bob-rae-on-the-queen%e2%80%99s-diamond-jubilee/| last=Rae| first=Bob| authorlink=Bob Rae| title=Statement by Liberal Leader Bob Rae on the Queen\u2019s Diamond Jubilee| date=6 February 2012| publisher=Liberal Party of Canada| accessdate=26 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215100904/http://www.liberal.ca/newsroom/news-release/statement-by-liberal-leader-bob-rae-on-the-queen%E2%80%99s-diamond-jubilee| archivedate=15 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=4619| last=Harper| first=Stephen| authorlink=Stephen Harper| title=The Queen's Diamond Jubilee: a Canadian celebration| date=6 February 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=26 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120808071318/http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=4619| archivedate=8 August 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Royal Standard of Canada.svg|thumb|right|The royal standard of Elizabeth II, Queen of Canada, which was flown at various locations across Canada during Diamond Jubilee Week.]]\nAlso on 6 and 7 February, the first of the 60,000 Canadian [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]]s to be distributed to citizens and permanent residents were handed out by [[Lieutenant governor (Canada)|lieutenant governors]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lieutenant-gouverneur.qc.ca/salle-de-presse/allocutions/6-02-12.htm| last=Duchense| first=Pierre| title=Allocution de Son Honneur l'honorable Pierre Duchesne, lieutenant-gouverneur du Qu\u00e9bec, \u00e0 l'occasion de la c\u00e9r\u00e9monie de remise de la M\u00e9daille du jubil\u00e9 de diamant de Sa Majest\u00e9 la reine Elizabeth II| date=6 February 2012| publisher=Bureau du Lieutenant-gouverneur du Qu\u00e9bec| language=French| accessdate=29 June 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521221423/http://www.lieutenant-gouverneur.qc.ca/salle-de-presse/allocutions/6-02-12.htm| archivedate=21 May 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Commissioner#Canada|commissioners]],<ref name=NWT /> and other dignitaries across the country; 60 individuals were given theirs personally by the Governor General at Rideau Hall.<ref name=PEI /><ref name=CTVJubilee>{{cite news|url=http://edmonton.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20120206/diamond-jubilee-celebrations-120206/20120206/?hub=EdmontonHome |title=Canada kicks off festivities for Queen's jubilee |date=6 February 2012 |publisher=CTV |accessdate=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318190237/http://edmonton.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20120206/diamond-jubilee-celebrations-120206/20120206/?hub=EdmontonHome |archivedate=18 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14414| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=Sixty Canadians are Honoured During the Inaugural Presentation Ceremony of the Diamond Jubilee Medal at Rideau Hall| date=6 February 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref> All federal [[Member of Parliament (Canada)|Members of Parliament]] (MPs) received the award automatically and a few refused, some because they belonged to the [[Quebec sovereignty movement|Quebec separatist]] [[Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]],<ref name=WFP>{{citation|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/canada/breakingnews/jubilee-hoopla-a-royal-pain-for-some-anti-monarchists-who-question-cost-138800719.html|last=Rakobowchuk| first=Peter| title=Jubilee hoopla a royal pain for some anti-monarchists who question cost| date=6 February 2012|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press| accessdate=10 February 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref> and one because he felt the money being spent by the Crown on jubilee events and markers was a waste.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/canada/breakingnews/canada-kicks-off-four-months-of-celebrations-for-queens-diamond-jubilee--138871859.html|last=McQuigge| first=Michelle| title=Canada kicks off four months of celebrations for Queen's Diamond Jubilee| date=7 February 2012|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press| accessdate=9 February 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref> [[Citizens for a Canadian Republic]] claimed that day that the government's spending of money on the Queen's jubilee was to be expected \"from the personality cult dynasties of North Korea or Syria\".<ref>{{cite press release| title=Jubilee celebrations raise questions of priorities| publisher=Citizens for a Canadian Republic| date=6 February 2012| url=http://www.canadian-republic.ca/media_release_02-06-12-B.html| accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> The [[Saint-Jean-Baptiste Society]] claimed it would stage \"counter-celebrations\".<ref name=WFP />\n\nIn [[Nova Scotia]], the provincial government announced the establishment of educational programmes related to the Queen and her role in Canadian government and the one-time award of the $2000 Diamond Jubilee Award Scholarship to 60 Grade 12 students in the province.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://gov.ns.ca/iga/djedu.asp| last=Government of Nova Scotia| title=The Diamond Jubilee of Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II > Diamond Jubilee Education Initiatives| publisher=Queen's Printer for Nova Scotia| accessdate=29 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604134528/http://gov.ns.ca/iga/djedu.asp| archivedate=4 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> There and in other provinces and territories, various events were held on Accession Day, other days during Diamond Jubilee Week, and past its end.{{refn|[[Gordie Gosse]], the [[Speaker of the House of Assembly of Nova Scotia]], held a youth event at [[Province House (Nova Scotia)|Province House]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://gov.ns.ca/iga/djPhoto.asp| last=Government of Nova Scotia| title=The Diamond Jubilee of Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II > Diamond Jubilee Photos| publisher=Queen's Printer for Nova Scotia| accessdate=29 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603060929/http://gov.ns.ca/iga/djPhoto.asp| archivedate=3 June 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Lieutenant Governor of British Columbia]] [[Steven Point]] hosted a tea and later formal reception at [[Government House (British Columbia)|Government House]].<ref name=BCCeremony>{{cite news| url=http://www.opinion250.com/blog/view/23244| title=Diamond Jubilee Celebration Held At BC Legislature| date=14 February 2012| publisher=680 News| accessdate=2 March 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130131012207/http://www.opinion250.com/blog/view/23244| archivedate=31 January 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> A public official reception was held by the [[Commissioner of the Northwest Territories|territorial commissioner]] at the [[Legislative Assembly of the Northwest Territories]] on 7 February, at which a pictorial display with the theme of past royal tours of the territory was opened.<ref name=NWT /> A ceremony, attended by the [[Lieutenant Governor of British Columbia|Lieutenant Governor]], [[Premier of British Columbia|Premier]], and parliamentary officials was held in conjunction with the opening of the British Columbia legislature on 14 February.<ref name=BCCeremony /> And [[Lieutenant Governor of Ontario]] [[David Onley]] mounted at the viceregal suite at the [[Ontario Legislative Building]] an exhibition entitled ''60 in 60'', to \"show six decades of Her Majesty's devotion and service to Canada.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.jubilee.lt.gov.on.ca/60in60/| last=Office of the Lieutenant Governor of Ontario| title=60 in 60| publisher=Queen's Printer for Ontario| accessdate=6 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517205344/http://www.jubilee.lt.gov.on.ca/60in60/| archivedate=17 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>|group=n|name=Prov}} The [[Speaker of the Senate (Canada)|Speaker of the Senate]], [[No\u00ebl Kinsella]], and [[Speaker of the House of Commons (Canada)|Speaker of the House of Commons]], [[Andrew Scheer]], were received by the Queen at [[Buckingham Palace]] on 21 February 2012, where they presented a loyal address to the sovereign.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/CourtCircular/Todaysevents.aspx| last=Royal Household| title=Court Circular > 21 February 2012| publisher=[[Queen's Printer]]| accessdate=25 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229062758/http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/CourtCircular/Todaysevents.aspx| archivedate=29 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The [[Canadian Postal Museum]] also opened on 19 March the exhibition Designed for a Queen, which displayed 645 postal portraits of the Queen from Canada, other [[Commonwealth of Nations]] countries, and [[British Overseas Territories]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.civilization.ca/event/designed-for-a-queen-celebrating-the-60-year-reign-of-queen-elizabeth-ii-through-stamps| title=Exhibitions > Special Exhibitions > Designed for a Queen: Celebrating the 60-year Reign of Queen Elizabeth II through Stamps| publisher=Canadian Museum of Civilization| accessdate=28 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511112036/http://www.civilization.ca/event/designed-for-a-queen-celebrating-the-60-year-reign-of-queen-elizabeth-ii-through-stamps| archivedate=11 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Royal tour====\n[[File:2012 Royal Tour of Canada, Queen's Park 7.JPG|thumb|left|[[Charles, Prince of Wales]], speaks to the public outside of the [[Ontario Legislative Building]] during his tour of Canada for the Diamond Jubilee]]\n\n[[Charles, Prince of Wales]], and [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]], toured parts of the country in May,<ref name=CNW/> making stops in [[New Brunswick]], Ontario, and [[Saskatchewan]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14382| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=Their Royal Highnesses The Prince of Wales and The Duchess of Cornwall to Undertake a Royal Tour of Canada in 2012| date=14 December 2011| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=14 December 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20141014105320/http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14382| archivedate=14 October 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref> In an editorial he wrote for ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', Charles stated he wanted his activities during the tour to reflect the jubilee's \"central theme of service to others\" and expressed that he was \"returning to Canada in this special Jubilee year, to renew my own pledge of service and to encourage others to consider how they might contribute their own particular talent\".<ref>{{citation| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/opinions/opinion/through-service-to-others-we-build-strong-communities/article2436190/| author1=Prince Charles| author2=Prince of Wales| authorlink=Charles, Prince of Wales| title=Through service to others, we build strong communities| date=18 May 2012| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| accessdate=25 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523202145/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/opinions/opinion/through-service-to-others-we-build-strong-communities/article2436190/| archivedate=23 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> In that vein, he in all three provinces visited with people associated with his organisation [[The Prince's Charities#The Prince's Charities Canada|The Prince's Charities Canada]] and presented Diamond Jubilee Medals to recipients.\n\nThe couple arrived at [[Saint John Airport]] on the evening of 20 May.<ref name=DCHItinerary>{{cite web| url=http://pch.gc.ca/eng/1336669990111/1336670644633| last=Department of Canadian Heritage| title=Topics > Monarchy in Canada > 2012 Royal Tour > 2012 Royal Tour Itinerary| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=11 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521034454/http://pch.gc.ca/eng/1336669990111/1336670644633| archivedate=21 May 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The following day, they were formally welcomed by the Governor General and met at [[CFB Gagetown|Canadian Forces Base Gagetown]] with young Canadian Forces veterans and mentors involved in the Military Entrepreneurship program before moving on to [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]]. There, they undertook a walking tour of Prince William Street to observe heritage projects and meet the 2002 Committee for the Prince of Wales Municipal Heritage Leadership Prize, participated in a citizenship ceremony, attended [[Victoria Day]] events, and opened the Diamond Jubilee IT Centre at Hazen-White-St. Francis School.<ref name=DCHItinerary/> They then flew on to [[Toronto]] to meet with emergency workers and their families and observe the annual fireworks show at [[The Beaches|Ashbridges Bay]] that marks Victoria Day and the [[Queen's Birthday#Canada|Queen's official Canadian birthday]].\n\nOn 22 May, the couple attended an event hosted by the [[Lieutenant Governor of Ontario]], [[David Onley]], at [[Queen's Park (Toronto)|Queen's Park]]. After, the Duchess visited [[The Queen's Own Rifles of Canada]], of which she is colonel-in-chief,<ref>{{citation| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/article/1170776--royal-tour-2012-details-announced-for-charles-and-camilla-s-tour-of-toronto| last=Daubs| first=Katie| title=Royal Tour 2012: Details announced for Charles and Camilla's tour of Toronto| date=30 April 2012| newspaper=Toronto Star| accessdate=5 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827070741/http://www.thestar.com/news/article/1170776--royal-tour-2012-details-announced-for-charles-and-camilla-s-tour-of-toronto| archivedate=27 August 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> laying at the armoury a wreath in memory of fallen Canadian soldiers, while the Prince of Wales saw the Digital Media Zone at [[Ryerson University]], toured the construction site of the athletes' village for the [[2015 Pan American Games]] (where [[Premier of Ontario]] [[Dalton McGuinty]] announced a portion of [[Front Street (Toronto)|Front Street]] running through the village would be named ''Diamond Jubilee Promenade''<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20120522/prince-charles-camilla-in-toronto-120522/#ixzz1vhjnJQPS| title=Prince Charles, Camilla head to Regina after Toronto tour| date=22 May 2012| publisher=CTV| accessdate=23 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525075702/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20120522/prince-charles-camilla-in-toronto-120522#ixzz1vhjnJQPS| archivedate=25 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>), visited the Yonge Street Mission, and met with the national leadership of the [[Assembly of First Nations]]. The couple also attended a luncheon hosted by the [[government of Ontario]] and participated in a [[Canadian Forces]] event at [[Fort York]] commemorating the 200th anniversary of the [[War of 1812]],<ref name=DCHItinerary /> the Prince there wearing his uniform of a [[Lieutenant-general (Canada)|lieutenant-general]] of the [[Canadian Army]].\n[[File:Saskatchewan Legislative Building Front.JPG|thumb|right|The [[Saskatchewan Legislative Building]] in 2012. The building's centenary was marked by [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], and [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]], as part of their Canadian royal tour earlier that year.]]\nThey arrived in [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]] on 23 May and marked the centenary of [[Saskatchewan Legislative Building|Saskatchewan's legislative building]], participated in a reception held by the Lieutenant Governor of Saskatchewan at Government House, toured the [[First Nations University of Canada]], and visited an environmentally friendly water purification plant. In the evening, the Prince and Duchess attended at the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) Depot Division Drill Hall a performance of the [[Regina Symphony Orchestra]], of which Prince Charles is patron.<ref name=DCHItinerary/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://pch.gc.ca/eng/1335470669033/1335471159074| last=Department of Canadian Heritage| title=The Department > Newsroom > Government of Canada Unveils Details of the 2012 Royal Tour| date=30 April 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=5 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130628032051/http://www.pch.gc.ca/eng/1335470669033/1335471159074| archivedate=28 June 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> There, the Prime Minister announced that Charles was to be appointed Honorary Commissioner of the RCMP, taking the post from his mother, the Queen, who became the RCMP's Commissioner-in-Chief.<ref>{{citation| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/harper-names-prince-charles-honorary-rcmp-commissioner/article2441944/| last=Mackrael| first=Kim| title=Harper names Prince Charles honorary RCMP commissioner| date=23 May 2012| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| accessdate=25 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526020840/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/harper-names-prince-charles-honorary-rcmp-commissioner/article2441944/| archivedate=26 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[New Democratic Party of Canada|New Democratic Party]] MP [[Pat Martin]], an open anti-monarchist, stated in the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] that the tour was \"a [[Bread and circuses|bread-and-circuses]] routine\" intended to distract from cuts to the [[Public Service of Canada|federal civil service]].<ref>{{citation| url=http://fullcomment.nationalpost.com/2012/04/30/kelly-mcparland-nathan-cullens-deportment-police-can-start-with-pat-martin/| last=McParland| first=Kelly| title=Nathan Cullen's deportment police can start with Pat Martin| date=30 April 2012| newspaper=National Post| accessdate=6 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120716091322/http://fullcomment.nationalpost.com/2012/04/30/kelly-mcparland-nathan-cullens-deportment-police-can-start-with-pat-martin/| archivedate=16 July 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Minister of Canadian Heritage, [[James Moore (Canadian politician)|James Moore]], said the tour would be the \"least expensive for taxpayers\" of those that had taken place since 2009.<ref>{{citation| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/tories-blasted-over-1-million-bread-and-circuses-royal-tour/article2417917/?from=sec501| last=Chase| first=Steven| title=Tories blasted over $1-million 'bread and circuses' royal tour| date=30 April 2012| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| accessdate=6 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525182454/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/tories-blasted-over-1-million-bread-and-circuses-royal-tour/article2417917/?from=sec501| archivedate=25 May 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Events through June====\nAt the Queen's request,<ref name=CTVRCMP>{{cite news |url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/TopStories/20120523/rcmp-musical-ride-buckingham-palace-guard-duty-120523/ |title=Mounties guard the Queen in London for a day |date=23 May 2012 |publisher=CTV |accessdate=25 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525075532/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/TopStories/20120523/rcmp-musical-ride-buckingham-palace-guard-duty-120523/ |archivedate=25 May 2012  }}</ref> members of the RCMP's [[Musical Ride]], after performing in the [[Diamond Jubilee Pageant]] at [[Windsor Castle]], took part in the Changing of the Guard on 23 May as they formed the [[Queen's Guard|Queen's Life Guard]] outside Buckingham Palace for 24 hours.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iUQJHXQFYW2HsFHhH0wdTWl5oEsw?docId=CNG.da5623a1e1f2af30fd41b88f6c00592c.301| title=Canada's Mounties guard Buckingham Palace| date=24 May 2012|agency=AFP| accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> Said by the contingent's commander to be a \"way for Canada and the Mounties to salute her Majesty the Queen in her Diamond Jubilee year\",<ref name=CTVRCMP/> it was the second time the RCMP had performed the task since doing so as a part of the Diamond Jubilee celebrations for Queen Victoria in 1897.<ref>{{citation| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/worldview/mounties-set-to-replace-queens-life-guard-at-buckingham-palace-for-one-day/article2439909/| last=Saunders| first=Doug| title=Mounties set to replace Queen's Life Guard at Buckingham Palace for one day| date=22 May 2012| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| accessdate=25 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525115523/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/worldview/mounties-set-to-replace-queens-life-guard-at-buckingham-palace-for-one-day/article2439909/| archivedate=25 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n{{Quote box| width=250px| border=1px| align=left| quote=We, Your Majesty's loyal and dutiful subjects, the House of Commons of Canada in Parliament assembled, beg to offer our sincere congratulations on the happy completion of the sixtieth year of Your reign.\n\nIn this, the Diamond Jubilee year of your reign as Queen of Canada, we trust that Your gracious and peaceful reign may continue for many years and that Divine Providence will preserve Your Majesty in health, in happiness and in the affectionate loyalty of Your people.<ref name=LoyAddress>{{Citation| last=Parliament of Canada| year=2012| editor-last=O'Malley| editor-first=Kady| title=To The Queen's Most Excellent Majesty, with love from Her Canadian parliamentarians...| journal=CBC| publication-date=2012| url=http://www.cbc.ca/newsblogs/politics/inside-politics-blog/2012/06/to-the-queens-most-excellent-majesty-with-love-from-her-canadian-parliamentarians.html| accessdate=4 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727074637/http://www.cbc.ca/newsblogs/politics/inside-politics-blog/2012/06/to-the-queens-most-excellent-majesty-with-love-from-her-canadian-parliamentarians.html| archivedate=27 July 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>| salign=right| source=Parliament of Canada, 2012}}\n\nIn the [[Parliament of Canada|federal parliament]] on 31 May, a loyal address to the Queen was passed.<ref name=LoyAddress /> The [[Lieutenant Governor of Manitoba]] held a Diamond Jubilee garden party at the province's Government House on 26 May.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20120511/diamond-jubilee-events-schedule-itinerary-queen-120511/| title=The Diamond Jubilee: Schedule of events| date=14 May 2012| publisher=CTV| accessdate=28 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518082222/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20120511/diamond-jubilee-events-schedule-itinerary-queen-120511/| archivedate=18 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Royal British Columbia Museum]] on 1 June opened an exhibition of approximately 100 [[Cecil Beaton]] photographs of Elizabeth II throughout her life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalbcmuseum.bc.ca/Exhibit_Gall/queenelizabethII.aspx| title=Exhibits & Galleries > Visiting Exhibitions > Queen Elizabeth II by Cecil Beaton: A Diamond Jubilee Celebration| publisher=Royal British Columbia Museum| accessdate=2 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref>\n[[File:Barbeau Peak, Nunavut.jpg|thumb|right|[[Barbeau Peak|Mount Barbeau]] in [[Nunavut]]]]\n\nA team of Canadian and British mountaineers reached the summit of [[Barbeau Peak|Mount Barbeau]], in Canada's arctic, by 3 June and there held a tea party in celebration of the jubilee. From the summit, they sent a loyal greeting to the Queen via satellite, to which the monarch promised to reply.<ref>{{cite news| title=Adventurers to celebrate Queen\u2019s Jubilee atop Arctic peak| date=22 May 2012| publisher=CBC}}</ref> The next day, a group from the [[Royal Canadian Dragoons]] stationed in [[Afghanistan]] climbed with British soldiers to the peak of the 7,000 foot mountain Gharib Ghar, within the [[Kabul Military Training Center]], \"as part of the Diamond Jubilee celebrations for Queen Elizabeth II.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dragoons.ca/afganchange.html| title=The Changing Role of Dragoons in Afghanistan| publisher=Royal Canadian Dragoons| accessdate=16 July 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120721214108/http://www.dragoons.ca/afganchange.html| archivedate=21 July 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, [[Canada House]] held a Big Jubilee Lunch on 3 June and two beacons were lit on the building's roof the following evening,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/united_kingdom-royaume_uni/events-evenements/diamond_jubilee-jubile_diamant.aspx?lang=eng&view=d| last=High Commission of Canada to the United Kingdom| authorlink=High Commission of Canada to the United Kingdom| title=Canada celebrates Her Majesty's Diamond Jubilee| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=28 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505210732/http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/united_kingdom-royaume_uni/events-evenements/diamond_jubilee-jubile_diamant.aspx?lang=eng&view=d| archivedate=5 May 2012 }}</ref> the night of the [[Diamond Jubilee Concert]]. Johnston attended both events and Harper was at the latter.<ref name=GGLondon /><ref name=VS>{{citation| url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/Harper+joins+Diamond+Jubilee+celebrations/6722925/story.html| last=Kennedy| first=Mark| title=Harper joins the Diamond Jubilee celebrations| date=3 June 2012| newspaper=Vancouver Sun| accessdate=4 June 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref> Another reception was held at Canada House on the evening of 6 June, at which the Governor General and [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]], were present.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14560| last=Johnston| first=David| authorlink=David Johnston| title=Reception with the Business Community| date=6 June 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=22 June 2012}}</ref>\nHarper was granted an audience with the Queen at Buckingham Palace on 5 June.<ref name=VS/> Also at the palace, the Governor General, the Prime Minister, and the Queen unveiled a [[Canadian royal symbols#Artworks|new portrait of the sovereign]] commissioned by the federal Crown-in-Council and painted by Canadian painter Phil Richards. The creation of the portrait became the subject of a [[National Film Board of Canada]] (NFB) documentary directed by [[Hubert Davis (filmmaker)|Hubert Davis]] and released in the fall of 2012 as part of the NFB's ''Queen's Diamond Jubilee Collector's Edition''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://realscreen.com/2012/06/07/national-film-board-puts-final-touches-to-the-portrait/#ixzz1xyvJFwJf| last=Vlessing| first=Etan| title=National Film Board puts final touches to \"The Portrait\"| date=5 June 2012| publisher=Realscreen| accessdate=16 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402171234/http://realscreen.com/2012/06/07/national-film-board-puts-final-touches-to-the-portrait/#ixzz1xyvJFwJf| archivedate=2 April 2015| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfb.ca/film/portrait/|title=The Portrait|last=Davis, Hubert (director)|work=Documentary film|publisher=[[National Film Board of Canada]]|accessdate=13 October 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017044641/http://www.nfb.ca/film/portrait|archivedate=17 October 2012}}</ref> The painting was on 25 June installed in the ballroom at Rideau Hall. Dedicated at the same time by the Governor General were new bronze and glass handrails, with detailing evoking the Diamond Jubilee, flanking the ceremonial staircase in Rideau Hall's main entrance foyer.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14596| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=Her Majesty The Queen's New Painting Arrives at Rideau Hall| date=25 June 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 June 2012, the government of the [[Northwest Territories]] (NWT) and the City of [[Yellowknife]] held at the Northern Arts and Cultural Centre a garden party with [[barbecue]], concert, and other activities. On 14 June, Amber Jubilee Ninebark shrubs were planted on the grounds of the NWT legislative assembly.<ref name=NWT /> Four days later, a gala concert was held at [[Roy Thomson Hall]] in Toronto, at which 600 diamond jubilee medals were awarded to members of the [[Order of Canada]] and [[Order of Ontario]]. The event, hosted by the Lieutenant Governor of Ontario, was attended by the Governor General and his wife and performers included the [[Famous People Players]], [[Susan Aglukark]], [[Molly Johnson]], [[Ben Heppner]], and [[Gordon Lightfoot]], who conceived the idea of the event.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/story/2012/06/18/jubilee-gala-toronto.html| title=Diamond Jubilee Gala toasts exceptional Canadians| date=18 June 2012| publisher=CBC| accessdate=19 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619053044/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/story/2012/06/18/jubilee-gala-toronto.html| archivedate=19 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Further events====\n[[File:British pageantry at Canadian Museum of Civilization (8347684263).jpg|thumb|left|The [[Queen's Beasts]] on display at the [[Canadian Museum of Civilization]] during Elizabeth II's Diamond Jubilee]]\nThe [[Lieutenant Governor of Saskatchewan]] held a garden party at [[Government House (Saskatchewan)|Government House]] on [[Canada Day]] and,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://jubileesk.ca/events/item/?e=6| archive-url=https://archive.today/20120716224505/http://jubileesk.ca/events/item/?e=6| url-status=dead| archive-date=16 July 2012| last=Government of Saskatchewan| title=Events > Garden Party| publisher=Queen's Printer for Saskatchewan| accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> in the Northwest Territories, the Canada Day parade was themed to celebrate the jubilee and numerous jubilee medal presentation ceremonies took place.<ref name=NWT /> Also on 1 July, the [[Canadian Museum of Civilization]] opened the exhibit ''A Queen and Her Country'', showing artefacts from the [[Crown Collection]] relating to Queen Elizabeth II and her role as Queen of Canada, including the [[Queen's Beasts]] from [[Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II|her coronation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.civilization.ca/exhibitions/special-exhibitions/a-queen-and-her-country3| title=Exhibitions > Special Exhibitions > A Queen and Her Country| publisher=Canadian Museum of Civilization| accessdate=28 June 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625031245/http://www.civilization.ca/exhibitions/special-exhibitions/a-queen-and-her-country3| archivedate=25 June 2012 }}</ref> At Rideau Hall on 11 September, a reception, attended by the Governor General; his wife; [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]]; [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex]]; and others, was held for the [[Royal Victorian Order]] Association of Canada and to \"honour of the 60th anniversary of Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II\u2019s accession to the Throne.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14708| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=Working Visit to Canada by The Earl and Countess of Wessex| date=10 September 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=12 September 2012}}</ref> The Earl also distributed Diamond Jubilee Medals to recipients in Toronto and to members of the RCMP in [[Iqaluit]], [[Nunavut]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://blogs.canoe.ca/royalspectacle/general/prince-edward-sophie-kick-off-tour/| last=Schwass-Bueckert| first=Kate| title=Prince Edward, Sophie kick off tour| date=11 September 2012| publisher=Canoe| accessdate=16 September 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130115071634/http://blogs.canoe.ca/royalspectacle/general/prince-edward-sophie-kick-off-tour/| archivedate=15 January 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/story/2012/09/13/north-royal-visit-iqaluit.html| title=Royals commend RCMP officers in Iqaluit| date=13 September 2012| publisher=CBC| accessdate=16 September 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916015841/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/story/2012/09/13/north-royal-visit-iqaluit.html| archivedate=16 September 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The government of the Northwest Territories held through September an essay contest for youth to explain \"how the Queen is important to [[First Nations]] and [[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)|M\u00e9tis people]].\"<ref name=NWT />\n\nA conference on the Canadian Crown was conducted in Saskatchewan on 25 October.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://jubileesk.ca/events/item/?e=7| last=Government of Saskatchewan| title=Events > Conference on the Crown| publisher=Queen's Printer for Saskatchewan| accessdate=7 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120710034648/http://jubileesk.ca/events/item/?e=7| archivedate=10 July 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Governor General the following day unveiled a plaque identifying the Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Trail, a part of the [[Trans Canada Trail]] between the [[West Block]] on [[Parliament Hill]] and the [[Supreme Court of Canada]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14800| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=Governor General to Unveil New Plaque in Honour of the Naming of The Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Trail| date=24 October 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=25 October 2012}}</ref> In Nova Scotia, [[Nova Scotia Highway 106|highway 106]] was renamed as ''Jubilee Highway''.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20121221002| last=Government of Nova Scotia| title=Highway Naming Commemorates 60-year Reign| date=21 December 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Nova Scotia| accessdate=21 December 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220034319/http://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20121221002| archivedate=20 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Communities across Canada also held events to mark the jubilee,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebratecanada.info/docs/Plan%20Diamond%20Jubilee%202012.pdf|title=London Celebrates Canada|publisher=City of London|accessdate=6 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905170736/http://www.celebratecanada.info/docs/Plan%20Diamond%20Jubilee%202012.pdf|archivedate=5 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://museumsofburlington.com/events/21-queen-s-jubilee-mother-s-day-royal-tea--may-13-2012| title=Events > Upcoming Events > Queen's Jubilee & Mother's Day Royal Tea| publisher=Museums of Burlington| accessdate=5 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120605020450/http://www.museumsofburlington.com/events/21-queen-s-jubilee-mother-s-day-royal-tea--may-13-2012| archivedate=5 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.metrocinema.org/film_view/3541/| title=Queen's Diamond Jubilee: The Queen| publisher=Metro Cinema| accessdate=5 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805222513/http://www.metrocinema.org/film_view/3541/| archivedate=5 August 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.monarchist.ca/en/jubilee-jubile/events| title=List of Diamond Jubilee events| publisher=Monarchist League of Canada| accessdate=5 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414201429/http://www.monarchist.ca/en/jubilee-jubile/events| archivedate=14 April 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gov.pe.ca/diamondjubilee/index.php3?number=1042882&lang=E| last=Government of Prince Edward Island| title=The Diamond Jubilee: A Prince Edward Island Celebration > Community Events| publisher=Queen's Printer for Prince Edward Island| accessdate=16 September 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025092210/http://www.gov.pe.ca/diamondjubilee/index.php3?number=1042882&lang=E| archivedate=25 October 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> as did the federal government until the jubilee celebration ended on Accession Day 2013.\n\n===Jamaica===\n[[Prince Harry]] toured Jamaica between 5 and 8 March 2012,<ref name=GoJam>{{cite news| url=http://go-jamaica.com/news/read_article.php?id=35102| title=Preparations underway for Prince\u2019s visit| date=7 February 2012| publisher=Go-Jamaica| accessdate=11 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210183703/http://go-jamaica.com/news/read_article.php?id=35102| archivedate=10 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/Big-foreign-media-coverage-for-Prince-Harry-s-visit_10924286| title=Big foreign media coverage for Prince Harry's visit| date=29 February 2012| newspaper=Jamaica Observer| accessdate=29 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302182553/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/Big-foreign-media-coverage-for-Prince-Harry-s-visit_10924286| archivedate=2 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> participating in various events marking his grandmother's Diamond Jubilee as Jamaica's queen regnant, first as [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|Queen of the United Kingdom]], between 1952 and 1962, and subsequently as [[Monarchy of Jamaica|Queen of Jamaica]] (Jamaica will also thus be concurrently celebrating 50 years of independence). During the tour, the Prince partook in military exercises with the [[Jamaica Defence Force]], visited Bustamante Hospital for Children and, in [[Trelawny Parish]], visited Water Square, Falmouth Pier, and the William Knibb Baptist Church, where he paid respect at the [[William Knibb]] memorial. The Prince attended an event for the charity Rise Life,<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2111338/Prince-Harry-Jamaica-Prince-dances-Bob-Marley-Diamond-Jubilee-tour-wearing-blue-shoes.html| title=Don't step on my blue suede shoes: Party Prince Harry gets down to Bob Marley in Jamaica wearing {{Sic|hide=y|brightly|-}}coloured desert boots| date=7 March 2012| newspaper=Daily Mail| accessdate=8 March 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308033052/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2111338/Prince-Harry-Jamaica-Prince-dances-Bob-Marley-Diamond-Jubilee-tour-wearing-blue-shoes.html| archivedate=8 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> ran with [[Usain Bolt]] at the latter's training ground at the [[University of the West Indies]], [[Mona, Jamaica|Mona]]. There, he was also named an Honorary Fellow of the university.<ref>{{citation| url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/latest/article.php?id=35727| title=Prince Harry named Honorary UWI Fellow| date=6 March 2012| newspaper=The Gleaner| accessdate=8 March 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307233703/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/latest/article.php?id=35727| archivedate=7 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> A Jamaica Night reception was held at the Royal Caribbean Hotel in Montego Bay and [[Governor-General of Jamaica]] Sir [[Patrick Allen (politician)|Patrick Allen]] hosted a dinner at [[King's House, Jamaica|King's House]] as a combined celebration of the Diamond Jubilee and Jamaica's 50th anniversary of independence. The Prime Minister, [[Portia Simpson Miller]], stated the tour was intended to \"highlight the country's tourism developments on the North Coast and the important work being done in the area of youth and children.\"<ref name=GoJam />\n\nThe Governor-General and his wife travelled to London, United Kingdom (UK), to partake in various events there in June, including a reception held by the High Commissioner of Jamaica to the UK.<ref name=JGDJL />  Jamaica's Diamond Jubilee celebrations proceeded despite Miller's ongoing work to have the country become a republic.<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.jis.gov.jm/news/leads/30943| title=High Commissioner Assures UK Jamaicans on Republic Status| date=17 June 2012| publisher=Jamaica Information Service| accessdate=24 June 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525154011/http://www.jis.gov.jm/news/leads/30943| archivedate=25 May 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand===\n[[File:NZ Jubilee Emblem.jpg|thumb|right|The official emblem of the [[Monarchy of New Zealand|Queen of New Zealand]]'s Diamond Jubilee<ref>{{cite web| url=http://gg.govt.nz/content/queens-diamond-jubilee-emblem| last=Governor-General of New Zealand| authorlink=Governor-General of New Zealand| title=Queen's Diamond Jubilee Emblem of New Zealand| publisher=Governor-General of New Zealand| accessdate=29 November 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111218200831/http://gg.govt.nz/content/queens-diamond-jubilee-emblem| archivedate=18 December 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref>]]\nSir [[Jerry Mateparae]], the [[Governor-General of New Zealand]], unveiled New Zealand's Diamond Jubilee emblem on 27 November 2011 and announced at that time that a full programme would be forthcoming.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://gg.govt.nz/content/queens-diamond-jubilee-emblem| last=Office of the Governor-General of New Zealand| title=Queen's Diamond Jubilee Emblem of New Zealand| publisher=Government Printing Office| accessdate=29 November 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111218200831/http://gg.govt.nz/content/queens-diamond-jubilee-emblem| archivedate=18 December 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[New Zealand Post]] and the [[Reserve Bank of New Zealand]] stated in January 2012 the release a silver proof dollar coin to celebrate the Queen's Diamond Jubilee and, the following month, the [[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] added Crown-related entries to [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand]] and an essay on the jubilee to NZ.History.net.nz.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://coins.nzpost.co.nz/2012/queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee-silver-proof-coin| last=New Zealand Post| title=2012 Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Silver Proof Coin| publisher=Government Printing Office| accessdate=1 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20120201184023/http://coins.nzpost.co.nz/2012/queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee-silver-proof-coin| archivedate=1 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| title=Waitangi Day starts Queen's Diamond Jubilee celebrations| last=Ministry for Culture and Heritage| date=3 February 2012| url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU1202/S00036/waitangi-day-starts-queens-diamond-jubilee-celebrations.htm| publisher=Scoop| accessdate=3 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207184309/http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU1202/S00036/waitangi-day-starts-queens-diamond-jubilee-celebrations.htm| archivedate=7 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The New Zealand post also issued sets of Diamond Jubilee stamps showing images of Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip throughout her reign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stamps.nzpost.co.nz/new-zealand/2012/queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee|title=2012 Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee|website=New Zealand Post Stamps|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222031115/http://stamps.nzpost.co.nz/new-zealand/2012/queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee|archivedate=22 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nPrime Minister [[John Key]] moved a motion in the [[New Zealand House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] congratulating the Queen on her Diamond Jubilee on 7 February.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.parliament.nz/en-NZ/PB/Debates/Debates/9/e/6/50HansD_20120207_00000012-Motions-Queen-Elizabeth-II-Diamond-Jubilee.htm| last=Parliament of New Zealand| authorlink=Parliament of New Zealand| title=Motions \u2013 Queen Elizabeth II \u2013 Diamond Jubilee| publisher=Government Printing Office| accessdate=10 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304173955/http://www.parliament.nz/en-NZ/PB/Debates/Debates/9/e/6/50HansD_20120207_00000012-Motions-Queen-Elizabeth-II-Diamond-Jubilee.htm| archivedate=4 March 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Queen-in-Council|Governor-General-in-Council]] also launched, two days later, via the [[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)|Ministry of Health]], the Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Research Grant, \"seeking to purchase research projects that transfer knowledge from initiatives with proven effectiveness, into practice in the health sector\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrc.govt.nz/news-and-media/news/queen-elizabeth-ii-jubilee-research-grant-health-knowledge-action |last=Health Research Council of New Zealand |title=Queen Elizabeth II Jubilee Research Grant \u2013 Health Knowledge to Action |date=9 February 2012 |publisher=Government Printing Office |accessdate=19 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213030438/http://www.hrc.govt.nz/news-and-media/news/queen-elizabeth-ii-jubilee-research-grant-health-knowledge-action |archivedate=13 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe New Zealand Army Band took part in the Diamond Jubilee Pageant held at Windsor Castle and also took part in the changing of guard ceremony at Buckingham Palace. In New Zealand, ''[[New Zealand Herald]]'' opinion columnist [[Jim Hopkins]] was critical of the jubilee celebrations held over the [[Queen's Birthday#New Zealand|Queen's Birthday weekend]], calling it a \"missed opportunity\".<ref name=hopkins>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/opinion/news/article.cfm?c_id=466&objectid=10811537|title=Shame we blew Queen's Jubilee|date=8 June 2012|accessdate=30 July 2012|publisher=[[New Zealand Herald]]}}</ref> He was also critical of [[TVNZ]]'s lack of jubilee related content in its daily news broadcast.<ref name=hopkins />\n\nA royal tour was undertaken by [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], and [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]], between 10 and 16 November 2012.<ref name=TelegraphPoW /><ref>{{cite press release| last=Office of the Prime Minister of New Zealand| title=PM marks beginning of Diamond Jubilee year| publisher=Government Printing Office| date=6 February 2012| url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1202/S00051/pm-marks-beginning-of-diamond-jubilee-year.htm| accessdate=6 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207145515/http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1202/S00051/pm-marks-beginning-of-diamond-jubilee-year.htm| archivedate=7 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> travelling to [[Auckland]], [[Wellington, New Zealand|Wellington]], [[Christchurch]], and [[Manawatu]]. Their programme is to focus on excellence and innovation in business, agriculture, community service, and sports, as well as children's literacy and animal health.<ref name=TelegraphPoW />\n\n===Papua New Guinea===\n[[Charles, Prince of Wales]], and [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]], toured Papua New Guinea between 3 and 5 November. During their time in the country, the couple met church, charity, and community volunteers, cultural groups, and members of the [[Papua New Guinea Defence Force]] in and near [[Port Moresby]].<ref name=TelegraphPoW />\n\n===Oceanic realms===\n[[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge]], and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]], visited the [[Solomon Islands]] and [[Tuvalu]].<ref name=BBCJplans />\n\n===Other Caribbean and West Indies realms===\nThe Queen's realms throughout the Caribbean and West Indies planned a number of Diamond Jubilee events. Using [[RFA Fort Rosalie (A385)|RFA ''Fort Rosalie'']], [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]], and [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex]], visited other Caribbean realms, including: Antigua and Barbuda, Grenada, Montserrat and Saint Lucia.<ref name=BBCJplans /><ref>{{Citation|last=Prime Minister of St. Kitts and Nevis |title=Display during visit of cruise ship Queen Elizabeth to mark Diamond Jubilee |publisher=The Office of the Prime Minister of St. Kitts and Nevis |date=7 December 2011 |url=http://www.cuopm.com/newsitem_new.asp?articlenumber=2583&post200803=true |accessdate=8 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415034623/http://www.cuopm.com/newsitem_new.asp?articlenumber=2583&post200803=true |archivedate=15 April 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/8955439/Diamond-Jubilee-Royal-Family-will-visit-every-Realm.html| title=Diamond Jubilee: Royal Family will visit every Realm| author=Staff writer| date=14 December 2011| work=The Daily Telegraph| location=UK| accessdate=5 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210003539/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/8955439/Diamond-Jubilee-Royal-Family-will-visit-every-Realm.html| archivedate=10 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Saint Kitts and Nevis===\nHistorical re-enactments were put on in Saint Kitts and Nevis for the Earl and Countess of Wessex, who arrived on 3 March 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.sknvibes.com/news/newsdetails.cfm/53702| title=Dramatic historical re-enactments to mark Diamond Jubilee celebration| date=17 February 2012| publisher=SKNVibes| accessdate=19 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120225031529/http://www.sknvibes.com/news/newsdetails.cfm/53702| archivedate=25 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> There, the couple met with Governor-General Sir [[Cuthbert Sebastian]], Prime Minister [[Denzil Douglas]], and other dignitaries, watched cultural shows (including the performance of a [[Calypso music|calypso]] song about the Queen), and the Earl unveiled a plaque commemorating the Diamond Jubilee and officially designated the [[Basseterre Valley]] Park as the Royal Basseterre Valley Park. They also visited [[Brimstone Hill Fortress National Park]] and the children's ward of the JNF Hospital and the Children's Home before attending a state dinner and fireworks display at Port Zante.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.winnfm.com/news2.asp?NewsID=8293#.T1JtfH2Hawc.twitter| last=Frederick| first=Toni|title=Prince Edward delights the crowd| date=3 March 2012| publisher=Winn FM| accessdate=6 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Saint Lucia===\nThe Earl and Countess of Wessex arrived in Saint Lucia on 21 February 2012 and there participated in Independence Day celebrations and attended receptions held by the [[Governor-General of Saint Lucia]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/st-lucia-celebrates-33-years-of-independence/| title=St Lucia celebrates 33 years of Independence| date=22 February 2012| publisher=NationNews| accessdate=23 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202222118/http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/st-lucia-celebrates-33-years-of-independence/| archivedate=2 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> They also visited the Association of Saint Lucia and the Saint Lucia School of Music.<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.thedominican.net/2012/02/royals-to-begin-visit.html| title=Royals to begin Caribbean tour bypasses Dominica| date=16 February 2012| newspaper=The Dominican| accessdate=19 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203072813/http://www.thedominican.net/2012/02/royals-to-begin-visit.html| archivedate=3 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Saint Vincent and the Grenadines===\nIn Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, a Diamond Jubilee Celebrations Committee was established to oversee events staged to mark, between February and June 2012, the Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II's accession as queen regnant of the country, from 1952 to 1979 as [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|Queen of the United Kingdom]] and thereafter as [[Monarchy of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines|Queen of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]]. The committee head, former Minister of Culture Rene Baptiste, stated the aim was to \"showcase what we have to offer, as well as our loyalty to the Parliament...\" The Earl and Countess of Wessex, aboard [[RFA Fort Rosalie (A385)|RFA ''Fort Rosalie'']], arrived for their tour of country on 25 February and visited the restored [[Botanic Gardens St. Vincent]] and planted a Pink Poui tree, attended an official lunch at Government House, and planted [[Roystonea|Royal Palms]] on the [[Grenadines]].\n\nTrade unionist Noel Jackson said he heard displeasure expressed by Vincentians towards the royal tour and that \"a lot of people were cursing.\" Senator Julian Francis, the General Secretary of the governing [[Unity Labour Party]], stated the public reaction to the presence of the royal couple \"confirmed to me that we could not have won [[2009 Vincentian constitutional referendum|the 2009 referendum on a republic]]. The outpouring of the people in St. Vincent to come and greet Prince Edward yesterday confirmed to me that people, in the majority in St. Vincent, still want the monarchy... It was like a carnival in town yesterday.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://i-witness-news.com/2012/02/27/majority-of-vincentians-still-want-the-monarchy/| title=Majority of Vincentians 'still want the monarchy'| date=27 February 2012| publisher=I-Witness News| accessdate=28 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301110030/http://i-witness-news.com/2012/02/27/majority-of-vincentians-still-want-the-monarchy/| archivedate=1 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA Diamond Jubilee Lecture was delivered in March, a flower show and tea party was held at Government House on 4 and 5 May, a stamp exhibition was mounted at the National Trust headquarters and an exhibition of photographs of the Queen in Saint Vincent and the Grenadines was displayed at the National Public Library. A Queen's Birthday parade took place, as did a Diamond Jubilee Beacon Event on 4 June, part of the wider plan to light such beacons at the same time across the Commonwealth.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.thevincentian.com/dcmain.aspx?p=0&i=9355&skin=75&tID=198 |last=Clarke |first=Karissa |title=Big plans to mark Queen's Diamond Jubilee |date=2 February 2012 |newspaper=The Vincentian |accessdate=5 February 2012 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\n[[File:Diamond Jubilee 60 2012 logo.jpg|thumb|right|The United Kingdom's Diamond Jubilee logo]]\n[[File:Cmglee Sea Containers House OXO Tower jubilee.jpg|thumb|right|[[Sea Containers House]] decorated with a [[Largest photographs in the world|large photograph]] of [[Silver Jubilee of Elizabeth II|her Silver Jubilee]]]]\n[[File:Red Arrows II.JPG|thumb|right|Flypast by the [[Red Arrows]] over Buckingham Palace on 5 June]]\n\n====Planning====\nIn the United Kingdom, national and regional events to mark the Diamond Jubilee were coordinated by the [[Queen-in-Council]] and her Royal Household at [[Buckingham Palace]].<ref name=Mail>{{Cite news| title=The Queen: Don't link my Jubilee celebration to 'flashy' Olympics| work=Daily Mail| location=London| date=27 June 2009| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1195973/The-Queen-Dont-link-Jubilee-celebration-flashy-Olympics.html| accessdate=31 October 2010| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130114055826/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1195973/The-Queen-Dont-link-Jubilee-celebration-flashy-Olympics.html| archivedate=14 January 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> As with the [[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Golden Jubilee]] in 2002, the [[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]] was responsible for coordinating the [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]]-led aspects of the celebrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gov.uk/what_we_do/honours/diamondjubilee.aspx| last=Department of Culture, Media, and Sport| title=diamond jubilee| publisher=[[Queen's Printer]]| accessdate=31 October 2010| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100927050301/http://culture.gov.uk/what_we_do/honours/diamondjubilee.aspx| archivedate=27 September 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gov.uk/diamondjubilee| last=Department for Culture, Media, and Sport| authorlink=Department for Culture, Media and Sport| title=what we do > honours and ceremonials >  diamond jubilee| publisher=[[Queen's Printer]]| accessdate=20 April 2010| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100329153058/http://www.culture.gov.uk/diamondjubilee| archivedate=29 March 2010 }}</ref> Events were planned so as to keep the use of tax money to a minimum; most funds used to fund celebrations were drawn from private donors and sponsors. Only the cost of security was by [[HM Treasury|Her Majesty's Treasury]].<ref name=GlobePomp /> The British logo for the Diamond Jubilee was selected through a contest held by the [[BBC]] children's programme ''[[Blue Peter]]''; the winning design, announced in February 2011, was created by ten-year-old Katherine Dewar.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12518165|title=Queen's Diamond Jubilee emblem revealed|date=21 February 2011|accessdate=21 February 2011|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221051419/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12518165|archivedate=21 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2011/DiamondJubileeemblemunveiled21February2011.aspx| last=Royal Household| title=Diamond Jubilee emblem unveiled| publisher=[[Queen's Printer]]| date=11 February 2011| accessdate=10 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215181939/http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2011/DiamondJubileeemblemunveiled21February2011.aspx| archivedate=15 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Extended weekend====\nOn 5 January 2010, the [[Lord President of the Council]] and [[Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills|Business Secretary]] [[Peter Mandelson|Lord Mandelson]] announced that an extra [[bank holiday]] would take place on 5 June 2012.<ref name=Mail /><ref name=PA>{{Cite news|title=Extra bank holiday to mark Jubilee |publisher=Press Association |date=5 January 2010 |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5iFc6Cmk-AJ72Mo5lMkmGuUqHSxIw |accessdate=5 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108223450/http://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5iFc6Cmk-AJ72Mo5lMkmGuUqHSxIw |archivedate=8 January 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=BIS>{{cite web|title=Extra Bank holiday to mark Queen's Diamond Jubilee |publisher=Department for Business Innovation & Skills |date=5 January 2010 |url=http://www.bis.gov.uk/jubilee |accessdate=6 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120405181048/http://www.bis.gov.uk/jubilee |archivedate=5 April 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Moving the Spring Bank Holiday (the last Monday in May) to 4 June resulted in a four-day holiday in honour of the Diamond Jubilee.<ref name=PA /><ref name=Reuters>{{Cite news|title=Extra holiday for 2012 Jubilee |publisher=Reuters |date=5 January 2010 |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKTRE6043L120100105 |accessdate=5 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107121124/http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKTRE6043L120100105 |archivedate=7 January 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> As national holidays are a [[Reserved and excepted matters|devolved matter]], Scotland's [[First Minister of Scotland|first minister]] confirmed that the bank holiday would be held on 5 June in Scotland. Some economists later theorised that the holiday could reduce the country's gross domestic product by 0.5% in the second quarter of the year, though this would be partially offset by increased sales for the hospitality and merchandise sectors.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.sky.com/home/business/article/16163892| title='Diamond Jubilee Could Harm The Economy'| publisher=Sky News| date=6 February 2012| accessdate=6 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207185203/http://news.sky.com/home/business/article/16163892| archivedate=7 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Queen Elizabeth II.JPG|thumb|left|The Queen travelling by car to [[St Paul's Cathedral]] for the service of thanksgiving on 5 June]]\n\nMany events were staged in London during the bank holiday weekend.<ref name=Reuters /> The [[River Thames|River]] [[Thames Diamond Jubilee Pageant]] was held on 3 June; a maritime parade of 1,000 boats from around the Commonwealth\u2014the largest flotilla seen on the river in 350 years\u2014together with other celebrations along the river banks.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://thamesdiamondjubileepageant.org/| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110407222350/http://www.thamesdiamondjubileepageant.org/| url-status=dead| archive-date=7 April 2011| title=Welcome| publisher=Diamond Jubilee| accessdate=7 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=London river extravaganza planned for Queen's jubilee| publisher=France 24| date=6 April 2011| url=http://www.france24.com/en/20110406-london-river-extravaganza-planned-queens-jubilee| accessdate=7 April 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120126151433/http://www.france24.com/en/20110406-london-river-extravaganza-planned-queens-jubilee| archivedate=26 January 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation| last=Bates| first=Stephen| title=Thames flotilla to mark Queen's diamond jubilee| newspaper=The Guardian| date=5 April 2011| url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/apr/05/thames-flotilla-queen-diamond-jubilee| accessdate=7 April 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203051933/http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/apr/05/thames-flotilla-queen-diamond-jubilee| archivedate=3 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Heavy rain started during the event and the commemorative airforce flyover at the end was cancelled due to very low [[cloud base]] and bad visibility at ground level. Along with almost all members of the Royal Family, various governors-general from the Commonwealth realms other than the UK were in attendance.<ref name=GGLondon>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14556| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=The Central Weekend \u2013 Queen's Diamond Jubilee| date=1 June 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=JGDJL>{{citation| url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20120601/social/social5.html| title=Sir Patrick and Lady Allen for Diamond Jubilee| date=1 June 2012| newspaper=Jamaica Gleaner| accessdate=4 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603040004/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20120601/social/social5.html| archivedate=3 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Diamond Jubilee Concert]], with a preceding afternoon picnic in the palace gardens for the 10,000 concert ticket holders,<ref name=BBC_McCartney_to_play>{{cite web| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16925230| title=Sir Paul McCartney to play Queen Diamond Jubilee gig| publisher=BBC| work=BBC News| date=7 February 2012| accessdate=20 April 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120519122700/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16925230| archivedate=19 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=BBC_Webber_Barlow>{{cite web| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-17152327| title=Andrew Lloyd Webber and Gary Barlow write Jubilee song| publisher=BBC| work=BBC News| date=24 February 2012| accessdate=20 April 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418202717/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-17152327| archivedate=18 April 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=BBC_Blumenthal>{{cite web| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-17757416| title=Heston Blumenthal plans 'best of British' Jubilee picnic| publisher=BBC| work=BBC News| date=18 April 2012| accessdate=20 April 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419224021/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-17757416| archivedate=19 April 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> was held the following day, in front of [[Buckingham Palace]], and featured acts representing each decade of the Queen's 60-year reign.\n\n[[Street party|Street parties]] were permitted to take place across the country.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.communities.gov.uk/newsstories/newsroom/1700319| last=Department for Communities and Local Government| title=The new, simple, easy-to-use form to organise street parties has arrived!| publisher=[[Queen's Printer]]| accessdate=19 February 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202145525/http://www.communities.gov.uk/newsstories/newsroom/1700319| archivedate=2 February 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Special community lottery grants, called ''The Jubilee People's Millions'', are being offered by the [[Big Lottery Fund]] and [[ITV plc|ITV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peoplesmillions.org.uk/faqs|title=Lottery Millions to Help Communities Bloom for Diamond Jubilee|publisher=The National Lottery|accessdate=19 February 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110305184121/http://www.peoplesmillions.org.uk/faqs|archivedate=5 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nMembers of the Royal Family, governors-general, and prime ministers from the Commonwealth realms were present at various functions held on 4 and 5 June: A reception took place at Buckingham Palace before the Diamond Jubilee Concert and a service of thanksgiving was conducted the following day at [[St Paul's Cathedral|St. Paul's Cathedral]], also attended by 2,000 other guests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stpauls.co.uk/News-Press/News-Archive/2012/Queen-celebrates-Jubilee-at-St-Pauls-images|title=Queen celebrates Jubilee at St Paul's|publisher=St Paul's Cathedral|accessdate=20 September 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921054306/http://www.stpauls.co.uk/News-Press/News-Archive/2012/Queen-celebrates-Jubilee-at-St-Pauls-images|archivedate=21 September 2013}}</ref> [[Will Todd]]'s anthem \"The Call of Wisdom\", commissioned specially for this event, was performed by the Diamond Choir, made up of about 40 children from around the UK.<ref>{{cite web| title=OUP: Diamond Jubilee anthem by Will Todd| url=http://www.oup.com/uk/pressreleases/willtodd/| publisher=Oxford University Press| accessdate=3 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606130004/http://www.oup.com/uk/pressreleases/willtodd/| archivedate=6 June 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Diamond Choir: Meet the Choir| url=http://www.diamondchoir.co.uk/meet-the-choir.asp| publisher=St. Paul's Cathedral| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723171816/http://www.diamondchoir.co.uk/meet-the-choir.asp| archivedate=23 July 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[The Archbishop of Canterbury]] dedicated his sermon to the Queen, during which he noted her \"lifelong dedication\" and stated that she \"has made her 'public' happy and all the signs are that she is herself happy, fulfilled and at home in these encounters.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18330637| title=Dr Williams pays tribute to the Queen at thanksgiving| date=5 June 2012| publisher=BBC| accessdate=24 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120610205106/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18330637| archivedate=10 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Afterwards, a formal lunch was held in [[Westminster Hall]]. The Queen returned to [[Buckingham Palace]] at 2:20 pm, in an open top carriage procession and escorted by [[The Household Cavalry Regiment]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18327711 Diamond jubilee: Flypast bring celebrations to an end] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608190912/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18327711 |date=8 June 2012 }} BBC News. Accessed 24 June 2012.</ref> Another reception was held at [[Guildhall, London|London's Guildhall]] and a luncheon took place at [[Lancaster House]], hosted by the British [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]].<ref name=GlobePomp /><ref name=GGLondon /> A reception solely for governors-general was held by the Queen at Buckingham Palace.<ref name=GGLondon />\n\nThe weekend of celebrations ended with a balcony appearance at Buckingham Palace. The Queen appeared on the balcony with the Prince of Wales, the Duchess of Cornwall, the Duke of Cambridge, the Duchess of Cambridge, and Prince Harry in front of cheering crowds outside the palace and along [[The Mall, London|The Mall]]. There followed a [[feu de joie]] and a [[flypast]] by the [[Red Arrows]] and historic aircraft,<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18327711 Diamond Jubilee: flypast brings celebrations to an end] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608190912/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18327711 |date=8 June 2012 }} BBC News. Accessed 5 June 2012.</ref> including the last flying [[Lancaster bomber]] in Britain.  Several media commentators commented on the significance of only senior members of the royal family appearing on the balcony.  BBC royal correspondent Peter Hunt remarked that it \"sent a message demonstrating both continuity and restraint at a time of austerity\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18327711 Diamond Jubilee: flypast brings celebrations to an end] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608190912/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18327711 |date=8 June 2012 }} BBC News. Accessed 24 June 2012.</ref>\n\n====Permanent tributes====\n\nTo mark the jubilee, the Queen bestowed [[List of UK place names with royal patronage#Royal Borough|Royal Borough]] status on [[Royal Borough of Greenwich|Greenwich]], in southeast London.<ref name=PA /><ref name=GC>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenwich.gov.uk/Greenwich/LeisureCulture/RoyalGreenwich/RoyalGreenwich.htm |title=Greenwich to become Royal Borough |publisher=Greenwich Council |date=5 January 2010 |accessdate=5 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108082815/http://www.greenwich.gov.uk/Greenwich/LeisureCulture/RoyalGreenwich/RoyalGreenwich.htm |archivedate=8 January 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In addition, a competition was held to grant in 2012 [[City status in the United Kingdom|city status]] to towns and either a [[List of lord mayoralties and lord provostships in the United Kingdom|lord mayoralty or lord provostship]] to one city.{{refn|The towns that bid for city status were:<ref name=entrants>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-13796689| title=More than 25 towns bid for Diamond Jubilee city status| publisher=BBC| date=16 June 2011| accessdate=18 June 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617043606/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-13796689| archivedate=17 June 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bolton, Bournemouth, Chelmsford, Colchester, Coleraine, Corby, Craigavon, Croydon, Doncaster, Dorchester, Dudley, Dumfries, Gateshead, Goole, Luton, Medway, Middlesbrough, Milton Keynes, Perth, Reading, Southend, St Asaph, St Austell, Stockport, Tower Hamlets, and Wrexham.\n\nThe cities that bid for a Lord Mayoralty or Lord Provostship were:<ref name=entrants /> Armagh, Cambridge, Derby, Gloucester, Lancaster, Newport, Peterborough, Salford, Southampton, St Albans, Sunderland, and Wakefield.|group=n|name=Cities}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11887723|title=Diamond Jubilee to be marked by creation of new UK city|publisher=BBC|date=1 December 2010|accessdate=1 December 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204074545/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11887723|archivedate=4 December 2010}}</ref> City status was awarded to [[Chelmsford]] in England, [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]] in Scotland and [[St Asaph]] in Wales. [[Armagh]], Northern Ireland, was awarded the Lord Mayoralty.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-17364651|title=Three towns win city status for Diamond Jubilee|publisher=BBC|date=14 March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425183250/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-17364651|archivedate=25 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Olympic park in East London, created for the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London Olympics]], was named the [[Olympic Park, London|Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park]] following the Olympics.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Games site renamed the Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park| publisher=BBC| date=7 October 2010| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-11492273| accessdate=15 October 2010| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101014074838/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-11492273| archivedate=14 October 2010| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Queen Elizabeth II Fields Challenge (Queen Elizabeth Fields Challenge in Scotland) was a project of the charity [[Fields in Trust]] to safeguard parks and green spaces as public recreation land in perpetuity for future generations to enjoy, and to provide a permanent legacy of the Diamond Jubilee and the Olympics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalfoundation.com/our-work/queen-elizabeth-ii-fields-challenge/|title=Queen Elizabeth II Fields Challenge|publisher=The Royal Foundation|accessdate=24 July 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729104839/http://www.royalfoundation.com/our-work/queen-elizabeth-ii-fields-challenge/|archivedate=29 July 2017}}</ref> The [[Woodland Trust]] planned to establish 60 Jubilee [[woodland]]s during 2011 and 2012, one of almost 500 acres \u2013 [[Flagship Diamond Wood]], Leicestershire \u2013 and the remainder 60 acres each.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-14327232| title=Woodland Trust searching for jubilee wood site| publisher=BBC| date=30 July 2011| accessdate=30 July 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110730171623/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-14327232| archivedate=30 July 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA stained glass window, paid for by MPs and members of the House of Lords, was unveiled in the Queen's presence at [[Westminster Hall]] in March 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kennedy|first=Maev|title=Queen's diamond jubilee stained glass window unveiled by MPs|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/mar/20/queen-diamond-jubilee-glass|accessdate=5 June 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=20 March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129203218/http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/mar/20/queen-diamond-jubilee-glass|archivedate=29 January 2016}}</ref> In addition, a majority of MPs endorsed the renaming of the [[clock tower]] of [[Westminster Palace]] that houses Big Ben, to the [[Elizabeth Tower]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Hough|first=Andrew|title=The Queen's Diamond Jubilee: 'Big Ben to be renamed Elizabeth Tower'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9307060/The-Queens-Diamond-Jubilee-Big-Ben-to-be-renamed-Elizabeth-Tower.html|accessdate=3 June 2012|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|date=3 June 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603034658/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9307060/The-Queens-Diamond-Jubilee-Big-Ben-to-be-renamed-Elizabeth-Tower.html|archivedate=3 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:RoyalJubileeBells in the church.jpg|thumb|The Royal Jubilee Bells in St James Garlickhythe before being hung in the church's tower]]\nThe [[Royal Jubilee Bells]], made for the Jubilee and a feature of the [[Thames Diamond Jubilee Pageant]], were delivered to the church of [[St James Garlickhythe]] in the [[City of London]] on 15 June 2012 and arranged along the central aisle. They were dedicated by the [[John Waine|Rt Revd John Waine]] on Sunday 17 June and hanging commenced in the tower shortly thereafter. They were rung for the first time in the church on 4 July.<ref>{{cite web|last=Love|first=Dickon R.|url=http://london.lovesguide.com/james_garlickhythe.htm|title=Church Bells of the City of London \u2013 St James Garlickhythe|publisher=Love's Guide to the Bells of the City of London|accessdate=5 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170311191225/http://london.lovesguide.com/james_garlickhythe.htm|archivedate=11 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Royal Mint issued a number of coins including an official \u00a35 coin, a 5oz coin and a kilo coin.<ref>Sovereign Mint [http://sovereignmint.co.uk/queen-elizabeth-iis-diamond-jubilee-coins-issued-for-2012/ \"Official Diamond Jubilee coins from the Royal Mint\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426173640/http://sovereignmint.co.uk/queen-elizabeth-iis-diamond-jubilee-coins-issued-for-2012/ |date=26 April 2015 }}, ''[[Official Diamond Jubilee coins from the Royal Mint]]''</ref> A five-pound [[sterling silver]] coin was issued by the Government of Gibraltar to mark the occasion.<ref>Towermint [http://www.towermint.com/Shop/product/27 \"Diamond Jubilee Five Pounds Silver Coin\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805185313/http://www.towermint.com/Shop/product/27 |date=5 August 2012 }}, ''[[Diamond Jubilee Five Pounds Silver Coin]]'', 1 May 2012.  Retrieved on 7 November 2012.</ref>\n\nIn October 2012 it was announced that the Queen would bestow the honorary title of [[Regius Professor]]ship to up to six university chairs in the United Kingdom, to recognise \"excellence in teaching and research\";<ref>{{Cite news| title=New Regius professorships to mark Jubilee| author=Elizabeth Gibney| url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/421475.article| magazine=Times Higher Education| date=12 October 2012| accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref> the number was chosen to represent the decades of the Queen's reign.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/80218/Entry-Guidelines-Q-A.pdf| format=PDF| title=Regius Professorships \u2013 entry guidelines| date=October 2012| publisher=[[Cabinet Office]]| accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref> The full list was announced on 29 January 2013 and comprised twelve new chairs, in recognition of the \"exceptionally high quality\" of the departments considered.<ref>{{Cite press release| title=Cabinet Office: The Queen awards prestigious Regius professorships to twelve universities| date=29 January 2013| publisher=PoliticsHome| url=http://www.politicshome.com/uk/article/70924/cabinet_office_the_queen_awards_prestigious_regius_professorships_to_twelve_universities.html| accessdate=3 April 2013| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322001916/http://www.politicshome.com/uk/article/70924/cabinet_office_the_queen_awards_prestigious_regius_professorships_to_twelve_universities.html| archivedate=22 March 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|Kew Gardens]] announced that the Main Gate, the entrance to the gardens from Kew Green, was to be renamed Elizabeth Gate in honour of the Queen. [[Princess Alexandra, The Honourable Lady Ogilvy|Princess Alexandra]] attended the naming ceremony on 21 October 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/news/9993864.Royalty_opens_Kew_Gardens__Elizabeth_Gate/|title=Royalty opens Kew Gardens' Elizabeth Gate|work=Richmond and Twickenham Times|date=21 October 2012|accessdate=12 July 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714130113/http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/news/9993864.Royalty_opens_Kew_Gardens__Elizabeth_Gate/|archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 December 2012, the [[British Foreign Office]] announced that a portion of the British Antarctic Territory was to be named [[Queen Elizabeth Land]] in honour of Her Majesty in her diamond jubilee year.<ref>{{cite web|title=UK to name part of Antarctica Queen Elizabeth Land|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20757382|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=18 December 2012|date=18 December 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103083842/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20757382|archivedate=3 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nA seemingly less permanent tribute that gained widespread popularity was a work provided by street artist [[Banksy]]. His [[Slave Labour (mural)|\"Slave Labour\"]] stencil on a north London wall offered pointed criticism of the jubilee celebrations and the conditions that support British nationalism.<ref>Sarah Lyall, {{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/01/world/europe/give-us-our-banksy-mural-back-londoners-say.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=26 February 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304110740/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/01/world/europe/give-us-our-banksy-mural-back-londoners-say.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 |archivedate=4 March 2013  }}, ''The New York Times'', 1 March 2013.</ref> The mural's removal and subsequent attempted sale at auction in February 2013 sparked international controversy, highlighting the piece's worth to local and regional residents.<ref>Richard Luscombe, {{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2013/feb/23/banksy-missing-mural-auction-stopped |title=Archived copy |accessdate=18 April 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014183955/http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2013/feb/23/banksy-missing-mural-auction-stopped |archivedate=14 October 2013  }}, ''The Guardian'', 23 February 2013</ref> Its title, perhaps coincidentally, conjured another contentious part of the celebrations where unemployed workers, bussed into London on an allegedly unpaid trial to staff security for the event, were made to work under what some described as \"appalling\" conditions.<ref>Felicity Morse, {{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/06/05/kerry-mccarthy-mp-jubilee-workfare-unemployed_n_1570067.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=28 March 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209050000/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/06/05/kerry-mccarthy-mp-jubilee-workfare-unemployed_n_1570067.html |archivedate=9 December 2013  }}, ''Huffington Post'', 5 June 2012.</ref>\n\n====Other events====\nOn Accession Day, 6 February, a 62-[[21-gun salute|gun salute]] was mounted on the banks of the [[River Thames]], near the [[Tower of London]] and the Queen made a visit to [[Norfolk]], one of the first places the monarch visited after acceding to the throne.<ref name=BelStamps /> Later in the month, Queen Elizabeth attended a multi-faith (Bah\u00e1'\u00ed, Buddhist, Christian, Hindu, Jain, Jewish, Muslim, Sikh, and Zoroastrian) reception held at the residence of the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[Lambeth Palace]], in honour of the jubilee.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://news.bahai.org/story/889| title=Queen launches Diamond Jubilee year with multifaith reception| date=21 February 2012| publisher=Bah\u00e1'\u00ed World News Service| accessdate=25 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526103746/http://news.bahai.org/story/889| archivedate=26 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Queen addressed both houses of [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliament]] in [[Westminster Hall]] on 20 March 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16628608| title=Queen to address Parliament joint session for jubilee| publisher=BBC| date=19 January 2012| accessdate=19 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120223033218/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16628608| archivedate=23 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Also in March, the [[Royal Commonwealth Society]] launched the Jubilee Time Capsule to mark the jubilee.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.jubileetimecapsule.org| title=Jubilee Time Capsule| publisher=Royal Commonwealth Society| accessdate=15 July 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712104542/http://www.jubileetimecapsule.org/| archivedate=12 July 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]] and [[Andrew Marr]] created the television documentary ''[[The Diamond Queen (TV programme)|The Diamond Queen]]'', in which various members of the Royal Family and current and former politicians spoke about the Sovereign and her life. The documentary was criticised by the campaign group [[Republic (political organisation)|Republic]], which argued that it breached BBC guidelines on impartiality.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-17119720 BBC royal series The Diamond Queen biased, Republic says] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527213129/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-17119720 |date=27 May 2012 }}, ''[[BBC News]]''</ref>\n\nAt Buckingham Palace, a display of the Queen's diamonds was opened to the public.<ref name=GlobePomp /> On 4 June, the bells in each of the 34 church bell towers along the [[River Welland]] valley rang in succession, ending with the ringing of the bell at [[Fosdyke]] 60 times.<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.northantset.co.uk/news/local/a-royal-ring-for-queen-s-jubilee-1-3814645#| title=A royal ring for Queen's jubilee| date=6 May 2012| newspaper=Evening Telegraph| accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 May, the Queen attended the [[Diamond Jubilee Armed Forces Parade and Muster]], the [[British Armed Forces]]' own tribute to the monarch, in [[Windsor Castle]] and nearby [[Home Park, Windsor|Home Park]]. The first time all three services had assembled for the Queen for such an event at the same time, it featured military reviews and a 2,500 strong military parade through the town, as well as a military flypast featuring 78 aircraft.<ref name=BBC_Parade>{{cite web| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18123991| title=Diamond Jubilee: Armed forces in parade and flypast| publisher=BBC| work=BBC News| date=19 May 2012| accessdate=19 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120519031218/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18123991| archivedate=19 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA [[Nowka Bais]] competition in [[Oxford]] was dedicated to the Diamond Jubilee. The Queen issued a statement on the event and expressed her interest about the [[Bengal]]i sporting tradition to the event organisers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/opinion/heritage/2017/07/25/bangladeshi-boat-race-uk|publisher=[[Dhaka Tribune]]|title=Bangladeshi boat race takes the UK by storm|author=Morshed Akhter Badol|date=25 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Overseas territories====\n[[File:Queen's Birthday Parade 2012 - Prince Edward.jpg|thumb|left|The Earl and Countess of Wessex at the Queen's Birthday Parade, Grand Casemates Square, [[Gibraltar]], June 2012]]\n[[Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester]], toured the [[British Virgin Islands]] (BVI) in March 2012. On [[Montserrat]], he met participants in the Sailability BVI programme, including [[Special Olympics]] medallists, and staff and associates of the Eslyn Henley Ritchie Learning Centre, BVI Technical and Vocational Institute, BVI Services, and the Department of Youth Affairs and Sports.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukinmontserrat.fco.gov.uk/en/news/?view=News&id=739827082 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120730041609/http://ukinmontserrat.fco.gov.uk/en/news/?view=News&id=739827082 |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 July 2012 |last=Office of the Governor of Montserrat |authorlink=Governor of Montserrat |title=HRH The Duke of Gloucester Visits Watersports Centre, Inspects Sailability's Fleet |date=8 March 2012 |publisher=[[Queen's Printer]] |accessdate=8 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\n[[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]], and [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex]], visited the British Overseas Territory of [[Gibraltar]], between 11\u201313 June 2012,<ref name=TeleGibraltar>{{citation| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/spain/9258138/Spain-issues-formal-complaint-over-Prince-Edward-Gibraltar-visit.html| last=Govan| first=Fiona| title=Spain issues formal complaint over Prince Edward Gibraltar visit| date=10 May 2012| newspaper=The Telegraph| accessdate=11 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511034927/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/spain/9258138/Spain-issues-formal-complaint-over-Prince-Edward-Gibraltar-visit.html| archivedate=11 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Montserrat]].{{When|date=March 2012}}<ref name=BBCJplans /> The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation (Spain)|Spanish Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation]] expressed \"upset and concern\" about the couple's tour of Gibraltar, which Spain claims as Spanish territory.<ref name=TeleGibraltar />\n\n==Other Commonwealth countries==\nVisits were planned by [[Anne, Princess Royal|Princess Anne]] to Zambia and Mozambique, while the [[Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester|Duke of Gloucester]] made official visits to Uganda and Malta. In Asia, [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]], visited India, while [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge]], and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]], visited Malaysia, Singapore, and the Solomon Islands.<ref>{{Citation| last=guardian.co.uk| title=Royal family to mark Queen's diamond jubilee with visits to Commonwealth| newspaper=The Guardian| date=14 December 2011| url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/dec/14/royal-family-diamond-jubilee-commonwealth| accessdate=15 December 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317185818/http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/dec/14/royal-family-diamond-jubilee-commonwealth| archivedate=17 March 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]], and [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex]], visited Trinidad and Tobago,<ref>{{cite news|last=Harris|first=Carolyn|title=Royals of the Caribbean: The 2012 Diamond Jubilee Commonwealth Tours Begin|url=http://www.royalhistorian.com/royals-of-the-caribbean-the-2012-diamond-jubilee-commonwealth-tours-begin/|accessdate=22 June 2013|publisher=royalhistorian.com|date=15 February 2012}}</ref> as did [[Governor General of Canada]] [[David Johnston]].\n\n===South Africa===\nThe British Consulate in Cape Town,<ref>UK High Commission Pretoria{{vague|date=June 2012}}</ref> in conjunction with the Hout Bay and Llandudno Heritage Trust, hosted a firing of ancient muzzle-loading cannons at East Fort in Hout Bay. The Hout Bay and Llandudno Heritage Trust restored the Fort's original Swedish made 18 pounder muzzle-loading cannons, dating from 1752, and fired two rolling salvo salutes, of six cannon shots each, in the Queen\u2019s honour and in recognition of the bond of friendship between South Africa and Great Britain. The South African Navy Band was in attendance and the guns were fired by VIPs who were guided by gunners of the \"Honourable Order of Hout Bay Artillerymen\".\n\nAt the Victoria and Alfred Waterfront of the Port of Cape Town, a flotilla from the [[Royal Cape Yacht Club]] sailed past the Hildebrand Ristorante and into-the Victoria Basin and the Cape Town Highlanders marched from Ferryman's to Nobel Square. British Consul General Chris Trott lit a beacon, followed by a further six-gun salute and both South African national anthem and \"God Save the Queen\". {{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Other areas==\n\n===Hong Kong===\nHong Kong, a [[British overseas territory|British dependent territory]] until 1997 and the most populous one, had The Big Jubilee Lunch on 3 June 2012, organised by the [[Royal Commonwealth Society|Royal Commonwealth Society in Hong Kong]]. On 5 June 2012, there was a service of thanksgiving at the territory's [[Hong Kong Sheng Kung Hui|Anglican]] [[St. John's Cathedral (Hong Kong)|Cathedral Church of St. John the Evangelist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukinhongkong.fco.gov.uk/en/visiting-uk/jubilee-2012/hk-events |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20121214012754/http://ukinhongkong.fco.gov.uk/en/visiting-uk/jubilee-2012/hk-events |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 December 2012 |title=Hong Kong Jubilee 2012 Events |publisher=UK in Hong Kong |accessdate=6 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]]\n* [[2012 Diamond Jubilee Honours]]\n* [[Silver Jubilee of Elizabeth II]]\n* [[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II]]\n* [[Sapphire Jubilee of Elizabeth II]]\n* [[List of monarchs in Britain by length of reign]]\n* [[List of Jubilees of British monarchs]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n{{Reflist|group=\"n\"}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Diamond Jubilee of Queen Elizabeth II}}\n\n* {{Official website|http://www.thediamondjubilee.org/}}\n* [http://www.pch.gc.ca/eng/1296669421850/1296669769856 Department of Canadian Heritage: The Queen's Diamond Jubilee]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120210133249/http://gg.govt.nz/content/diamond-jubilee Governor-General of New Zealand: The Queen's Diamond Jubilee]\n* [http://www.royal.gov.uk/HMTheQueen/TheQueenandspecialanniversaries/TheQueensDiamondJubilee2012/TheQueensDiamondJubilee2012.aspx The British Monarchy: The Queen's Diamond Jubilee 2012]\n* [http://www.jubileetribute.org/#&slider1=1 The Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust]\n* [http://www.diamondjubileebeacons.co.uk/ Official Diamond Jubilee Beacons website]\n* [http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/onlinereview2013/the-queens-realms/index.html The Prince of Wales and Duchess of Cornwall's Diamond Jubilee tours]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G7kRM3mh7qc&feature=endscreen Governor General of Canada David Johnston's Diamond Jubilee message]\n* [http://www.historymuseum.ca/exhibitions/past-exhibitions/a-queen-and-her-country3 Canadian Museum of History: A Queen and Her Country]\n* [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/60160/supplement/1 Loyal Addresses on The London Gazette]\n* ''[http://www.archives.gov.on.ca/en/explore/online/jubilee/index.aspx The Archives of Ontario Celebrates the Diamond Jubilee of Queen Elizabeth II]'', online exhibit on Archives of Ontario website\n\n{{Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Diamond Jubilee}}\n\n[[Category:Elizabeth II]]\n[[Category:Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II| ]]\n[[Category:British monarchy]]\n[[Category:Events involving British royalty]]\n[[Category:Anniversaries]]\n[[Category:2012 in Australia]]\n[[Category:2012 in Canada]]\n[[Category:2012 in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:2012 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Monarchy in Australia]]\n[[Category:Monarchy in Canada]]\n[[Category:Monarchy in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:2012 in South Africa]]\n[[Category:2012 in Belize]]\n[[Category:2012 in Barbados]]\n[[Category:2012 in the Bahamas]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|60th anniversary of the accession of Queen Elizabeth II}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:Spirit of Chartwell.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Left to right, atop barge: (grouped at left) the [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Duke of Edinburgh]]; the [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|Duke of Cambridge]]; the [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|Duchess of Cambridge]]; [[Prince Harry]]; [[Queen Elizabeth II]]; (grouped at right) the [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|Duchess of Cornwall]]; the [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince of Wales]], aboard the [[MV Spirit of Chartwell|MV ''Spirit of Chartwell'']] during the Thames Diamond Jubilee Pageant on 3 June 2012]]\n\nThe year 2012 marked the '''Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II''' being the 60th anniversary of the accession of [[Queen Elizabeth II]] on 6 February 1952. The only [[Diamond jubilee|Diamond Jubilee]] celebration for any of Elizabeth's predecessors was in 1897, for the 60th anniversary of the 1837 accession of [[Queen Victoria#Diamond Jubilee|Queen Victoria]].\n\nFollowing the tradition of the Queen's [[Silver Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Silver]] and [[Golden Jubilee of Queen Elizabeth II|Golden Jubilees]], commemorative events were held throughout the [[Commonwealth of Nations]]. \n\nThe Queen and the [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Duke of Edinburgh]] toured the United Kingdom and other members of the Royal Family toured the rest of the Commonwealth as the monarch' representatives. The jubilee celebrations marked the beginning of the withdrawal of the Duke of Edinburgh from public life and a more prominent role for the Duke of Cambridge and Prince Harry in commonwealth affairs.\n\nNumerous events and tributes were held over the year and throughout the Commonwealth, culminating in a jubilee pageant held in London. The Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust was set up as a charitable foundation with a mission to leave a lasting legacy across the Commonwealth. <ref>{{cite web |title=Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust |url=https://www.jubileetribute.org/ |website=Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust}}</ref> Other projects included the [[Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Wood]] and the issuing of [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal|commemorative medals]].\n\n==Commonwealth-wide and beyond==\n{{Quote box| width=250px| border=1px| align=right| quote=In this special year, as I dedicate myself anew to your service, I hope we will all be reminded of the power of togetherness and the convening strength of family, friendship, and good neighbourliness, examples of which I have been fortunate to see throughout my reign and which my family and I look forward to seeing in many forms as we travel throughout the United Kingdom and the wider Commonwealth.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2012/TheQueensDiamondJubileemessage.aspx| last=Royal Household| title=The Queen's Diamond Jubilee message| date=6 February 2012| publisher=[[Queen's Printer]]| accessdate=8 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211124329/http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2012/TheQueensDiamondJubileemessage.aspx| archivedate=11 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>| salign=right| source=Elizabeth II, 2012}}\n\nAt the [[Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting 2011|2011 Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting]] in [[Perth]], Australia, [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British Prime Minister]] [[David Cameron]] announced the creation of the Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust, which was officially launched in the UK on 6 February 2012.<ref name=TF>{{cite press release|title=The Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust |publisher=Australian Government Publishing Service |date=7 February 2012 |url=http://www.pm.gov.au/press-office/queen-elizabeth-diamond-jubilee-trust |accessdate=11 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606234311/http://www.pm.gov.au/press-office/queen-elizabeth-diamond-jubilee-trust |archivedate=6 June 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Chaired by former British prime minister Sir [[John Major]], the trust was intended to support charitable organisations and projects across the [[Commonwealth of Nations]], focusing on areas such as cures for diseases and the promotion of all types of culture and education.<ref name=TF /> In early 2012, [[Prime Minister of Australia]] [[Julia Gillard]] announced the [[Monarchy of Australia|Australian Crown]]-[[Queen-in-Council|in-Council]] would make an A$5.4 million contribution to the trust and the [[Monarchy of New Zealand|New Zealand Crown]]-in-Council later made a similar $1 million donation.<ref name=TF /><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.msn.co.nz/nationalnews/8422619/nz-to-give-1m-to-diamond-jubilee| title=NZ to give $1m to Diamond Jubilee| date=20 February 2012| publisher=MSN NZ| accessdate=20 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525161812/http://news.msn.co.nz/nationalnews/8422619/nz-to-give-1m-to-diamond-jubilee| archivedate=25 May 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Canadian government announced in April that former prime minister [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]] would be Canada's representative to the organisation.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20120430/chretien-represents-canada-on-queens-jubilee-trust-120430/| title=Charles, Camilla to visit Canada in May; Chretien named envoy| date=30 April 2012| publisher=CTV| accessdate=30 April 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501101543/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20120430/chretien-represents-canada-on-queens-jubilee-trust-120430/| archivedate=1 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, a senior advisor was quoted as saying the Queen set two guidelines for the planning of her jubilee: the use of public funds should be minimised and people should not \"be forced to celebrate\".<ref name=GlobePomp>{{citation| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/queens-diamond-jubilee-poised-to-outdo-royal-weddings-pomp/article2327411/| last=Renzetti| first=Elizabeth| title=Queen's Diamond Jubilee poised to outdo Royal Wedding\u2019s pomp| date=5 February 2012| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| accessdate=6 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206094040/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/queens-diamond-jubilee-poised-to-outdo-royal-weddings-pomp/article2327411/| archivedate=6 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The first major international event of the jubilee celebrations was the [[Diamond Jubilee Pageant]], also branded ''The World Comes to Windsor'', a cavalcade held at [[Windsor Castle]] to celebrate the Queen's visits to and tours of over 250 countries, as well as her passion for horses. The show, which featured 550 horses and 1,100 performers from around the world, was performed in the evenings between 10 and 13 May, after the daytime events of the annual [[Royal Windsor Horse Show]] had taken place. The Queen attended the final night.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-berkshire-15544379| title=Windsor reveals 'spectacular' plans for Diamond Jubilee| date=1 November 2011| publisher=BBC| accessdate=21 April 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425125244/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-berkshire-15544379| archivedate=25 April 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/queen-elizabeth-II/8862164/Queens-Diamond-Jubilee-500-horses-from-around-the-world-will-put-on-equine-display-in-Windsor.html| last=Rayner| first=Gordon| title=Queen's Diamond Jubilee: 500 horses from around the world will put on equine display in Windsor| date=2 November 2011| newspaper=The Telegraph| accessdate=21 April 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603065328/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/queen-elizabeth-II/8862164/Queens-Diamond-Jubilee-500-horses-from-around-the-world-will-put-on-equine-display-in-Windsor.html| archivedate=3 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5i-Rx6x-d9E5b1l7UR2TN_m6u1N7Q?docId=N0092271333454487401A| title=Boyle to sing for Queen's pageant| date=3 April 2012| publisher=The Press Association| accessdate=21 April 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May, the Queen hosted an informal lunch at Windsor Castle for more than twenty current or former monarchs from other countries.<ref>{{citation| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9275284/The-Queen-welcomes-monarchs-to-Diamond-Jubilee-lunch.html| title=The Queen welcomes monarchs to Diamond Jubilee lunch| newspaper=The Telegraph| date=18 May 2012| accessdate=22 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120521103855/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9275284/The-Queen-welcomes-monarchs-to-Diamond-Jubilee-lunch.html| archivedate=21 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9274691/Jubilee-monarchs-lunch-the-full-guest-list.html| title=Jubilee monarchs' lunch: the full guest list| date=18 May 2012| newspaper=The Telegraph| accessdate=22 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523022345/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9274691/Jubilee-monarchs-lunch-the-full-guest-list.html| archivedate=23 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the evening of the same day, the [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince of Wales]] and the [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|Duchess of Cornwall]] hosted a dinner that most of the monarchs also attended, although the Queen herself was not present.<ref name=Donnely>{{citation| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/9277117/A-feast-fit-for-Kings-and-Queens-hosted-by-a-Prince.html| last=Donnely| first=Laura| title=A feast fit for Kings and Queens, hosted by a Prince| newspaper=The Telegraph| date=18 May 2012| accessdate=22 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522002727/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/9277117/A-feast-fit-for-Kings-and-Queens-hosted-by-a-Prince.html| archivedate=22 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Criticism was directed at the presence of the [[Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifa|King of Bahrain]] at the lunch, because of alleged repression of [[Bahraini uprising (2011\u2013present)|protests against the government of Bahrain]] in that country in 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18099937| title=Queen's lunch for monarchs attracts controversy| date=18 May 2012| publisher=BBC| accessdate=23 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522060516/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18099937| archivedate=22 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> In London, protesters against the King assembled outside Buckingham Palace during the dinner, although he did not attend that event.<ref name=Donnely />\n\n[[File:Queen at the Diamond Jubilee.JPG|thumb|left|[[Queen Elizabeth II]] arriving at [[St Paul's Cathedral]] for the service of thanksgiving on 5 June 2012]]\nThe lighting of thousands of beacons across the Commonwealth took place on 4 June. The number of beacons was originally set at 2,012; by the closing date for registrations, approximately 4,000 had been submitted in the United Kingdom alone.<ref name=DMBeacons>{{citation| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2138239/Red-fires-night-Royal-delight-Queen-use-huge-crystal-trigger-4-000-beacons-lit-celebrate-Diamond-Jubilee.html| last=Vinter| first=Phil| title=Red fires at night, Royal delight: Queen to use huge crystal to trigger last of 4,000 beacons lit to celebrate Diamond Jubilee| date=2 May 2012| newspaper=Daily Mail| accessdate=9 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130114023552/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2138239/Red-fires-night-Royal-delight-Queen-use-huge-crystal-trigger-4-000-beacons-lit-celebrate-Diamond-Jubilee.html| archivedate=14 January 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The first beacon of the Jubilee was lit on the grounds of Apifo'ou College in [[Nuku\u02bbalofa]], Tonga, by Tongan [[World Association of Girl Guides and Girl Scouts|girl]] and [[Boy Scout]]s using coconut sheath torches.<ref name=matangi>{{cite news| title=Tonga's guides and scouts light first Diamond Jubilee beacon| url=http://matangitonga.to/2012/06/05/tongas-guides-and-scouts-light-first-diamond-jubilee-beacon| work=[[Matangi Tonga]]| date=4 June 2012| accessdate=5 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120607221840/http://matangitonga.to/2012/06/05/tongas-guides-and-scouts-light-first-diamond-jubilee-beacon| archivedate=7 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Other nations, including [[Kenya]], [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[India]], [[Seychelles]], [[Sri Lanka]], and several [[Caribbean]] states, took part in the beacon lighting. The world's most remote beacon was lit in [[Tristan da Cunha]] in the south Atlantic, using [[Invasive species|invasive, non-native plant]]s to fuel the fire.<ref name=birdwatch>{{cite news| title=Burning aliens for the Queen| url=http://www.birdwatch.co.uk/channel/newsitem.asp?c=11&cate=__12179| date=4 June 2012| publisher=Birdwatch| accessdate=5 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608114110/http://www.birdwatch.co.uk/channel/newsitem.asp?c=11&cate=__12179| archivedate=8 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=tpa>{{cite news| title=Remote islanders join Jubilee party| url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5jCSPlwfBEZNFt7f4p0iodwYCRe7A?docId=N0060401338688550812A| date=4 June 2012| publisher=Press Association| accessdate=5 June 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, British servicemen and women wounded in battle and individuals representing charities carried beacons to the summits of the UK's four highest peaks. One beacon was lit at [[Treetops Hotel]] in [[Aberdare National Park]] in Kenya, where the Queen was at the moment of her accession to the throne.<ref name=DMBeacons /> The Queen lit the beacon outside [[Buckingham Palace]] at 10:30 pm,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diamondjubileebeacons.co.uk/pages/lighting_times_173419.cfm |title=The Queen's Diamond Jubilee Beacons > Beacon Lighting Times |publisher=[[Queen's Printer]] |accessdate=9 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507050246/http://www.diamondjubileebeacons.co.uk/pages/lighting_times_173419.cfm |archivedate=7 May 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.canada.com/news/Wounded+soldiers+carry+beacons+Queen+diamond+jubilee/6073863/story.html| last=Agence France Presse| title=Wounded soldiers to carry beacons for Queen's diamond jubilee| date=30 January 2012| publisher=canada.com| accessdate=9 May 2012}}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=SheriffIsInTown |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> by inserting a large, specially made, diamond-cut crystal into a receptacle.<ref name=DMBeacons /> The lighting proceeded until the final beacon was lit in Canada eight hours later.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.canada.com/news/Diamond+Jubilee+will+globe+alight/6559106/story.html| last=Rainey| first=Sarah| title=Diamond Jubilee will set the globe alight| date=3 May 2012| publisher=canada.com| accessdate=28 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617155449/http://www.canada.com/news/Diamond+Jubilee+will+globe+alight/6559106/story.html| archivedate=17 June 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Queen's husband, [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]], was hospitalised with a [[Urinary tract infection|bladder infection]] on 4 June and thus was not able to attend any of the official events. In his speech given at the conclusion of the Diamond Jubilee Concert, the Prince of Wales commented on the sadness of his father's absence and urged the crowd to cheer loud enough for the Duke to hear in hospital.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9311477/The-Queens-Diamond-Jubilee-Concert-Loudest-cheer-for-the-Duke-of-Edinburgh.html| last=Bowater| first=Donna| title=The Queen's Diamond Jubilee Concert: Loudest cheer for the Duke of Edinburgh| date=5 June 2012| newspaper=Daily Telegraph| accessdate=24 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620033457/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9311477/The-Queens-Diamond-Jubilee-Concert-Loudest-cheer-for-the-Duke-of-Edinburgh.html| archivedate=20 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]], stated after visiting his father that the latter was watching the celebrations on television.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18331680| title=Prince Philip 'feeling better'| date=5 June 2012| publisher=BBC| accessdate=24 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617041902/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18331680| archivedate=17 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Queen visited the Duke the following day.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18342301| title=Queen visits Prince Philip in hospital| date=6 June 2012| publisher=BBC| accessdate=24 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120618003110/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18342301| archivedate=18 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThat same evening, a pre-recorded message by the Queen was released and aired on television around the world.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18333624| title=Diamond jubilee: Queen \"humbled by experience\"| date=5 June 2012| publisher=BBC| accessdate=24 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617195123/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18333624| archivedate=17 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Commonwealth realms==\n\n===Australia===\n[[Quentin Bryce]], the [[Governor-General of Australia]], announced that the Diamond Jubilee would be celebrated \"with a host of national and community events throughout the Commonwealth.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gg.gov.au/announcement.php/view/id/50/title/queens-birthday-message |last=Office of the Governor General of Australia |authorlink=Governor General of Australia |title=Queen's Birthday Message |publisher=Australian Government Publishing Service|accessdate=15 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314025232/http://www.gg.gov.au/announcement.php/view/id/50/title/queens-birthday-message |archivedate=14 March 2012 }}</ref> In a similar vein, it was said in late 2011 that the government of [[Queensland]] was planning to declare a holiday in June 2012 to mark the jubilee.\n\nThe [[Royal Australian Mint]] announced in August 2011 that it would be releasing a silver proof 50-cent coin to celebrate the Queen's Diamond Jubilee.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ramint.gov.au/media/noticeboard/2011/downloads/20110907a_checklist.pdf| last=Royal Australian Mint| authorlink=Royal Australian Mint| title=2012 Product Launch for the Royal Australian Mint| publisher=Royal Australian Mint| accessdate=18 September 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124145655/http://www.ramint.gov.au/media/noticeboard/2011/downloads/20110907a_checklist.pdf| archivedate=24 November 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Australia Post issued a series of special stamps to mark the occasion.\n\nPaying tribute to Elizabeth II as [[Queen of Australia]] in the [[Australian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] on 6 February 2012, [[Prime Minister of Australia]] [[Julia Gillard]] stated the Queen was a revered figure in Australia.<ref>Hansard, Australian Parliament, 6 February 2012</ref> Gillard also announced that she would on 4 June light a beacon atop [[Parliament House, Canberra|Parliament House]] and that a street in the parliamentary triangle in [[Canberra]] would be renamed ''Queen Elizabeth Terrace''.<ref name=TF /> Meanwhile, [[Premier of Western Australia|Western Australian Premier]] [[Colin Barnett]] announced on 28 May that a new waterfront development in [[Perth]] would be named [[Elizabeth Quay]] in the Queen's honour.\n\nA detachment of the [[New South Wales Police Force|New South Wales Mounted Police]] performed at the [[Diamond Jubilee Pageant]] held at Windsor Castle in May 2012. At the end of the same month, Prince Charles presented Diamond Jubilee medals to those in the [[Victoria Cross and George Cross Association]], including three Australian Victoria Cross recipients.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2152488/Charles-Camilla-meet-28-living-VCs-GCs-ahead-Diamond-Jubilee.html| publisher=Associated Newspapers Ltd| last=Hardman| first=Robert| title=Charles and Camilla meet 28 living VCs and GCs ahead of Diamond Jubilee| date=31 May 2012| newspaper=Daily Mail| accessdate=7 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20120601164915/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2152488/Charles-Camilla-meet-28-living-VCs-GCs-ahead-Diamond-Jubilee.html| archivedate=1 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA special [[Ecumenism|ecumenical]] service was conducted in [[St James' Church, Sydney]], at which the invited preacher was Cardinal [[George Pell]] and the [[Governor of New South Wales]], [[Marie Bashir]], was the guest of honour. The [[Anglican Church of Australia]] also held a service of prayer and thanksgiving to commemorate the Diamond Jubilee at [[St John's Cathedral (Brisbane)|St John's Cathedral]] in Brisbane, on 20 May 2012. The service was welcomed by [[Phillip Aspinall]], Anglican Archbishop of Brisbane, and the Homily was given by [[Mark Coleridge]], Catholic Archbishop of Brisbane. The guest of honour was the [[Governor of Queensland]], [[Penelope Wensley]], and [[Ian Walker (politician)|Ian Walker]] represented the Queensland Cabinet.\n\nBetween 5 and 10 November 2012, [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], and [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]], toured the country, travelling to Queensland, Victoria, South Australia, New South Wales, and the Australian Capital Territory.<ref>{{citation| last=Viellaris| first=Renee| url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/bligh-shakes-up-public-holidays/story-e6freoof-1226186716689| title=Bligh shakes up public holidays, gifts Queenslanders another day off| date=6 November 2011| newspaper=The Courier-Mail| accessdate=6 November 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420135604/http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/bligh-shakes-up-public-holidays/story-e6freoof-1226186716689| archivedate=20 April 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=BBCJplans>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16174233| title=Royal Family plans for Queen's Diamond Jubilee unveiled| date=14 December 2011| publisher=BBC| accessdate=14 December 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111214181456/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16174233| archivedate=14 December 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.thediamondjubilee.org/commonwealth-visits-2012.htm| title=Commonwealth Visits in 2012| publisher=Royal Household| date=6 June 2012| accessdate=6 June 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref><ref name=TelegraphPoW>{{citation| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/prince-charles/9552611/Prince-of-Wales-and-Duchess-of-Cornwall-to-make-Australian-visit.html| title=Prince of Wales and Duchess of Cornwall to make Australian visit| date=19 September 2012| newspaper=The Telegraph| accessdate=21 September 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921114200/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/prince-charles/9552611/Prince-of-Wales-and-Duchess-of-Cornwall-to-make-Australian-visit.html| archivedate=21 September 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Bahamas===\n[[Prince Harry]] toured The Bahamas. There, he attended a reception for youth leaders and met with [[Governor-General of the Bahamas]] Sir [[Arthur Foulkes]]. The Prince attended an outdoor ceremony where children's schools, clubs, and associations presented themselves and delivered a speech at [[Government House, The Bahamas|Government House]],<ref>{{citation| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/prince-harry/9125017/Prince-Harry-praises-Bahamas-schoolchildren-on-Jubilee-tour.html| title=Prince Harry praises Bahamas schoolchildren on Jubilee tour| date=5 March 2012| newspaper=The Telegraph| accessdate=6 March 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306043400/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/prince-harry/9125017/Prince-Harry-praises-Bahamas-schoolchildren-on-Jubilee-tour.html| archivedate=6 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> where he stated \"I stand before you with a deep sense of pride at being asked to convey to you a message of good wishes from The Queen on the occasion of her Diamond Jubilee.\" He also took part in maritime exercises organised by the [[Royal Bahamas Defence Force]] and toured [[Harbour Island, Bahamas|Harbour Island]].<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2110094/Prince-Harrys-Diamond-Jubilee-tour-Harry-meets-Miss-Bahamas-day-beauty-queen-declared-marry-him.html| last=English| first=Rebecca| title=When Harry met Miss Bahamas: Couple get acquainted a day after beauty queen declared she would marry the prince| date=6 March 2012| newspaper=Daily Mail| accessdate=6 March 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20120307095154/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2110094/Prince-Harrys-Diamond-Jubilee-tour-Harry-meets-Miss-Bahamas-day-beauty-queen-declared-marry-him.html| archivedate=7 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Barbados===\n[[File:National Heroes Square, Bridgetown.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Parliament of Barbados]], where the [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|Earl of Wessex]] read to a joint sitting of the legislature a message from [[Elizabeth II]], [[Monarchy of Barbados|Queen of Barbados]], on 23 February 2012, to mark the Queen's diamond jubilee]]\n\nTo mark Elizabeth II's 60 years as Barbados' monarch\u2014as Queen of the United Kingdom between 1952 and 1966 and as [[Monarchy of Barbados|Queen of Barbados]] thereafter\u2014the country hosted the Queen's youngest son and his wife, [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|the Earl]] and [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex|Countess of Wessex]], between 23 and 24 February 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7314| first=Sharon| last=Lynch| title=Royal Visit To Mark Queen\u2019s Diamond Jubilee| date=25 January 2012| newspaper=Barbados Government Information Service (BGIS)| accessdate=7 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129203218/http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7314| archivedate=29 January 2016| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The tour began with the Earl and Countess arriving, aboard [[RFA Fort Rosalie (A385)|RFA ''Fort Rosalie'']], at the [[Port of Bridgetown|Deep Water Harbour]] of Bridgetown,<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.trinidadexpress.com/news/Pomp_at_port__as_British__royals_roll_in-140821023.html| last=Neaves| first=Julien| title=Pomp at port as British royals roll in| date=29 February 2012| newspaper=Trinidad Express| accessdate=29 February 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302184853/http://www.trinidadexpress.com/news/Pomp_at_port__as_British__royals_roll_in-140821023.html| archive-date=2 March 2012| url-status=dead}}</ref> where Barbadian military personnel were given inspection.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.caribbean360.com/index.php/news/barbados_news/556952.html| title=Red carpet welcome for Royal Couple| date=24 February 2012| publisher=Caribbean360| accessdate=25 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302000703/http://www.caribbean360.com/index.php/news/barbados_news/556952.html| archivedate=2 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=23010| title=Barbados leg of Diamond Jubilee gets underway| date=24 February 2012| newspaper=[[The Barbados Advocate]]| accessdate=25 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202222244/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=23010| archivedate=2 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite video| people=Esther Byer-Suckoo| title=Barbadian Minister Esther Byer-Suckoo briefs Press on the Royal Visit| medium=Video| publisher=News Distribution Network| location=Bridgetown| date=21 February 2012| url=http://landing.newsinc.com/shared/video.html?freewheel=90640&sitesection=nationnewslocal&VID=23579300| accessdate=24 February 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150502134244/http://landing.newsinc.com/shared/video.html?freewheel=90640&sitesection=nationnewslocal&VID=23579300| archive-date=2 May 2015| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=22983| title=All systems go!... for whirlwind two-day official Royal visit| date=22 February 2012| newspaper=The Barbados Advocate| accessdate=24 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120721005646/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=22983| archivedate=21 July 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> To a joint sitting of the [[Parliament of Barbados]], the Earl read a written message from the Queen,<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/royal-sitting/| title=Royal Sitting| date=24 February 2012| newspaper=[[The Daily Nation (Barbados)|The Daily Nation]]| accessdate=25 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202230606/http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/royal-sitting/| archivedate=2 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> in which the monarch stated she has taken note of the level of development Barbados had achieved during its 45 years of independence and called the country a model small state for others around the world.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7553| last=Carrington| first=J.| title=Queen Elizabeth II Proud of Barbados' Achievements| date=24 February 2012| publisher=Barbados Government Information Service| accessdate=24 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506040523/http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7553| archivedate=6 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| title=Prince Edward praises island on progress| last=Parris| first=Dawne| url=http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/prince-edward-praises-island-on-progress/| date=24 February 2012| newspaper=[[The Daily Nation (Barbados)|The Daily Nation]]| accessdate=24 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227223233/http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/prince-edward-praises-island-on-progress/| archivedate=27 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Parliamentary officials responded with thanks to the Queen for her service to the country and Barbadians and invited her to the island to celebrate the 375th anniversary of the establishment of the Barbadian parliament in 2014.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7536| title=Barbados Grateful To Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II| first=Julie| last=Carrington| date=23 February 2012| publisher=Barbados Government Information Service| accessdate=24 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506040203/http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7536| archivedate=6 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| title=Queen invited for 375th milestone| last=Parris| first=Dawne| url=http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/queen-invited-for-375th-milestone/| date=24 February 2012| newspaper=[[The Daily Nation (Barbados)|The Daily Nation]]| accessdate=24 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228003010/http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/queen-invited-for-375th-milestone/| archivedate=28 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The visiting royal couple opened an exhibit at the [[University of the West Indies]], [[Cave Hill Campus]], and an official state dinner and reception was held at [[Government House, Barbados|Government House]] in the evening.<ref name=BarVisitSun>{{citation| url=http://www.bajansunonline.com/barbados-royal-visit-to-mark-queens-diamond-jubilee/| last=Lynch| first=Sharon| title=Barbados: Royal Visit To Mark Queen's Diamond Jubilee| date=27 January 2012| newspaper=Bajan Sun Online| accessdate=6 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120719162855/http://www.bajansunonline.com/barbados-royal-visit-to-mark-queens-diamond-jubilee/| archivedate=19 July 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://landing.newsinc.com/shared/video.html?freewheel=90640&sitesection=nationnewslocal&VID=23580671| title=VIDEO: The Earl and Countess of Wessex Prince Edward and his wife Sophie, visit Parliament and Cave Hill Campus| author=TRH| date=23 February 2012| publisher=[[The Daily Nation (Barbados)|The Daily Nation]]| accessdate=24 February 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150502121250/http://landing.newsinc.com/shared/video.html?freewheel=90640&sitesection=nationnewslocal&VID=23580671| archive-date=2 May 2015| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe following day, the Countess visited the Albert C. Graham Children's Development Centre at Ladymeade Gardens, while the Earl presented eight [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award|Duke of Edinburgh's Gold Award]]s to Barbadian youth at a dedication ceremony. Directly following, the couple travelled together to a ceremony to commemorate the Diamond Jubilee, where a plaque was unveiled at the [[Kensington Oval]] [[List of Test cricket grounds|cricket stadium]].<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7548| title=Royal Sitting| date=24 February 2012| newspaper=The Daily Nation| accessdate=25 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506040456/http://www.gisbarbados.gov.bb/index.php?categoryid=13&p2_articleid=7548| archivedate=6 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=RV>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=23031| title=Royal Visit| date=25 February 2012| newspaper=The Barbados Advocate| accessdate=25 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202225514/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=23031| archivedate=2 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Other events included the Earl and Countess lunching with Prime Minister [[Freundel Stuart]] at his residence, [[Ilaro Court]], and touring several areas of Bridgetown that were added to [[UNESCO]]'s list of [[World Heritage Site]]s in 2011.<ref name=BarVisitSun /><ref name=RV />\n\nAs in other Commonwealth realms, a set of commemorative Diamond Jubilee stamps were released by the Barbados Postal Service.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://barbadospostal.com/home/3052.html| title=Barbados: Now Available: Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Commemorative Stamp Issue| publisher=Barbados Postal Service| accessdate=18 November 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20121118020955/http://barbadospostal.com/home/3052.html| archivedate=18 November 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> An [[ecumenical]] thanksgiving service was held at the St. Mary's Anglican Church in [[Bridgetown]] on 3 June and a beacon lighting at the [[Garrison Savannah]] the following day,<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=25108| title=Barbados gives thanks| date=4 June 2012| newspaper=The Barbados Advocate| accessdate=16 June 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130117153545/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=25108| archivedate=17 January 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=24890| title=Thanksgiving Service for Queen\u2019s Diamond Jubilee| date=24 May 2012| newspaper=The Barbados Advocate| accessdate=25 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120724192735/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=24890| archivedate=24 July 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=24902| title=Barbadians urged not miss Beacon Lighting Ceremony| date=24 May 2012| newspaper=The Barbados Advocate| accessdate=25 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120718134106/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=24902| archivedate=18 July 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> where an official [[Trooping of the Colour]] was performed by the [[Barbados Defence Force]] and [[military tattoo]] performed by the [[Royal Barbados Police Force]].<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=25129| title=Garrison Savannah a special place| date=5 June 2012| newspaper=The Barbados Advocate| accessdate=16 June 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130117135412/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=25129| archivedate=17 January 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Members of the Barbados Boys Scout Association with high honours were chosen to aid in the actual beacon lighting.<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=25128| title=Beacon lit for Queen\u2019s jubilee| date=6 June 2012| newspaper=The Barbados Advocate| accessdate=16 June 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130117165049/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=local&NewsID=25128| archivedate=17 January 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Belize===\nIn Belize, the [[Governor-General of Belize|Governor-General]]-[[Queen-in-Council|in-Council]] and the Belize Tourism Board organised a tour of the country by [[Prince Harry]], between 2 and 3 March 2012, as part of the country's celebrations of Elizabeth II's 60th year as monarch of Belize, first as [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|Queen of the United Kingdom]] and then, after 1981, as [[Monarchy of Belize|Queen of Belize]]. Harry visited [[Belmopan]] and [[San Ignacio (town)|San Ignacio]] where ceremonies and events had less emphasis on state protocol.<ref name=Belizian>{{cite news| url=http://belizean.com/prince-harrys-belize-schedule-released-1046/| title=Prince Harry's Belize Schedule Released|date=17 February 2012| publisher=Belizian| accessdate=1 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref> In the capital, Harry unveiled a series of commemorative stamps issued by the Belize Postal Service,<ref name=BelStamps>{{citation| url=http://www.guardian.bz/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4378%3Acommemorative-stamps-for-elizabeths-60th-year-as-queen-&catid=40%3Apolitics&Itemid=90| last=Williams| first=Shane D.| title=Commemorative Stamps for Elizabeth's 60th Year as Queen| date=9 February 2012| newspaper=The Guardian| accessdate=11 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231002250/http://www.guardian.bz/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4378%3Acommemorative-stamps-for-elizabeths-60th-year-as-queen-&catid=40%3Apolitics&Itemid=90| archivedate=31 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> attended the city's street festival, and dedicated a street as ''Queen Elizabeth II Boulevard'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-17248431|title=Diamond Jubilee: Prince Harry visits Mayan ruins in Belize|date=3 March 2012|publisher=BBC|accessdate=6 March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305214530/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-17248431|archivedate=5 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> where he delivered a speech on the sovereign's behalf.\n\n===Canada===\n[[File:Can-Diamond-Jubilee-logo.jpg|thumb|right|The official emblem of the [[Monarchy of Canada|Queen of Canada]]'s Diamond Jubilee]]\n====Planning====\nForethought on the anniversary began as early as April 2007, when then-Secretary of State for Canadian Heritage [[Jason Kenney]] requested the various [[Lieutenant Governor (Canada)|lieutenant governors]] begin preparations for the jubilee.<ref>{{Citation| last=Kenney| first=Jason| author-link=Jason Kenney| date=23 April 2007| contribution=Lieutenant Governors Meeting| editor-last=Department of Canadian Heritage| editor-link=Department of Canadian Heritage| title=Speeches > The Honourable Jason Kenney| place=Regina| publication-place=Ottawa| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pc-ch/minstr/arc_disc-spch/kenney/2007/20070423-eng.cfm| accessdate=29 November 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611163321/http://www.pch.gc.ca/pc-ch/minstr/arc_disc-spch/kenney/2007/20070423-eng.cfm| archivedate=11 June 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Three years later, the question of a national holiday to mark the jubilee was raised in the media and a series of official announcements were made by the Minister of Canadian Heritage.<ref>{{Cite news| publisher=CBC| date=6 January 2010| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/pointofview/2010/01/diamond-jubilee-should-we-get-a-national-holiday.html| title=Diamond Jubilee: should we get a national holiday?| accessdate=4 June 2010| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100811045757/http://www.cbc.ca/news/pointofview/2010/01/diamond-jubilee-should-we-get-a-national-holiday.html| archivedate=11 August 2010| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Canadian Secretary to the Queen|Secretary to the Queen]], [[Kevin S. MacLeod]], was charged by the [[Queen-in-Council|Governor General-in-Council]] to head the Diamond Jubilee Committee (DJC)\u2014a 14-member group of individuals drawn from the provincial and territorial governments, non-governmental organisations, officials from the Departments of [[Department of Citizenship and Immigration Canada|Citizenship and Immigration]], [[Department of National Defence (Canada)|National Defence]], and [[Department of Canadian Heritage|Canadian Heritage]] (DCH), and the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]<ref name=CBC$>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2012/01/09/pol-queen-diamond-jubilee.html?cmp=rss| last=The Canadian Press| title=Conservatives balked at cost of Queen's Diamond Jubilee| date=9 January 2012| publisher=CBC| accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref>\u2014that oversaw the organisation of the country's [[f\u00eate]]s for Elizabeth II's 60 years as [[Monarchy of Canada|Queen of Canada]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=PM announces the appointment of Kevin MacLeod as Canadian Secretary to the Queen |publisher=Office of the Prime Minister |date=1 April 2009 |url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=2501 |accessdate=29 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090405014141/http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=2501 |archivedate=5 April 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> Similarly, [[Premier of Alberta]] [[Ed Stelmach]] in February 2011 tasked the Alberta Chief of Protocol and the Private Secretary to the [[Lieutenant Governor of Alberta]] to form and head a committee to develop plans for the province's Diamond Jubilee celebrations.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://alberta.ca/home/NewsFrame.cfm?ReleaseID=%2Facn%2F%2F201102%2F29852ED3E4C18-FF66-8F19-0627D5EAD11E39EE.html| last=Government of Alberta| title=Planning launches for Alberta's Diamond Jubilee celebrations| date=3 February 2011| publisher=Queen's Printer for Alberta| accessdate=29 January 2012}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> As with other royal events, the DCH played a large role in organisation and planning. $7.5 million of resources, granted to the DCH in the previous budget approved by the federal parliament, was allocated for federal jubilee celebrations, education and awareness, and distribution to community groups; $2 million was for events in the Queen's honour and $3.7 million was allocated for the Diamond Jubilee medal.<ref name=CBC$ /> The total amount was reduced by [[Minister of Canadian Heritage]] [[James Moore (Canadian politician)|James Moore]] from the DJC's original estimate of $8.8 million.<ref name=CBC$ />\n\n====Pre-events====\n[[File:Diamond Jubilee of Queen Elizabeth II - Canadian Senate Foyer (14579919150).jpg|thumb|left|The Diamond Jubilee Window in the Senate foyer in the [[Centre Block]] of Canada's parliament. It depicts Elizabeth II along with [[Queen Victoria]], who also celebrated a diamond jubilee.]]\nThe Queen, on 3 July 2010, dedicated the Queen Elizabeth II Gardens outside [[Government House (Manitoba)|her official residence in Manitoba]] and there planted an Amber Jubilee [[Physocarpus|Ninebark]] shrub, the [[cultivar]] having been created specifically for the Diamond Jubilee.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.royaltour.gc.ca/itiner/itiner-eng.cfm| last=Department of Canadian Heritage| authorlink=Department of Canadian Heritage| title=2010 Royal Tour > Itinerary for 2010 Royal Tour of Canada| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=9 August 2010| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619144300/http://royaltour.gc.ca/itiner/itiner-eng.cfm| archivedate=19 June 2010| df=dmy-all}}</ref> At [[Rideau Hall]] in Ottawa, she also, on 30 June, unveiled a commemorative [[stained glass]] window depicting herself and Queen Victoria with their respective [[royal cypher]]s and renditions of the [[Centre Block]] of the [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian parliament]] during the reign of each monarch.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/About/Senate/jubilee/crown-e.htm| last=Parliament of Canada| title=The Diamond Jubilee Window: A Celebration of the Crown in Canada| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=15 April 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312084326/http://www.parl.gc.ca/About/Senate/jubilee/crown-e.htm| archivedate=12 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last=Foot| first=Richard| title=Queen Elizabeth in Halifax| publisher=Global News| date=29 June 2010| url=http://news.globaltv.com/canada/Queen+Elizabeth+tour+Canada/3208763/story.html| accessdate=1 July 2010| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607195024/http://news.globaltv.com/canada/Queen+Elizabeth+tour+Canada/3208763/story.html| archivedate=7 June 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Foot |first=Richard |title=Queen Elizabeth to skip Quebec on Canadian tour |newspaper=Montreal Gazette |date=27 June 2010 |url=https://montrealgazette.com/Queen+skip+Quebec+Canadian+tour/3208778/story.html |accessdate=1 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100630162832/http://www.montrealgazette.com/Queen+skip+Quebec+Canadian+tour/3208778/story.html |archivedate=30 June 2010 }}</ref> The window, a gift from the [[Senate of Canada|Canadian Senate]], was installed above the Senate entrance to the Centre Block and dedicated by [[Governor General of Canada|Governor General]] [[David Johnston]] on 7 February 2012.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14416| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=Governor General to Attend the Dedication Ceremony of the Diamond Jubilee Window in Senate Foyer| date=6 February 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nA [[corbel]] within the Sovereigns' Arches of the [[Centre Block#Senate foyer|Senate foyer]] was sculpted into a rendition of the Queen and unveiled on 9 December 2010 by the Governor General.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=13980&lan=eng| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| authorlink=Governor General of Canada|title=Governor General to Unveil the Corbel of Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II| date=7 December 2010| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|accessdate=7 December 2010}}</ref> The [[Royal Canadian Mint]] also issued an \"extensive set\" of coins to mark the anniversary.<ref>{{Citation|last=Canadian Press|title=Canadian mint marking royal wedding with collector coins|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=2 March 2011|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/royalfamily/royalwedding/article/947234--canadian-mint-marking-royal-wedding-with-collector-coins|accessdate=8 March 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110305044234/http://www.thestar.com/news/world/royalfamily/royalwedding/article/947234--canadian-mint-marking-royal-wedding-with-collector-coins|archivedate=5 March 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Further, the [[Royal Regiment of Canadian Artillery]] (RRCA) in 2011 presented the Queen, their captain-general since 1952, with a diamond and gold brooch, made by [[Birks & Mayors]] in the form of the regiment's cap badge, and announced the creation of The Captain General's Diamond Jubilee Bursary Award for educational activities of members of the RRCA and family.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/895213/her-majesty-the-queen-receives-a-brooch-produced-by-canadian-jeweller-birks-in-honour-of-her-diamond-jubilee-as-captain-general-of-the-royal-regiment-| title=Her Majesty the Queen Receives a Brooch Produced by Canadian Jeweller Birks in Honour of her Diamond Jubilee as Captain General of the Royal Regiment of Canadian Artillery| date=14 December 2011| publisher=Canada Newswire| accessdate=15 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614170610/http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/895213/her-majesty-the-queen-receives-a-brooch-produced-by-canadian-jeweller-birks-in-honour-of-her-diamond-jubilee-as-captain-general-of-the-royal-regiment-| archivedate=14 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Diamond Jubilee Week====\nDiamond Jubilee Week began on [[Accession Day]] (6 February) 2012.<ref name=CNW>{{Citation| title=Government of Canada Unveils Plans for Her Majesty's Diamond Jubilee Celebrations| agency=Office of the Prime Minister| date=6 December 2011| url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/890901/government-of-canada-unveils-plans-for-her-majesty-s-diamond-jubilee-celebrations| publisher=Canada Newswire| accessdate=8 December 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311062132/http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/890901/government-of-canada-unveils-plans-for-her-majesty-s-diamond-jubilee-celebrations| archivedate=11 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> That day, the [[Royal standards of Canada#Sovereign's standard|monarch's personal standard for Canada]] was unfurled at Rideau Hall and on [[Parliament Hill]], as well as at provincial [[Government Houses in Canada|royal residences]] and [[Legislative Assemblies of Canadian provinces and territories|legislatures across the country]];<ref>{{cite web| url=http://lt.gov.ns.ca/news-events/entry/diamond-jubilee-events/| last=Office of the Lieutenant Governor of Nova Scotia| title=Media > News and Events > Diamond Jubilee Events| date=23 January 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Nova Scotia| accessdate=16 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304003111/http://lt.gov.ns.ca/news-events/entry/diamond-jubilee-events/| archivedate=4 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.chrisd.ca/blog/50254/manitoba-queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee-celebrations/| archive-url=https://archive.today/20120731184335/http://www.chrisd.ca/blog/50254/manitoba-queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee-celebrations/| url-status=dead| archive-date=31 July 2012| title=Manitoba Celebrating Queen's Diamond Jubilee| date=6 February 2012| publisher=ChrisD| accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=PEI>{{cite web| url=http://www.gov.pe.ca/newsroom/index.php3?number=news&newsnumber=8229&dept=&lang=E| last=Office of the Lieutenant Governor of Prince Edward Island| title=Diamond Jubilee Celebrations Begin| date=3 February 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Prince Edward Island| accessdate=29 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606125718/http://www.gov.pe.ca/newsroom/index.php3?number=news&newsnumber=8229&dept=&lang=E| archivedate=6 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=NWT>{{cite web| url=http://www.executive.gov.nt.ca/offices/protocol/NWTJubileeEvents/index.html| last=Northwest Territories Executive| title=Department of Executive > Offices of the Executive > Protocol > NWT Jubilee Events| publisher=Government of the Northwest Territories Publications| accessdate=26 July 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703065742/http://www.executive.gov.nt.ca/offices/protocol/NWTJubileeEvents/index.html| archivedate=3 July 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> permission was granted by the Queen to break the usual protocol of flying the banner only where the sovereign is physically present.<ref name=CTVJubilee /> At noon on the same day, the [[Peace Tower#Carillon|Peace Tower carillon]] played a tribute to Elizabeth II.{{refn|This included the tunes \"[[O Canada]]\", \"Westminster\" (for carillon), \"[[And did those feet in ancient time|Jerusalem]]\", \"This Canada of Ours\", \"[[Andante (tempo)|Andante]]\" (from Sonata for 47 Bells), and \"[[God Save the Queen]]\".<ref name=Music />|group=n|name=Music}}<ref name=Music>{{cite web| url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/About/House/Collections/carillon/programme-e.htm| last=Parliament of Canada| title=The House of Commons Heritage Collection > Carillon > Programme| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=6 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504144051/http://www.parl.gc.ca/About/House/Collections/carillon/programme-e.htm| archivedate=4 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Prime Minister and the leader of the [[Liberal Party of Canada]] issued statements commending the Queen for her six decades of \"dedicated service to our country, to the Commonwealth and to the world.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.liberal.ca/newsroom/news-release/statement-by-liberal-leader-bob-rae-on-the-queen%e2%80%99s-diamond-jubilee/| last=Rae| first=Bob| authorlink=Bob Rae| title=Statement by Liberal Leader Bob Rae on the Queen\u2019s Diamond Jubilee| date=6 February 2012| publisher=Liberal Party of Canada| accessdate=26 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215100904/http://www.liberal.ca/newsroom/news-release/statement-by-liberal-leader-bob-rae-on-the-queen%E2%80%99s-diamond-jubilee| archivedate=15 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=4619| last=Harper| first=Stephen| authorlink=Stephen Harper| title=The Queen's Diamond Jubilee: a Canadian celebration| date=6 February 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=26 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120808071318/http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=4619| archivedate=8 August 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Royal Standard of Canada.svg|thumb|right|The royal standard of Elizabeth II, Queen of Canada, which was flown at various locations across Canada during Diamond Jubilee Week.]]\nAlso on 6 and 7 February, the first of the 60,000 Canadian [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]]s to be distributed to citizens and permanent residents were handed out by [[Lieutenant governor (Canada)|lieutenant governors]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lieutenant-gouverneur.qc.ca/salle-de-presse/allocutions/6-02-12.htm| last=Duchense| first=Pierre| title=Allocution de Son Honneur l'honorable Pierre Duchesne, lieutenant-gouverneur du Qu\u00e9bec, \u00e0 l'occasion de la c\u00e9r\u00e9monie de remise de la M\u00e9daille du jubil\u00e9 de diamant de Sa Majest\u00e9 la reine Elizabeth II| date=6 February 2012| publisher=Bureau du Lieutenant-gouverneur du Qu\u00e9bec| language=French| accessdate=29 June 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521221423/http://www.lieutenant-gouverneur.qc.ca/salle-de-presse/allocutions/6-02-12.htm| archivedate=21 May 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Commissioner#Canada|commissioners]],<ref name=NWT /> and other dignitaries across the country; 60 individuals were given theirs personally by the Governor General at Rideau Hall.<ref name=PEI /><ref name=CTVJubilee>{{cite news|url=http://edmonton.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20120206/diamond-jubilee-celebrations-120206/20120206/?hub=EdmontonHome |title=Canada kicks off festivities for Queen's jubilee |date=6 February 2012 |publisher=CTV |accessdate=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318190237/http://edmonton.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20120206/diamond-jubilee-celebrations-120206/20120206/?hub=EdmontonHome |archivedate=18 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14414| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=Sixty Canadians are Honoured During the Inaugural Presentation Ceremony of the Diamond Jubilee Medal at Rideau Hall| date=6 February 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref> All federal [[Member of Parliament (Canada)|Members of Parliament]] (MPs) received the award automatically and a few refused, some because they belonged to the [[Quebec sovereignty movement|Quebec separatist]] [[Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]],<ref name=WFP>{{citation|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/canada/breakingnews/jubilee-hoopla-a-royal-pain-for-some-anti-monarchists-who-question-cost-138800719.html|last=Rakobowchuk| first=Peter| title=Jubilee hoopla a royal pain for some anti-monarchists who question cost| date=6 February 2012|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press| accessdate=10 February 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref> and one because he felt the money being spent by the Crown on jubilee events and markers was a waste.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/canada/breakingnews/canada-kicks-off-four-months-of-celebrations-for-queens-diamond-jubilee--138871859.html|last=McQuigge| first=Michelle| title=Canada kicks off four months of celebrations for Queen's Diamond Jubilee| date=7 February 2012|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press| accessdate=9 February 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref> [[Citizens for a Canadian Republic]] claimed that day that the government's spending of money on the Queen's jubilee was to be expected \"from the personality cult dynasties of North Korea or Syria\".<ref>{{cite press release| title=Jubilee celebrations raise questions of priorities| publisher=Citizens for a Canadian Republic| date=6 February 2012| url=http://www.canadian-republic.ca/media_release_02-06-12-B.html| accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> The [[Saint-Jean-Baptiste Society]] claimed it would stage \"counter-celebrations\".<ref name=WFP />\n\nIn [[Nova Scotia]], the provincial government announced the establishment of educational programmes related to the Queen and her role in Canadian government and the one-time award of the $2000 Diamond Jubilee Award Scholarship to 60 Grade 12 students in the province.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://gov.ns.ca/iga/djedu.asp| last=Government of Nova Scotia| title=The Diamond Jubilee of Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II > Diamond Jubilee Education Initiatives| publisher=Queen's Printer for Nova Scotia| accessdate=29 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604134528/http://gov.ns.ca/iga/djedu.asp| archivedate=4 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> There and in other provinces and territories, various events were held on Accession Day, other days during Diamond Jubilee Week, and past its end.{{refn|[[Gordie Gosse]], the [[Speaker of the House of Assembly of Nova Scotia]], held a youth event at [[Province House (Nova Scotia)|Province House]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://gov.ns.ca/iga/djPhoto.asp| last=Government of Nova Scotia| title=The Diamond Jubilee of Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II > Diamond Jubilee Photos| publisher=Queen's Printer for Nova Scotia| accessdate=29 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603060929/http://gov.ns.ca/iga/djPhoto.asp| archivedate=3 June 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Lieutenant Governor of British Columbia]] [[Steven Point]] hosted a tea and later formal reception at [[Government House (British Columbia)|Government House]].<ref name=BCCeremony>{{cite news| url=http://www.opinion250.com/blog/view/23244| title=Diamond Jubilee Celebration Held At BC Legislature| date=14 February 2012| publisher=680 News| accessdate=2 March 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130131012207/http://www.opinion250.com/blog/view/23244| archivedate=31 January 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> A public official reception was held by the [[Commissioner of the Northwest Territories|territorial commissioner]] at the [[Legislative Assembly of the Northwest Territories]] on 7 February, at which a pictorial display with the theme of past royal tours of the territory was opened.<ref name=NWT /> A ceremony, attended by the [[Lieutenant Governor of British Columbia|Lieutenant Governor]], [[Premier of British Columbia|Premier]], and parliamentary officials was held in conjunction with the opening of the British Columbia legislature on 14 February.<ref name=BCCeremony /> And [[Lieutenant Governor of Ontario]] [[David Onley]] mounted at the viceregal suite at the [[Ontario Legislative Building]] an exhibition entitled ''60 in 60'', to \"show six decades of Her Majesty's devotion and service to Canada.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.jubilee.lt.gov.on.ca/60in60/| last=Office of the Lieutenant Governor of Ontario| title=60 in 60| publisher=Queen's Printer for Ontario| accessdate=6 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517205344/http://www.jubilee.lt.gov.on.ca/60in60/| archivedate=17 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>|group=n|name=Prov}} The [[Speaker of the Senate (Canada)|Speaker of the Senate]], [[No\u00ebl Kinsella]], and [[Speaker of the House of Commons (Canada)|Speaker of the House of Commons]], [[Andrew Scheer]], were received by the Queen at [[Buckingham Palace]] on 21 February 2012, where they presented a loyal address to the sovereign.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/CourtCircular/Todaysevents.aspx| last=Royal Household| title=Court Circular > 21 February 2012| publisher=[[Queen's Printer]]| accessdate=25 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229062758/http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/CourtCircular/Todaysevents.aspx| archivedate=29 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The [[Canadian Postal Museum]] also opened on 19 March the exhibition Designed for a Queen, which displayed 645 postal portraits of the Queen from Canada, other [[Commonwealth of Nations]] countries, and [[British Overseas Territories]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.civilization.ca/event/designed-for-a-queen-celebrating-the-60-year-reign-of-queen-elizabeth-ii-through-stamps| title=Exhibitions > Special Exhibitions > Designed for a Queen: Celebrating the 60-year Reign of Queen Elizabeth II through Stamps| publisher=Canadian Museum of Civilization| accessdate=28 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511112036/http://www.civilization.ca/event/designed-for-a-queen-celebrating-the-60-year-reign-of-queen-elizabeth-ii-through-stamps| archivedate=11 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Royal tour====\n[[File:2012 Royal Tour of Canada, Queen's Park 7.JPG|thumb|left|[[Charles, Prince of Wales]], speaks to the public outside of the [[Ontario Legislative Building]] during his tour of Canada for the Diamond Jubilee]]\n\n[[Charles, Prince of Wales]], and [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]], toured parts of the country in May,<ref name=CNW/> making stops in [[New Brunswick]], Ontario, and [[Saskatchewan]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14382| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=Their Royal Highnesses The Prince of Wales and The Duchess of Cornwall to Undertake a Royal Tour of Canada in 2012| date=14 December 2011| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=14 December 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20141014105320/http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14382| archivedate=14 October 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref> In an editorial he wrote for ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', Charles stated he wanted his activities during the tour to reflect the jubilee's \"central theme of service to others\" and expressed that he was \"returning to Canada in this special Jubilee year, to renew my own pledge of service and to encourage others to consider how they might contribute their own particular talent\".<ref>{{citation| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/opinions/opinion/through-service-to-others-we-build-strong-communities/article2436190/| author1=Prince Charles| author2=Prince of Wales| authorlink=Charles, Prince of Wales| title=Through service to others, we build strong communities| date=18 May 2012| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| accessdate=25 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523202145/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/opinions/opinion/through-service-to-others-we-build-strong-communities/article2436190/| archivedate=23 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> In that vein, he in all three provinces visited with people associated with his organisation [[The Prince's Charities#The Prince's Charities Canada|The Prince's Charities Canada]] and presented Diamond Jubilee Medals to recipients.\n\nThe couple arrived at [[Saint John Airport]] on the evening of 20 May.<ref name=DCHItinerary>{{cite web| url=http://pch.gc.ca/eng/1336669990111/1336670644633| last=Department of Canadian Heritage| title=Topics > Monarchy in Canada > 2012 Royal Tour > 2012 Royal Tour Itinerary| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=11 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521034454/http://pch.gc.ca/eng/1336669990111/1336670644633| archivedate=21 May 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The following day, they were formally welcomed by the Governor General and met at [[CFB Gagetown|Canadian Forces Base Gagetown]] with young Canadian Forces veterans and mentors involved in the Military Entrepreneurship program before moving on to [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]]. There, they undertook a walking tour of Prince William Street to observe heritage projects and meet the 2002 Committee for the Prince of Wales Municipal Heritage Leadership Prize, participated in a citizenship ceremony, attended [[Victoria Day]] events, and opened the Diamond Jubilee IT Centre at Hazen-White-St. Francis School.<ref name=DCHItinerary/> They then flew on to [[Toronto]] to meet with emergency workers and their families and observe the annual fireworks show at [[The Beaches|Ashbridges Bay]] that marks Victoria Day and the [[Queen's Birthday#Canada|Queen's official Canadian birthday]].\n\nOn 22 May, the couple attended an event hosted by the [[Lieutenant Governor of Ontario]], [[David Onley]], at [[Queen's Park (Toronto)|Queen's Park]]. After, the Duchess visited [[The Queen's Own Rifles of Canada]], of which she is colonel-in-chief,<ref>{{citation| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/article/1170776--royal-tour-2012-details-announced-for-charles-and-camilla-s-tour-of-toronto| last=Daubs| first=Katie| title=Royal Tour 2012: Details announced for Charles and Camilla's tour of Toronto| date=30 April 2012| newspaper=Toronto Star| accessdate=5 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827070741/http://www.thestar.com/news/article/1170776--royal-tour-2012-details-announced-for-charles-and-camilla-s-tour-of-toronto| archivedate=27 August 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> laying at the armoury a wreath in memory of fallen Canadian soldiers, while the Prince of Wales saw the Digital Media Zone at [[Ryerson University]], toured the construction site of the athletes' village for the [[2015 Pan American Games]] (where [[Premier of Ontario]] [[Dalton McGuinty]] announced a portion of [[Front Street (Toronto)|Front Street]] running through the village would be named ''Diamond Jubilee Promenade''<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20120522/prince-charles-camilla-in-toronto-120522/#ixzz1vhjnJQPS| title=Prince Charles, Camilla head to Regina after Toronto tour| date=22 May 2012| publisher=CTV| accessdate=23 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525075702/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20120522/prince-charles-camilla-in-toronto-120522#ixzz1vhjnJQPS| archivedate=25 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>), visited the Yonge Street Mission, and met with the national leadership of the [[Assembly of First Nations]]. The couple also attended a luncheon hosted by the [[government of Ontario]] and participated in a [[Canadian Forces]] event at [[Fort York]] commemorating the 200th anniversary of the [[War of 1812]],<ref name=DCHItinerary /> the Prince there wearing his uniform of a [[Lieutenant-general (Canada)|lieutenant-general]] of the [[Canadian Army]].\n[[File:Saskatchewan Legislative Building Front.JPG|thumb|right|The [[Saskatchewan Legislative Building]] in 2012. The building's centenary was marked by [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], and [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]], as part of their Canadian royal tour earlier that year.]]\nThey arrived in [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]] on 23 May and marked the centenary of [[Saskatchewan Legislative Building|Saskatchewan's legislative building]], participated in a reception held by the Lieutenant Governor of Saskatchewan at Government House, toured the [[First Nations University of Canada]], and visited an environmentally friendly water purification plant. In the evening, the Prince and Duchess attended at the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) Depot Division Drill Hall a performance of the [[Regina Symphony Orchestra]], of which Prince Charles is patron.<ref name=DCHItinerary/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://pch.gc.ca/eng/1335470669033/1335471159074| last=Department of Canadian Heritage| title=The Department > Newsroom > Government of Canada Unveils Details of the 2012 Royal Tour| date=30 April 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=5 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130628032051/http://www.pch.gc.ca/eng/1335470669033/1335471159074| archivedate=28 June 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> There, the Prime Minister announced that Charles was to be appointed Honorary Commissioner of the RCMP, taking the post from his mother, the Queen, who became the RCMP's Commissioner-in-Chief.<ref>{{citation| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/harper-names-prince-charles-honorary-rcmp-commissioner/article2441944/| last=Mackrael| first=Kim| title=Harper names Prince Charles honorary RCMP commissioner| date=23 May 2012| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| accessdate=25 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526020840/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/harper-names-prince-charles-honorary-rcmp-commissioner/article2441944/| archivedate=26 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[New Democratic Party of Canada|New Democratic Party]] MP [[Pat Martin]], an open anti-monarchist, stated in the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] that the tour was \"a [[Bread and circuses|bread-and-circuses]] routine\" intended to distract from cuts to the [[Public Service of Canada|federal civil service]].<ref>{{citation| url=http://fullcomment.nationalpost.com/2012/04/30/kelly-mcparland-nathan-cullens-deportment-police-can-start-with-pat-martin/| last=McParland| first=Kelly| title=Nathan Cullen's deportment police can start with Pat Martin| date=30 April 2012| newspaper=National Post| accessdate=6 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120716091322/http://fullcomment.nationalpost.com/2012/04/30/kelly-mcparland-nathan-cullens-deportment-police-can-start-with-pat-martin/| archivedate=16 July 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Minister of Canadian Heritage, [[James Moore (Canadian politician)|James Moore]], said the tour would be the \"least expensive for taxpayers\" of those that had taken place since 2009.<ref>{{citation| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/tories-blasted-over-1-million-bread-and-circuses-royal-tour/article2417917/?from=sec501| last=Chase| first=Steven| title=Tories blasted over $1-million 'bread and circuses' royal tour| date=30 April 2012| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| accessdate=6 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525182454/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/tories-blasted-over-1-million-bread-and-circuses-royal-tour/article2417917/?from=sec501| archivedate=25 May 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Events through June====\nAt the Queen's request,<ref name=CTVRCMP>{{cite news |url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/TopStories/20120523/rcmp-musical-ride-buckingham-palace-guard-duty-120523/ |title=Mounties guard the Queen in London for a day |date=23 May 2012 |publisher=CTV |accessdate=25 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525075532/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/TopStories/20120523/rcmp-musical-ride-buckingham-palace-guard-duty-120523/ |archivedate=25 May 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> members of the RCMP's [[Musical Ride]], after performing in the [[Diamond Jubilee Pageant]] at [[Windsor Castle]], took part in the Changing of the Guard on 23 May as they formed the [[Queen's Guard|Queen's Life Guard]] outside Buckingham Palace for 24 hours.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iUQJHXQFYW2HsFHhH0wdTWl5oEsw?docId=CNG.da5623a1e1f2af30fd41b88f6c00592c.301| title=Canada's Mounties guard Buckingham Palace| date=24 May 2012|agency=AFP| accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> Said by the contingent's commander to be a \"way for Canada and the Mounties to salute her Majesty the Queen in her Diamond Jubilee year\",<ref name=CTVRCMP/> it was the second time the RCMP had performed the task since doing so as a part of the Diamond Jubilee celebrations for Queen Victoria in 1897.<ref>{{citation| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/worldview/mounties-set-to-replace-queens-life-guard-at-buckingham-palace-for-one-day/article2439909/| last=Saunders| first=Doug| title=Mounties set to replace Queen's Life Guard at Buckingham Palace for one day| date=22 May 2012| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| accessdate=25 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525115523/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/worldview/mounties-set-to-replace-queens-life-guard-at-buckingham-palace-for-one-day/article2439909/| archivedate=25 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n{{Quote box| width=250px| border=1px| align=left| quote=We, Your Majesty's loyal and dutiful subjects, the House of Commons of Canada in Parliament assembled, beg to offer our sincere congratulations on the happy completion of the sixtieth year of Your reign.\n\nIn this, the Diamond Jubilee year of your reign as Queen of Canada, we trust that Your gracious and peaceful reign may continue for many years and that Divine Providence will preserve Your Majesty in health, in happiness and in the affectionate loyalty of Your people.<ref name=LoyAddress>{{Citation| last=Parliament of Canada| year=2012| editor-last=O'Malley| editor-first=Kady| title=To The Queen's Most Excellent Majesty, with love from Her Canadian parliamentarians...| journal=CBC| publication-date=2012| url=http://www.cbc.ca/newsblogs/politics/inside-politics-blog/2012/06/to-the-queens-most-excellent-majesty-with-love-from-her-canadian-parliamentarians.html| accessdate=4 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727074637/http://www.cbc.ca/newsblogs/politics/inside-politics-blog/2012/06/to-the-queens-most-excellent-majesty-with-love-from-her-canadian-parliamentarians.html| archivedate=27 July 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>| salign=right| source=Parliament of Canada, 2012}}\n\nIn the [[Parliament of Canada|federal parliament]] on 31 May, a loyal address to the Queen was passed.<ref name=LoyAddress /> The [[Lieutenant Governor of Manitoba]] held a Diamond Jubilee garden party at the province's Government House on 26 May.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20120511/diamond-jubilee-events-schedule-itinerary-queen-120511/| title=The Diamond Jubilee: Schedule of events| date=14 May 2012| publisher=CTV| accessdate=28 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518082222/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/Canada/20120511/diamond-jubilee-events-schedule-itinerary-queen-120511/| archivedate=18 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Royal British Columbia Museum]] on 1 June opened an exhibition of approximately 100 [[Cecil Beaton]] photographs of Elizabeth II throughout her life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalbcmuseum.bc.ca/Exhibit_Gall/queenelizabethII.aspx| title=Exhibits & Galleries > Visiting Exhibitions > Queen Elizabeth II by Cecil Beaton: A Diamond Jubilee Celebration| publisher=Royal British Columbia Museum| accessdate=2 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref>\n[[File:Barbeau Peak, Nunavut.jpg|thumb|right|[[Barbeau Peak|Mount Barbeau]] in [[Nunavut]]]]\n\nA team of Canadian and British mountaineers reached the summit of [[Barbeau Peak|Mount Barbeau]], in Canada's arctic, by 3 June and there held a tea party in celebration of the jubilee. From the summit, they sent a loyal greeting to the Queen via satellite, to which the monarch promised to reply.<ref>{{cite news| title=Adventurers to celebrate Queen\u2019s Jubilee atop Arctic peak| date=22 May 2012| publisher=CBC}}</ref> The next day, a group from the [[Royal Canadian Dragoons]] stationed in [[Afghanistan]] climbed with British soldiers to the peak of the 7,000 foot mountain Gharib Ghar, within the [[Kabul Military Training Center]], \"as part of the Diamond Jubilee celebrations for Queen Elizabeth II.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dragoons.ca/afganchange.html| title=The Changing Role of Dragoons in Afghanistan| publisher=Royal Canadian Dragoons| accessdate=16 July 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120721214108/http://www.dragoons.ca/afganchange.html| archivedate=21 July 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, [[Canada House]] held a Big Jubilee Lunch on 3 June and two beacons were lit on the building's roof the following evening,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/united_kingdom-royaume_uni/events-evenements/diamond_jubilee-jubile_diamant.aspx?lang=eng&view=d| last=High Commission of Canada to the United Kingdom| authorlink=High Commission of Canada to the United Kingdom| title=Canada celebrates Her Majesty's Diamond Jubilee| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=28 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505210732/http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/united_kingdom-royaume_uni/events-evenements/diamond_jubilee-jubile_diamant.aspx?lang=eng&view=d| archivedate=5 May 2012 }}</ref> the night of the [[Diamond Jubilee Concert]]. Johnston attended both events and Harper was at the latter.<ref name=GGLondon /><ref name=VS>{{citation| url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/Harper+joins+Diamond+Jubilee+celebrations/6722925/story.html| last=Kennedy| first=Mark| title=Harper joins the Diamond Jubilee celebrations| date=3 June 2012| newspaper=Vancouver Sun| accessdate=4 June 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref> Another reception was held at Canada House on the evening of 6 June, at which the Governor General and [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]], were present.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14560| last=Johnston| first=David| authorlink=David Johnston| title=Reception with the Business Community| date=6 June 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=22 June 2012}}</ref>\nHarper was granted an audience with the Queen at Buckingham Palace on 5 June.<ref name=VS/> Also at the palace, the Governor General, the Prime Minister, and the Queen unveiled a [[Canadian royal symbols#Artworks|new portrait of the sovereign]] commissioned by the federal Crown-in-Council and painted by Canadian painter Phil Richards. The creation of the portrait became the subject of a [[National Film Board of Canada]] (NFB) documentary directed by [[Hubert Davis (filmmaker)|Hubert Davis]] and released in the fall of 2012 as part of the NFB's ''Queen's Diamond Jubilee Collector's Edition''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://realscreen.com/2012/06/07/national-film-board-puts-final-touches-to-the-portrait/#ixzz1xyvJFwJf| last=Vlessing| first=Etan| title=National Film Board puts final touches to \"The Portrait\"| date=5 June 2012| publisher=Realscreen| accessdate=16 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402171234/http://realscreen.com/2012/06/07/national-film-board-puts-final-touches-to-the-portrait/#ixzz1xyvJFwJf| archivedate=2 April 2015| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfb.ca/film/portrait/|title=The Portrait|last=Davis, Hubert (director)|work=Documentary film|publisher=[[National Film Board of Canada]]|accessdate=13 October 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017044641/http://www.nfb.ca/film/portrait|archivedate=17 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The painting was on 25 June installed in the ballroom at Rideau Hall. Dedicated at the same time by the Governor General were new bronze and glass handrails, with detailing evoking the Diamond Jubilee, flanking the ceremonial staircase in Rideau Hall's main entrance foyer.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14596| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=Her Majesty The Queen's New Painting Arrives at Rideau Hall| date=25 June 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 June 2012, the government of the [[Northwest Territories]] (NWT) and the City of [[Yellowknife]] held at the Northern Arts and Cultural Centre a garden party with [[barbecue]], concert, and other activities. On 14 June, Amber Jubilee Ninebark shrubs were planted on the grounds of the NWT legislative assembly.<ref name=NWT /> Four days later, a gala concert was held at [[Roy Thomson Hall]] in Toronto, at which 600 diamond jubilee medals were awarded to members of the [[Order of Canada]] and [[Order of Ontario]]. The event, hosted by the Lieutenant Governor of Ontario, was attended by the Governor General and his wife and performers included the [[Famous People Players]], [[Susan Aglukark]], [[Molly Johnson]], [[Ben Heppner]], and [[Gordon Lightfoot]], who conceived the idea of the event.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/story/2012/06/18/jubilee-gala-toronto.html| title=Diamond Jubilee Gala toasts exceptional Canadians| date=18 June 2012| publisher=CBC| accessdate=19 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619053044/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/story/2012/06/18/jubilee-gala-toronto.html| archivedate=19 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Further events====\n[[File:British pageantry at Canadian Museum of Civilization (8347684263).jpg|thumb|left|The [[Queen's Beasts]] on display at the [[Canadian Museum of Civilization]] during Elizabeth II's Diamond Jubilee]]\nThe [[Lieutenant Governor of Saskatchewan]] held a garden party at [[Government House (Saskatchewan)|Government House]] on [[Canada Day]] and,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://jubileesk.ca/events/item/?e=6| archive-url=https://archive.today/20120716224505/http://jubileesk.ca/events/item/?e=6| url-status=dead| archive-date=16 July 2012| last=Government of Saskatchewan| title=Events > Garden Party| publisher=Queen's Printer for Saskatchewan| accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> in the Northwest Territories, the Canada Day parade was themed to celebrate the jubilee and numerous jubilee medal presentation ceremonies took place.<ref name=NWT /> Also on 1 July, the [[Canadian Museum of Civilization]] opened the exhibit ''A Queen and Her Country'', showing artefacts from the [[Crown Collection]] relating to Queen Elizabeth II and her role as Queen of Canada, including the [[Queen's Beasts]] from [[Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II|her coronation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.civilization.ca/exhibitions/special-exhibitions/a-queen-and-her-country3| title=Exhibitions > Special Exhibitions > A Queen and Her Country| publisher=Canadian Museum of Civilization| accessdate=28 June 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625031245/http://www.civilization.ca/exhibitions/special-exhibitions/a-queen-and-her-country3| archivedate=25 June 2012 }}</ref> At Rideau Hall on 11 September, a reception, attended by the Governor General; his wife; [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]]; [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex]]; and others, was held for the [[Royal Victorian Order]] Association of Canada and to \"honour of the 60th anniversary of Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II\u2019s accession to the Throne.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14708| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=Working Visit to Canada by The Earl and Countess of Wessex| date=10 September 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=12 September 2012}}</ref> The Earl also distributed Diamond Jubilee Medals to recipients in Toronto and to members of the RCMP in [[Iqaluit]], [[Nunavut]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://blogs.canoe.ca/royalspectacle/general/prince-edward-sophie-kick-off-tour/| last=Schwass-Bueckert| first=Kate| title=Prince Edward, Sophie kick off tour| date=11 September 2012| publisher=Canoe| accessdate=16 September 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130115071634/http://blogs.canoe.ca/royalspectacle/general/prince-edward-sophie-kick-off-tour/| archivedate=15 January 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/story/2012/09/13/north-royal-visit-iqaluit.html| title=Royals commend RCMP officers in Iqaluit| date=13 September 2012| publisher=CBC| accessdate=16 September 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916015841/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/story/2012/09/13/north-royal-visit-iqaluit.html| archivedate=16 September 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The government of the Northwest Territories held through September an essay contest for youth to explain \"how the Queen is important to [[First Nations]] and [[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)|M\u00e9tis people]].\"<ref name=NWT />\n\nA conference on the Canadian Crown was conducted in Saskatchewan on 25 October.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://jubileesk.ca/events/item/?e=7| last=Government of Saskatchewan| title=Events > Conference on the Crown| publisher=Queen's Printer for Saskatchewan| accessdate=7 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120710034648/http://jubileesk.ca/events/item/?e=7| archivedate=10 July 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Governor General the following day unveiled a plaque identifying the Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Trail, a part of the [[Trans Canada Trail]] between the [[West Block]] on [[Parliament Hill]] and the [[Supreme Court of Canada]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14800| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=Governor General to Unveil New Plaque in Honour of the Naming of The Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Trail| date=24 October 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=25 October 2012}}</ref> In Nova Scotia, [[Nova Scotia Highway 106|highway 106]] was renamed as ''Jubilee Highway''.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20121221002| last=Government of Nova Scotia| title=Highway Naming Commemorates 60-year Reign| date=21 December 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Nova Scotia| accessdate=21 December 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220034319/http://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20121221002| archivedate=20 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Communities across Canada also held events to mark the jubilee,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebratecanada.info/docs/Plan%20Diamond%20Jubilee%202012.pdf|title=London Celebrates Canada|publisher=City of London|accessdate=6 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905170736/http://www.celebratecanada.info/docs/Plan%20Diamond%20Jubilee%202012.pdf|archivedate=5 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://museumsofburlington.com/events/21-queen-s-jubilee-mother-s-day-royal-tea--may-13-2012| title=Events > Upcoming Events > Queen's Jubilee & Mother's Day Royal Tea| publisher=Museums of Burlington| accessdate=5 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120605020450/http://www.museumsofburlington.com/events/21-queen-s-jubilee-mother-s-day-royal-tea--may-13-2012| archivedate=5 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.metrocinema.org/film_view/3541/| title=Queen's Diamond Jubilee: The Queen| publisher=Metro Cinema| accessdate=5 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805222513/http://www.metrocinema.org/film_view/3541/| archivedate=5 August 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.monarchist.ca/en/jubilee-jubile/events| title=List of Diamond Jubilee events| publisher=Monarchist League of Canada| accessdate=5 May 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414201429/http://www.monarchist.ca/en/jubilee-jubile/events| archivedate=14 April 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gov.pe.ca/diamondjubilee/index.php3?number=1042882&lang=E| last=Government of Prince Edward Island| title=The Diamond Jubilee: A Prince Edward Island Celebration > Community Events| publisher=Queen's Printer for Prince Edward Island| accessdate=16 September 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025092210/http://www.gov.pe.ca/diamondjubilee/index.php3?number=1042882&lang=E| archivedate=25 October 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> as did the federal government until the jubilee celebration ended on Accession Day 2013.\n\n===Jamaica===\n[[Prince Harry]] toured Jamaica between 5 and 8 March 2012,<ref name=GoJam>{{cite news| url=http://go-jamaica.com/news/read_article.php?id=35102| title=Preparations underway for Prince\u2019s visit| date=7 February 2012| publisher=Go-Jamaica| accessdate=11 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210183703/http://go-jamaica.com/news/read_article.php?id=35102| archivedate=10 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/Big-foreign-media-coverage-for-Prince-Harry-s-visit_10924286| title=Big foreign media coverage for Prince Harry's visit| date=29 February 2012| newspaper=Jamaica Observer| accessdate=29 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302182553/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/Big-foreign-media-coverage-for-Prince-Harry-s-visit_10924286| archivedate=2 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> participating in various events marking his grandmother's Diamond Jubilee as Jamaica's queen regnant, first as [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|Queen of the United Kingdom]], between 1952 and 1962, and subsequently as [[Monarchy of Jamaica|Queen of Jamaica]] (Jamaica will also thus be concurrently celebrating 50 years of independence). During the tour, the Prince partook in military exercises with the [[Jamaica Defence Force]], visited Bustamante Hospital for Children and, in [[Trelawny Parish]], visited Water Square, Falmouth Pier, and the William Knibb Baptist Church, where he paid respect at the [[William Knibb]] memorial. The Prince attended an event for the charity Rise Life,<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2111338/Prince-Harry-Jamaica-Prince-dances-Bob-Marley-Diamond-Jubilee-tour-wearing-blue-shoes.html| title=Don't step on my blue suede shoes: Party Prince Harry gets down to Bob Marley in Jamaica wearing {{Sic|hide=y|brightly|-}}coloured desert boots| date=7 March 2012| newspaper=Daily Mail| accessdate=8 March 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308033052/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2111338/Prince-Harry-Jamaica-Prince-dances-Bob-Marley-Diamond-Jubilee-tour-wearing-blue-shoes.html| archivedate=8 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> ran with [[Usain Bolt]] at the latter's training ground at the [[University of the West Indies]], [[Mona, Jamaica|Mona]]. There, he was also named an Honorary Fellow of the university.<ref>{{citation| url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/latest/article.php?id=35727| title=Prince Harry named Honorary UWI Fellow| date=6 March 2012| newspaper=The Gleaner| accessdate=8 March 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307233703/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/latest/article.php?id=35727| archivedate=7 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> A Jamaica Night reception was held at the Royal Caribbean Hotel in Montego Bay and [[Governor-General of Jamaica]] Sir [[Patrick Allen (politician)|Patrick Allen]] hosted a dinner at [[King's House, Jamaica|King's House]] as a combined celebration of the Diamond Jubilee and Jamaica's 50th anniversary of independence. The Prime Minister, [[Portia Simpson Miller]], stated the tour was intended to \"highlight the country's tourism developments on the North Coast and the important work being done in the area of youth and children.\"<ref name=GoJam />\n\nThe Governor-General and his wife travelled to London, United Kingdom (UK), to partake in various events there in June, including a reception held by the High Commissioner of Jamaica to the UK.<ref name=JGDJL />  Jamaica's Diamond Jubilee celebrations proceeded despite Miller's ongoing work to have the country become a republic.<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.jis.gov.jm/news/leads/30943| title=High Commissioner Assures UK Jamaicans on Republic Status| date=17 June 2012| publisher=Jamaica Information Service| accessdate=24 June 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525154011/http://www.jis.gov.jm/news/leads/30943| archivedate=25 May 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand===\n[[File:NZ Jubilee Emblem.jpg|thumb|right|The official emblem of the [[Monarchy of New Zealand|Queen of New Zealand]]'s Diamond Jubilee<ref>{{cite web| url=http://gg.govt.nz/content/queens-diamond-jubilee-emblem| last=Governor-General of New Zealand| authorlink=Governor-General of New Zealand| title=Queen's Diamond Jubilee Emblem of New Zealand| publisher=Governor-General of New Zealand| accessdate=29 November 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111218200831/http://gg.govt.nz/content/queens-diamond-jubilee-emblem| archivedate=18 December 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref>]]\nSir [[Jerry Mateparae]], the [[Governor-General of New Zealand]], unveiled New Zealand's Diamond Jubilee emblem on 27 November 2011 and announced at that time that a full programme would be forthcoming.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://gg.govt.nz/content/queens-diamond-jubilee-emblem| last=Office of the Governor-General of New Zealand| title=Queen's Diamond Jubilee Emblem of New Zealand| publisher=Government Printing Office| accessdate=29 November 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111218200831/http://gg.govt.nz/content/queens-diamond-jubilee-emblem| archivedate=18 December 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[New Zealand Post]] and the [[Reserve Bank of New Zealand]] stated in January 2012 the release a silver proof dollar coin to celebrate the Queen's Diamond Jubilee and, the following month, the [[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] added Crown-related entries to [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand]] and an essay on the jubilee to NZ.History.net.nz.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://coins.nzpost.co.nz/2012/queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee-silver-proof-coin| last=New Zealand Post| title=2012 Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Silver Proof Coin| publisher=Government Printing Office| accessdate=1 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20120201184023/http://coins.nzpost.co.nz/2012/queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee-silver-proof-coin| archivedate=1 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation| title=Waitangi Day starts Queen's Diamond Jubilee celebrations| last=Ministry for Culture and Heritage| date=3 February 2012| url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU1202/S00036/waitangi-day-starts-queens-diamond-jubilee-celebrations.htm| publisher=Scoop| accessdate=3 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207184309/http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU1202/S00036/waitangi-day-starts-queens-diamond-jubilee-celebrations.htm| archivedate=7 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The New Zealand post also issued sets of Diamond Jubilee stamps showing images of Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip throughout her reign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stamps.nzpost.co.nz/new-zealand/2012/queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee|title=2012 Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee|website=New Zealand Post Stamps|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222031115/http://stamps.nzpost.co.nz/new-zealand/2012/queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee|archivedate=22 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nPrime Minister [[John Key]] moved a motion in the [[New Zealand House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] congratulating the Queen on her Diamond Jubilee on 7 February.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.parliament.nz/en-NZ/PB/Debates/Debates/9/e/6/50HansD_20120207_00000012-Motions-Queen-Elizabeth-II-Diamond-Jubilee.htm| last=Parliament of New Zealand| authorlink=Parliament of New Zealand| title=Motions \u2013 Queen Elizabeth II \u2013 Diamond Jubilee| publisher=Government Printing Office| accessdate=10 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304173955/http://www.parliament.nz/en-NZ/PB/Debates/Debates/9/e/6/50HansD_20120207_00000012-Motions-Queen-Elizabeth-II-Diamond-Jubilee.htm| archivedate=4 March 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Queen-in-Council|Governor-General-in-Council]] also launched, two days later, via the [[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)|Ministry of Health]], the Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Research Grant, \"seeking to purchase research projects that transfer knowledge from initiatives with proven effectiveness, into practice in the health sector\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrc.govt.nz/news-and-media/news/queen-elizabeth-ii-jubilee-research-grant-health-knowledge-action |last=Health Research Council of New Zealand |title=Queen Elizabeth II Jubilee Research Grant \u2013 Health Knowledge to Action |date=9 February 2012 |publisher=Government Printing Office |accessdate=19 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213030438/http://www.hrc.govt.nz/news-and-media/news/queen-elizabeth-ii-jubilee-research-grant-health-knowledge-action |archivedate=13 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe New Zealand Army Band took part in the Diamond Jubilee Pageant held at Windsor Castle and also took part in the changing of guard ceremony at Buckingham Palace. In New Zealand, ''[[New Zealand Herald]]'' opinion columnist [[Jim Hopkins]] was critical of the jubilee celebrations held over the [[Queen's Birthday#New Zealand|Queen's Birthday weekend]], calling it a \"missed opportunity\".<ref name=hopkins>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/opinion/news/article.cfm?c_id=466&objectid=10811537|title=Shame we blew Queen's Jubilee|date=8 June 2012|accessdate=30 July 2012|publisher=[[New Zealand Herald]]}}</ref> He was also critical of [[TVNZ]]'s lack of jubilee related content in its daily news broadcast.<ref name=hopkins />\n\nA royal tour was undertaken by [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], and [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]], between 10 and 16 November 2012.<ref name=TelegraphPoW /><ref>{{cite press release| last=Office of the Prime Minister of New Zealand| title=PM marks beginning of Diamond Jubilee year| publisher=Government Printing Office| date=6 February 2012| url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1202/S00051/pm-marks-beginning-of-diamond-jubilee-year.htm| accessdate=6 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207145515/http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1202/S00051/pm-marks-beginning-of-diamond-jubilee-year.htm| archivedate=7 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> travelling to [[Auckland]], [[Wellington, New Zealand|Wellington]], [[Christchurch]], and [[Manawatu]]. Their programme is to focus on excellence and innovation in business, agriculture, community service, and sports, as well as children's literacy and animal health.<ref name=TelegraphPoW />\n\n===Papua New Guinea===\n[[Charles, Prince of Wales]], and [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]], toured Papua New Guinea between 3 and 5 November. During their time in the country, the couple met church, charity, and community volunteers, cultural groups, and members of the [[Papua New Guinea Defence Force]] in and near [[Port Moresby]].<ref name=TelegraphPoW />\n\n===Oceanic realms===\n[[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge]], and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]], visited the [[Solomon Islands]] and [[Tuvalu]].<ref name=BBCJplans />\n\n===Other Caribbean and West Indies realms===\nThe Queen's realms throughout the Caribbean and West Indies planned a number of Diamond Jubilee events. Using [[RFA Fort Rosalie (A385)|RFA ''Fort Rosalie'']], [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]], and [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex]], visited other Caribbean realms, including: Antigua and Barbuda, Grenada, Montserrat and Saint Lucia.<ref name=BBCJplans /><ref>{{Citation|last=Prime Minister of St. Kitts and Nevis |title=Display during visit of cruise ship Queen Elizabeth to mark Diamond Jubilee |publisher=The Office of the Prime Minister of St. Kitts and Nevis |date=7 December 2011 |url=http://www.cuopm.com/newsitem_new.asp?articlenumber=2583&post200803=true |accessdate=8 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415034623/http://www.cuopm.com/newsitem_new.asp?articlenumber=2583&post200803=true |archivedate=15 April 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/8955439/Diamond-Jubilee-Royal-Family-will-visit-every-Realm.html| title=Diamond Jubilee: Royal Family will visit every Realm| author=Staff writer| date=14 December 2011| work=The Daily Telegraph| location=UK| accessdate=5 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210003539/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/8955439/Diamond-Jubilee-Royal-Family-will-visit-every-Realm.html| archivedate=10 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Saint Kitts and Nevis===\nHistorical re-enactments were put on in Saint Kitts and Nevis for the Earl and Countess of Wessex, who arrived on 3 March 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.sknvibes.com/news/newsdetails.cfm/53702| title=Dramatic historical re-enactments to mark Diamond Jubilee celebration| date=17 February 2012| publisher=SKNVibes| accessdate=19 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120225031529/http://www.sknvibes.com/news/newsdetails.cfm/53702| archivedate=25 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> There, the couple met with Governor-General Sir [[Cuthbert Sebastian]], Prime Minister [[Denzil Douglas]], and other dignitaries, watched cultural shows (including the performance of a [[Calypso music|calypso]] song about the Queen), and the Earl unveiled a plaque commemorating the Diamond Jubilee and officially designated the [[Basseterre Valley]] Park as the Royal Basseterre Valley Park. They also visited [[Brimstone Hill Fortress National Park]] and the children's ward of the JNF Hospital and the Children's Home before attending a state dinner and fireworks display at Port Zante.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.winnfm.com/news2.asp?NewsID=8293#.T1JtfH2Hawc.twitter| last=Frederick| first=Toni|title=Prince Edward delights the crowd| date=3 March 2012| publisher=Winn FM| accessdate=6 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Saint Lucia===\nThe Earl and Countess of Wessex arrived in Saint Lucia on 21 February 2012 and there participated in Independence Day celebrations and attended receptions held by the [[Governor-General of Saint Lucia]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/st-lucia-celebrates-33-years-of-independence/| title=St Lucia celebrates 33 years of Independence| date=22 February 2012| publisher=NationNews| accessdate=23 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202222118/http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/st-lucia-celebrates-33-years-of-independence/| archivedate=2 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> They also visited the Association of Saint Lucia and the Saint Lucia School of Music.<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.thedominican.net/2012/02/royals-to-begin-visit.html| title=Royals to begin Caribbean tour bypasses Dominica| date=16 February 2012| newspaper=The Dominican| accessdate=19 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203072813/http://www.thedominican.net/2012/02/royals-to-begin-visit.html| archivedate=3 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Saint Vincent and the Grenadines===\nIn Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, a Diamond Jubilee Celebrations Committee was established to oversee events staged to mark, between February and June 2012, the Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II's accession as queen regnant of the country, from 1952 to 1979 as [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|Queen of the United Kingdom]] and thereafter as [[Monarchy of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines|Queen of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]]. The committee head, former Minister of Culture Rene Baptiste, stated the aim was to \"showcase what we have to offer, as well as our loyalty to the Parliament...\" The Earl and Countess of Wessex, aboard [[RFA Fort Rosalie (A385)|RFA ''Fort Rosalie'']], arrived for their tour of country on 25 February and visited the restored [[Botanic Gardens St. Vincent]] and planted a Pink Poui tree, attended an official lunch at Government House, and planted [[Roystonea|Royal Palms]] on the [[Grenadines]].\n\nTrade unionist Noel Jackson said he heard displeasure expressed by Vincentians towards the royal tour and that \"a lot of people were cursing.\" Senator Julian Francis, the General Secretary of the governing [[Unity Labour Party]], stated the public reaction to the presence of the royal couple \"confirmed to me that we could not have won [[2009 Vincentian constitutional referendum|the 2009 referendum on a republic]]. The outpouring of the people in St. Vincent to come and greet Prince Edward yesterday confirmed to me that people, in the majority in St. Vincent, still want the monarchy... It was like a carnival in town yesterday.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://i-witness-news.com/2012/02/27/majority-of-vincentians-still-want-the-monarchy/| title=Majority of Vincentians 'still want the monarchy'| date=27 February 2012| publisher=I-Witness News| accessdate=28 February 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301110030/http://i-witness-news.com/2012/02/27/majority-of-vincentians-still-want-the-monarchy/| archivedate=1 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA Diamond Jubilee Lecture was delivered in March, a flower show and tea party was held at Government House on 4 and 5 May, a stamp exhibition was mounted at the National Trust headquarters and an exhibition of photographs of the Queen in Saint Vincent and the Grenadines was displayed at the National Public Library. A Queen's Birthday parade took place, as did a Diamond Jubilee Beacon Event on 4 June, part of the wider plan to light such beacons at the same time across the Commonwealth.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.thevincentian.com/dcmain.aspx?p=0&i=9355&skin=75&tID=198 |last=Clarke |first=Karissa |title=Big plans to mark Queen's Diamond Jubilee |date=2 February 2012 |newspaper=The Vincentian |accessdate=5 February 2012 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\n[[File:Diamond Jubilee 60 2012 logo.jpg|thumb|right|The United Kingdom's Diamond Jubilee logo]]\n[[File:Cmglee Sea Containers House OXO Tower jubilee.jpg|thumb|right|[[Sea Containers House]] decorated with a [[Largest photographs in the world|large photograph]] of [[Silver Jubilee of Elizabeth II|her Silver Jubilee]]]]\n[[File:Red Arrows II.JPG|thumb|right|Flypast by the [[Red Arrows]] over Buckingham Palace on 5 June]]\n\n====Planning====\nIn the United Kingdom, national and regional events to mark the Diamond Jubilee were coordinated by the [[Queen-in-Council]] and her Royal Household at [[Buckingham Palace]].<ref name=Mail>{{Cite news| title=The Queen: Don't link my Jubilee celebration to 'flashy' Olympics| work=Daily Mail| location=London| date=27 June 2009| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1195973/The-Queen-Dont-link-Jubilee-celebration-flashy-Olympics.html| accessdate=31 October 2010| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130114055826/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1195973/The-Queen-Dont-link-Jubilee-celebration-flashy-Olympics.html| archivedate=14 January 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> As with the [[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Golden Jubilee]] in 2002, the [[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]] was responsible for coordinating the [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]]-led aspects of the celebrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gov.uk/what_we_do/honours/diamondjubilee.aspx| last=Department of Culture, Media, and Sport| title=diamond jubilee| publisher=[[Queen's Printer]]| accessdate=31 October 2010| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100927050301/http://culture.gov.uk/what_we_do/honours/diamondjubilee.aspx| archivedate=27 September 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gov.uk/diamondjubilee| last=Department for Culture, Media, and Sport| authorlink=Department for Culture, Media and Sport| title=what we do > honours and ceremonials >  diamond jubilee| publisher=[[Queen's Printer]]| accessdate=20 April 2010| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100329153058/http://www.culture.gov.uk/diamondjubilee| archivedate=29 March 2010 }}</ref> Events were planned so as to keep the use of tax money to a minimum; most funds used to fund celebrations were drawn from private donors and sponsors. Only the cost of security was by [[HM Treasury|Her Majesty's Treasury]].<ref name=GlobePomp /> The British logo for the Diamond Jubilee was selected through a contest held by the [[BBC]] children's programme ''[[Blue Peter]]''; the winning design, announced in February 2011, was created by ten-year-old Katherine Dewar.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12518165|title=Queen's Diamond Jubilee emblem revealed|date=21 February 2011|accessdate=21 February 2011|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221051419/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12518165|archivedate=21 February 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2011/DiamondJubileeemblemunveiled21February2011.aspx| last=Royal Household| title=Diamond Jubilee emblem unveiled| publisher=[[Queen's Printer]]| date=11 February 2011| accessdate=10 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215181939/http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2011/DiamondJubileeemblemunveiled21February2011.aspx| archivedate=15 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Extended weekend====\nOn 5 January 2010, the [[Lord President of the Council]] and [[Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills|Business Secretary]] [[Peter Mandelson|Lord Mandelson]] announced that an extra [[bank holiday]] would take place on 5 June 2012.<ref name=Mail /><ref name=PA>{{Cite news|title=Extra bank holiday to mark Jubilee |publisher=Press Association |date=5 January 2010 |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5iFc6Cmk-AJ72Mo5lMkmGuUqHSxIw |accessdate=5 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108223450/http://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5iFc6Cmk-AJ72Mo5lMkmGuUqHSxIw |archivedate=8 January 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=BIS>{{cite web|title=Extra Bank holiday to mark Queen's Diamond Jubilee |publisher=Department for Business Innovation & Skills |date=5 January 2010 |url=http://www.bis.gov.uk/jubilee |accessdate=6 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120405181048/http://www.bis.gov.uk/jubilee |archivedate=5 April 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> Moving the Spring Bank Holiday (the last Monday in May) to 4 June resulted in a four-day holiday in honour of the Diamond Jubilee.<ref name=PA /><ref name=Reuters>{{Cite news|title=Extra holiday for 2012 Jubilee |publisher=Reuters |date=5 January 2010 |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKTRE6043L120100105 |accessdate=5 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107121124/http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKTRE6043L120100105 |archivedate=7 January 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> As national holidays are a [[Reserved and excepted matters|devolved matter]], Scotland's [[First Minister of Scotland|first minister]] confirmed that the bank holiday would be held on 5 June in Scotland. Some economists later theorised that the holiday could reduce the country's gross domestic product by 0.5% in the second quarter of the year, though this would be partially offset by increased sales for the hospitality and merchandise sectors.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.sky.com/home/business/article/16163892| title='Diamond Jubilee Could Harm The Economy'| publisher=Sky News| date=6 February 2012| accessdate=6 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207185203/http://news.sky.com/home/business/article/16163892| archivedate=7 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Queen Elizabeth II.JPG|thumb|left|The Queen travelling by car to [[St Paul's Cathedral]] for the service of thanksgiving on 5 June]]\n\nMany events were staged in London during the bank holiday weekend.<ref name=Reuters /> The [[River Thames|River]] [[Thames Diamond Jubilee Pageant]] was held on 3 June; a maritime parade of 1,000 boats from around the Commonwealth\u2014the largest flotilla seen on the river in 350 years\u2014together with other celebrations along the river banks.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://thamesdiamondjubileepageant.org/| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110407222350/http://www.thamesdiamondjubileepageant.org/| url-status=dead| archive-date=7 April 2011| title=Welcome| publisher=Diamond Jubilee| accessdate=7 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=London river extravaganza planned for Queen's jubilee| publisher=France 24| date=6 April 2011| url=http://www.france24.com/en/20110406-london-river-extravaganza-planned-queens-jubilee| accessdate=7 April 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120126151433/http://www.france24.com/en/20110406-london-river-extravaganza-planned-queens-jubilee| archivedate=26 January 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation| last=Bates| first=Stephen| title=Thames flotilla to mark Queen's diamond jubilee| newspaper=The Guardian| date=5 April 2011| url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/apr/05/thames-flotilla-queen-diamond-jubilee| accessdate=7 April 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203051933/http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/apr/05/thames-flotilla-queen-diamond-jubilee| archivedate=3 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Heavy rain started during the event and the commemorative airforce flyover at the end was cancelled due to very low [[cloud base]] and bad visibility at ground level. Along with almost all members of the Royal Family, various governors-general from the Commonwealth realms other than the UK were in attendance.<ref name=GGLondon>{{cite web| url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14556| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| title=The Central Weekend \u2013 Queen's Diamond Jubilee| date=1 June 2012| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=JGDJL>{{citation| url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20120601/social/social5.html| title=Sir Patrick and Lady Allen for Diamond Jubilee| date=1 June 2012| newspaper=Jamaica Gleaner| accessdate=4 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603040004/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20120601/social/social5.html| archivedate=3 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Diamond Jubilee Concert]], with a preceding afternoon picnic in the palace gardens for the 10,000 concert ticket holders,<ref name=BBC_McCartney_to_play>{{cite web| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16925230| title=Sir Paul McCartney to play Queen Diamond Jubilee gig| publisher=BBC| work=BBC News| date=7 February 2012| accessdate=20 April 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120519122700/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16925230| archivedate=19 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=BBC_Webber_Barlow>{{cite web| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-17152327| title=Andrew Lloyd Webber and Gary Barlow write Jubilee song| publisher=BBC| work=BBC News| date=24 February 2012| accessdate=20 April 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418202717/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-17152327| archivedate=18 April 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=BBC_Blumenthal>{{cite web| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-17757416| title=Heston Blumenthal plans 'best of British' Jubilee picnic| publisher=BBC| work=BBC News| date=18 April 2012| accessdate=20 April 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419224021/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-17757416| archivedate=19 April 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> was held the following day, in front of [[Buckingham Palace]], and featured acts representing each decade of the Queen's 60-year reign.\n\n[[Street party|Street parties]] were permitted to take place across the country.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.communities.gov.uk/newsstories/newsroom/1700319| last=Department for Communities and Local Government| title=The new, simple, easy-to-use form to organise street parties has arrived!| publisher=[[Queen's Printer]]| accessdate=19 February 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202145525/http://www.communities.gov.uk/newsstories/newsroom/1700319| archivedate=2 February 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Special community lottery grants, called ''The Jubilee People's Millions'', are being offered by the [[Big Lottery Fund]] and [[ITV plc|ITV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peoplesmillions.org.uk/faqs|title=Lottery Millions to Help Communities Bloom for Diamond Jubilee|publisher=The National Lottery|accessdate=19 February 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110305184121/http://www.peoplesmillions.org.uk/faqs|archivedate=5 March 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nMembers of the Royal Family, governors-general, and prime ministers from the Commonwealth realms were present at various functions held on 4 and 5 June: A reception took place at Buckingham Palace before the Diamond Jubilee Concert and a service of thanksgiving was conducted the following day at [[St Paul's Cathedral|St. Paul's Cathedral]], also attended by 2,000 other guests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stpauls.co.uk/News-Press/News-Archive/2012/Queen-celebrates-Jubilee-at-St-Pauls-images|title=Queen celebrates Jubilee at St Paul's|publisher=St Paul's Cathedral|accessdate=20 September 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921054306/http://www.stpauls.co.uk/News-Press/News-Archive/2012/Queen-celebrates-Jubilee-at-St-Pauls-images|archivedate=21 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Will Todd]]'s anthem \"The Call of Wisdom\", commissioned specially for this event, was performed by the Diamond Choir, made up of about 40 children from around the UK.<ref>{{cite web| title=OUP: Diamond Jubilee anthem by Will Todd| url=http://www.oup.com/uk/pressreleases/willtodd/| publisher=Oxford University Press| accessdate=3 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606130004/http://www.oup.com/uk/pressreleases/willtodd/| archivedate=6 June 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Diamond Choir: Meet the Choir| url=http://www.diamondchoir.co.uk/meet-the-choir.asp| publisher=St. Paul's Cathedral| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723171816/http://www.diamondchoir.co.uk/meet-the-choir.asp| archivedate=23 July 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[The Archbishop of Canterbury]] dedicated his sermon to the Queen, during which he noted her \"lifelong dedication\" and stated that she \"has made her 'public' happy and all the signs are that she is herself happy, fulfilled and at home in these encounters.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18330637| title=Dr Williams pays tribute to the Queen at thanksgiving| date=5 June 2012| publisher=BBC| accessdate=24 June 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120610205106/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18330637| archivedate=10 June 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Afterwards, a formal lunch was held in [[Westminster Hall]]. The Queen returned to [[Buckingham Palace]] at 2:20 pm, in an open top carriage procession and escorted by [[The Household Cavalry Regiment]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18327711 Diamond jubilee: Flypast bring celebrations to an end] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608190912/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18327711 |date=8 June 2012 }} BBC News. Accessed 24 June 2012.</ref> Another reception was held at [[Guildhall, London|London's Guildhall]] and a luncheon took place at [[Lancaster House]], hosted by the British [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]].<ref name=GlobePomp /><ref name=GGLondon /> A reception solely for governors-general was held by the Queen at Buckingham Palace.<ref name=GGLondon />\n\nThe weekend of celebrations ended with a balcony appearance at Buckingham Palace. The Queen appeared on the balcony with the Prince of Wales, the Duchess of Cornwall, the Duke of Cambridge, the Duchess of Cambridge, and Prince Harry in front of cheering crowds outside the palace and along [[The Mall, London|The Mall]]. There followed a [[feu de joie]] and a [[flypast]] by the [[Red Arrows]] and historic aircraft,<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18327711 Diamond Jubilee: flypast brings celebrations to an end] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608190912/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18327711 |date=8 June 2012 }} BBC News. Accessed 5 June 2012.</ref> including the last flying [[Lancaster bomber]] in Britain.  Several media commentators commented on the significance of only senior members of the royal family appearing on the balcony.  BBC royal correspondent Peter Hunt remarked that it \"sent a message demonstrating both continuity and restraint at a time of austerity\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18327711 Diamond Jubilee: flypast brings celebrations to an end] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608190912/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18327711 |date=8 June 2012 }} BBC News. Accessed 24 June 2012.</ref>\n\n====Permanent tributes====\n\nTo mark the jubilee, the Queen bestowed [[List of UK place names with royal patronage#Royal Borough|Royal Borough]] status on [[Royal Borough of Greenwich|Greenwich]], in southeast London.<ref name=PA /><ref name=GC>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenwich.gov.uk/Greenwich/LeisureCulture/RoyalGreenwich/RoyalGreenwich.htm |title=Greenwich to become Royal Borough |publisher=Greenwich Council |date=5 January 2010 |accessdate=5 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108082815/http://www.greenwich.gov.uk/Greenwich/LeisureCulture/RoyalGreenwich/RoyalGreenwich.htm |archivedate=8 January 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> In addition, a competition was held to grant in 2012 [[City status in the United Kingdom|city status]] to towns and either a [[List of lord mayoralties and lord provostships in the United Kingdom|lord mayoralty or lord provostship]] to one city.{{refn|The towns that bid for city status were:<ref name=entrants>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-13796689| title=More than 25 towns bid for Diamond Jubilee city status| publisher=BBC| date=16 June 2011| accessdate=18 June 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617043606/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-13796689| archivedate=17 June 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bolton, Bournemouth, Chelmsford, Colchester, Coleraine, Corby, Craigavon, Croydon, Doncaster, Dorchester, Dudley, Dumfries, Gateshead, Goole, Luton, Medway, Middlesbrough, Milton Keynes, Perth, Reading, Southend, St Asaph, St Austell, Stockport, Tower Hamlets, and Wrexham.\n\nThe cities that bid for a Lord Mayoralty or Lord Provostship were:<ref name=entrants /> Armagh, Cambridge, Derby, Gloucester, Lancaster, Newport, Peterborough, Salford, Southampton, St Albans, Sunderland, and Wakefield.|group=n|name=Cities}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11887723|title=Diamond Jubilee to be marked by creation of new UK city|publisher=BBC|date=1 December 2010|accessdate=1 December 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204074545/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11887723|archivedate=4 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> City status was awarded to [[Chelmsford]] in England, [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]] in Scotland and [[St Asaph]] in Wales. [[Armagh]], Northern Ireland, was awarded the Lord Mayoralty.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-17364651|title=Three towns win city status for Diamond Jubilee|publisher=BBC|date=14 March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425183250/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-17364651|archivedate=25 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Olympic park in East London, created for the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London Olympics]], was named the [[Olympic Park, London|Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park]] following the Olympics.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Games site renamed the Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park| publisher=BBC| date=7 October 2010| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-11492273| accessdate=15 October 2010| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101014074838/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-11492273| archivedate=14 October 2010| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Queen Elizabeth II Fields Challenge (Queen Elizabeth Fields Challenge in Scotland) was a project of the charity [[Fields in Trust]] to safeguard parks and green spaces as public recreation land in perpetuity for future generations to enjoy, and to provide a permanent legacy of the Diamond Jubilee and the Olympics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalfoundation.com/our-work/queen-elizabeth-ii-fields-challenge/|title=Queen Elizabeth II Fields Challenge|publisher=The Royal Foundation|accessdate=24 July 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729104839/http://www.royalfoundation.com/our-work/queen-elizabeth-ii-fields-challenge/|archivedate=29 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Woodland Trust]] planned to establish 60 Jubilee [[woodland]]s during 2011 and 2012, one of almost 500 acres \u2013 [[Flagship Diamond Wood]], Leicestershire \u2013 and the remainder 60 acres each.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-14327232| title=Woodland Trust searching for jubilee wood site| publisher=BBC| date=30 July 2011| accessdate=30 July 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110730171623/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-14327232| archivedate=30 July 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA stained glass window, paid for by MPs and members of the House of Lords, was unveiled in the Queen's presence at [[Westminster Hall]] in March 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kennedy|first=Maev|title=Queen's diamond jubilee stained glass window unveiled by MPs|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/mar/20/queen-diamond-jubilee-glass|accessdate=5 June 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=20 March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129203218/http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/mar/20/queen-diamond-jubilee-glass|archivedate=29 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In addition, a majority of MPs endorsed the renaming of the [[clock tower]] of [[Westminster Palace]] that houses Big Ben, to the [[Elizabeth Tower]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Hough|first=Andrew|title=The Queen's Diamond Jubilee: 'Big Ben to be renamed Elizabeth Tower'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9307060/The-Queens-Diamond-Jubilee-Big-Ben-to-be-renamed-Elizabeth-Tower.html|accessdate=3 June 2012|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|date=3 June 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603034658/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9307060/The-Queens-Diamond-Jubilee-Big-Ben-to-be-renamed-Elizabeth-Tower.html|archivedate=3 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:RoyalJubileeBells in the church.jpg|thumb|The Royal Jubilee Bells in St James Garlickhythe before being hung in the church's tower]]\nThe [[Royal Jubilee Bells]], made for the Jubilee and a feature of the [[Thames Diamond Jubilee Pageant]], were delivered to the church of [[St James Garlickhythe]] in the [[City of London]] on 15 June 2012 and arranged along the central aisle. They were dedicated by the [[John Waine|Rt Revd John Waine]] on Sunday 17 June and hanging commenced in the tower shortly thereafter. They were rung for the first time in the church on 4 July.<ref>{{cite web|last=Love|first=Dickon R.|url=http://london.lovesguide.com/james_garlickhythe.htm|title=Church Bells of the City of London - St James Garlickhythe|publisher=Love's Guide to the Bells of the City of London|accessdate=5 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170311191225/http://london.lovesguide.com/james_garlickhythe.htm|archivedate=11 March 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Royal Mint issued a number of coins including an official \u00a35 coin, a 5oz coin and a kilo coin.<ref>Sovereign Mint [http://sovereignmint.co.uk/queen-elizabeth-iis-diamond-jubilee-coins-issued-for-2012/ \"Official Diamond Jubilee coins from the Royal Mint\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426173640/http://sovereignmint.co.uk/queen-elizabeth-iis-diamond-jubilee-coins-issued-for-2012/ |date=26 April 2015 }}, ''[[Official Diamond Jubilee coins from the Royal Mint]]''</ref> A five-pound [[sterling silver]] coin was issued by the Government of Gibraltar to mark the occasion.<ref>Towermint [http://www.towermint.com/Shop/product/27 \"Diamond Jubilee Five Pounds Silver Coin\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805185313/http://www.towermint.com/Shop/product/27 |date=5 August 2012 }}, ''[[Diamond Jubilee Five Pounds Silver Coin]]'', 1 May 2012.  Retrieved on 7 November 2012.</ref>\n\nIn October 2012 it was announced that the Queen would bestow the honorary title of [[Regius Professor]]ship to up to six university chairs in the United Kingdom, to recognise \"excellence in teaching and research\";<ref>{{Cite news| title=New Regius professorships to mark Jubilee| author=Elizabeth Gibney| url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/421475.article| magazine=Times Higher Education| date=12 October 2012| accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref> the number was chosen to represent the decades of the Queen's reign.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/80218/Entry-Guidelines-Q-A.pdf| format=PDF| title=Regius Professorships \u2013 entry guidelines| date=October 2012| publisher=[[Cabinet Office]]| accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref> The full list was announced on 29 January 2013 and comprised twelve new chairs, in recognition of the \"exceptionally high quality\" of the departments considered.<ref>{{Cite press release| title=Cabinet Office: The Queen awards prestigious Regius professorships to twelve universities| date=29 January 2013| publisher=PoliticsHome| url=http://www.politicshome.com/uk/article/70924/cabinet_office_the_queen_awards_prestigious_regius_professorships_to_twelve_universities.html| accessdate=3 April 2013| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322001916/http://www.politicshome.com/uk/article/70924/cabinet_office_the_queen_awards_prestigious_regius_professorships_to_twelve_universities.html| archivedate=22 March 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|Kew Gardens]] announced that the Main Gate, the entrance to the gardens from Kew Green, was to be renamed Elizabeth Gate in honour of the Queen. [[Princess Alexandra, The Honourable Lady Ogilvy|Princess Alexandra]] attended the naming ceremony on 21 October 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/news/9993864.Royalty_opens_Kew_Gardens__Elizabeth_Gate/|title=Royalty opens Kew Gardens' Elizabeth Gate|work=Richmond and Twickenham Times|date=21 October 2012|accessdate=12 July 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714130113/http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/news/9993864.Royalty_opens_Kew_Gardens__Elizabeth_Gate/|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 December 2012, the [[British Foreign Office]] announced that a portion of the British Antarctic Territory was to be named [[Queen Elizabeth Land]] in honour of Her Majesty in her diamond jubilee year.<ref>{{cite web|title=UK to name part of Antarctica Queen Elizabeth Land|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20757382|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=18 December 2012|date=18 December 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103083842/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20757382|archivedate=3 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA seemingly less permanent tribute that gained widespread popularity was a work provided by street artist [[Banksy]]. His [[Slave Labour (mural)|\"Slave Labour\"]] stencil on a north London wall offered pointed criticism of the jubilee celebrations and the conditions that support British nationalism.<ref>Sarah Lyall, {{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/01/world/europe/give-us-our-banksy-mural-back-londoners-say.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-02-26 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304110740/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/01/world/europe/give-us-our-banksy-mural-back-londoners-say.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 |archivedate=4 March 2013 |df=dmy-all }}, ''The New York Times'', 1 March 2013.</ref> The mural's removal and subsequent attempted sale at auction in February 2013 sparked international controversy, highlighting the piece's worth to local and regional residents.<ref>Richard Luscombe, {{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2013/feb/23/banksy-missing-mural-auction-stopped |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-04-18 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014183955/http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2013/feb/23/banksy-missing-mural-auction-stopped |archivedate=14 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}, ''The Guardian'', 23 February 2013</ref> Its title, perhaps coincidentally, conjured another contentious part of the celebrations where unemployed workers, bussed into London on an allegedly unpaid trial to staff security for the event, were made to work under what some described as \"appalling\" conditions.<ref>Felicity Morse, {{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/06/05/kerry-mccarthy-mp-jubilee-workfare-unemployed_n_1570067.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-03-28 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209050000/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/06/05/kerry-mccarthy-mp-jubilee-workfare-unemployed_n_1570067.html |archivedate=9 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}, ''Huffington Post'', 5 June 2012.</ref>\n\n====Other events====\nOn Accession Day, 6 February, a 62-[[21-gun salute|gun salute]] was mounted on the banks of the [[River Thames]], near the [[Tower of London]] and the Queen made a visit to [[Norfolk]], one of the first places the monarch visited after acceding to the throne.<ref name=BelStamps /> Later in the month, Queen Elizabeth attended a multi-faith (Bah\u00e1'\u00ed, Buddhist, Christian, Hindu, Jain, Jewish, Muslim, Sikh, and Zoroastrian) reception held at the residence of the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[Lambeth Palace]], in honour of the jubilee.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://news.bahai.org/story/889| title=Queen launches Diamond Jubilee year with multifaith reception| date=21 February 2012| publisher=Bah\u00e1'\u00ed World News Service| accessdate=25 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526103746/http://news.bahai.org/story/889| archivedate=26 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Queen addressed both houses of [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliament]] in [[Westminster Hall]] on 20 March 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16628608| title=Queen to address Parliament joint session for jubilee| publisher=BBC| date=19 January 2012| accessdate=19 February 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120223033218/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16628608| archivedate=23 February 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Also in March, the [[Royal Commonwealth Society]] launched the Jubilee Time Capsule to mark the jubilee.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.jubileetimecapsule.org| title=Jubilee Time Capsule| publisher=Royal Commonwealth Society| accessdate=15 July 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712104542/http://www.jubileetimecapsule.org/| archivedate=12 July 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]] and [[Andrew Marr]] created the television documentary ''[[The Diamond Queen (TV programme)|The Diamond Queen]]'', in which various members of the Royal Family and current and former politicians spoke about the Sovereign and her life. The documentary was criticised by the campaign group [[Republic (political organisation)|Republic]], which argued that it breached BBC guidelines on impartiality.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-17119720 BBC royal series The Diamond Queen biased, Republic says] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527213129/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-17119720 |date=27 May 2012 }}, ''[[BBC News]]''</ref>\n\nAt Buckingham Palace, a display of the Queen's diamonds was opened to the public.<ref name=GlobePomp /> On 4 June, the bells in each of the 34 church bell towers along the [[River Welland]] valley rang in succession, ending with the ringing of the bell at [[Fosdyke]] 60 times.<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.northantset.co.uk/news/local/a-royal-ring-for-queen-s-jubilee-1-3814645#| title=A royal ring for Queen's jubilee| date=6 May 2012| newspaper=Evening Telegraph| accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 May, the Queen attended the [[Diamond Jubilee Armed Forces Parade and Muster]], the [[British Armed Forces]]' own tribute to the monarch, in [[Windsor Castle]] and nearby [[Home Park, Windsor|Home Park]]. The first time all three services had assembled for the Queen for such an event at the same time, it featured military reviews and a 2,500 strong military parade through the town, as well as a military flypast featuring 78 aircraft.<ref name=BBC_Parade>{{cite web| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18123991| title=Diamond Jubilee: Armed forces in parade and flypast| publisher=BBC| work=BBC News| date=19 May 2012| accessdate=19 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120519031218/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18123991| archivedate=19 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA [[Nowka Bais]] competition in [[Oxford]] was dedicated to the Diamond Jubilee. The Queen issued a statement on the event and expressed her interest about the [[Bengal]]i sporting tradition to the event organisers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/opinion/heritage/2017/07/25/bangladeshi-boat-race-uk|publisher=[[Dhaka Tribune]]|title=Bangladeshi boat race takes the UK by storm|author=Morshed Akhter Badol|date=25 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Overseas territories====\n[[File:Queen's Birthday Parade 2012 - Prince Edward.jpg|thumb|left|The Earl and Countess of Wessex at the Queen's Birthday Parade, Grand Casemates Square, [[Gibraltar]], June 2012]]\n[[Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester]], toured the [[British Virgin Islands]] (BVI) in March 2012. On [[Montserrat]], he met participants in the Sailability BVI programme, including [[Special Olympics]] medallists, and staff and associates of the Eslyn Henley Ritchie Learning Centre, BVI Technical and Vocational Institute, BVI Services, and the Department of Youth Affairs and Sports.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukinmontserrat.fco.gov.uk/en/news/?view=News&id=739827082 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120730041609/http://ukinmontserrat.fco.gov.uk/en/news/?view=News&id=739827082 |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 July 2012 |last=Office of the Governor of Montserrat |authorlink=Governor of Montserrat |title=HRH The Duke of Gloucester Visits Watersports Centre, Inspects Sailability's Fleet |date=8 March 2012 |publisher=[[Queen's Printer]] |accessdate=8 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\n[[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]], and [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex]], visited the British Overseas Territory of [[Gibraltar]], between 11\u201313 June 2012,<ref name=TeleGibraltar>{{citation| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/spain/9258138/Spain-issues-formal-complaint-over-Prince-Edward-Gibraltar-visit.html| last=Govan| first=Fiona| title=Spain issues formal complaint over Prince Edward Gibraltar visit| date=10 May 2012| newspaper=The Telegraph| accessdate=11 May 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511034927/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/spain/9258138/Spain-issues-formal-complaint-over-Prince-Edward-Gibraltar-visit.html| archivedate=11 May 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Montserrat]].{{When|date=March 2012}}<ref name=BBCJplans /> The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation (Spain)|Spanish Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation]] expressed \"upset and concern\" about the couple's tour of Gibraltar, which Spain claims as Spanish territory.<ref name=TeleGibraltar />\n\n==Other Commonwealth countries==\nVisits were planned by [[Anne, Princess Royal|Princess Anne]] to Zambia and Mozambique, while the [[Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester|Duke of Gloucester]] made official visits to Uganda and Malta. In Asia, [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]], visited India, while [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge]], and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]], visited Malaysia, Singapore, and the Solomon Islands.<ref>{{Citation| last=guardian.co.uk| title=Royal family to mark Queen's diamond jubilee with visits to Commonwealth| newspaper=The Guardian| date=14 December 2011| url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/dec/14/royal-family-diamond-jubilee-commonwealth| accessdate=15 December 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317185818/http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/dec/14/royal-family-diamond-jubilee-commonwealth| archivedate=17 March 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]], and [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex]], visited Trinidad and Tobago,<ref>{{cite news|last=Harris|first=Carolyn|title=Royals of the Caribbean: The 2012 Diamond Jubilee Commonwealth Tours Begin|url=http://www.royalhistorian.com/royals-of-the-caribbean-the-2012-diamond-jubilee-commonwealth-tours-begin/|accessdate=22 June 2013|publisher=royalhistorian.com|date=15 February 2012}}</ref> as did [[Governor General of Canada]] [[David Johnston]].\n\n===South Africa===\nThe British Consulate in Cape Town,<ref>UK High Commission Pretoria{{vague|date=June 2012}}</ref> in conjunction with the Hout Bay and Llandudno Heritage Trust, hosted a firing of ancient muzzle-loading cannons at East Fort in Hout Bay. The Hout Bay and Llandudno Heritage Trust restored the Fort's original Swedish made 18 pounder muzzle-loading cannons, dating from 1752, and fired two rolling salvo salutes, of six cannon shots each, in the Queen\u2019s honour and in recognition of the bond of friendship between South Africa and Great Britain. The South African Navy Band was in attendance and the guns were fired by VIPs who were guided by gunners of the \"Honourable Order of Hout Bay Artillerymen\".\n\nAt the Victoria and Alfred Waterfront of the Port of Cape Town, a flotilla from the [[Royal Cape Yacht Club]] sailed past the Hildebrand Ristorante and into-the Victoria Basin and the Cape Town Highlanders marched from Ferryman's to Nobel Square. British Consul General Chris Trott lit a beacon, followed by a further six-gun salute and both South African national anthem and \"God Save the Queen\". {{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Other areas==\n\n===Hong Kong===\nHong Kong, a [[British overseas territory|British dependent territory]] until 1997 and the most populous one, had The Big Jubilee Lunch on 3 June 2012, organised by the [[Royal Commonwealth Society|Royal Commonwealth Society in Hong Kong]]. On 5 June 2012, there was a service of thanksgiving at the territory's [[Hong Kong Sheng Kung Hui|Anglican]] [[St. John's Cathedral (Hong Kong)|Cathedral Church of St. John the Evangelist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukinhongkong.fco.gov.uk/en/visiting-uk/jubilee-2012/hk-events |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20121214012754/http://ukinhongkong.fco.gov.uk/en/visiting-uk/jubilee-2012/hk-events |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 December 2012 |title=Hong Kong Jubilee 2012 Events |publisher=UK in Hong Kong |accessdate=6 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]]\n* [[2012 Diamond Jubilee Honours]]\n* [[Silver Jubilee of Elizabeth II]]\n* [[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II]]\n* [[Sapphire Jubilee of Elizabeth II]]\n* [[List of monarchs in Britain by length of reign]]\n* [[List of Jubilees of British monarchs]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n{{Reflist|group=\"n\"}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Diamond Jubilee of Queen Elizabeth II}}\n\n* {{Official website|http://www.thediamondjubilee.org/}}\n* [http://www.pch.gc.ca/eng/1296669421850/1296669769856 Department of Canadian Heritage: The Queen's Diamond Jubilee]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120210133249/http://gg.govt.nz/content/diamond-jubilee Governor-General of New Zealand: The Queen's Diamond Jubilee]\n* [http://www.royal.gov.uk/HMTheQueen/TheQueenandspecialanniversaries/TheQueensDiamondJubilee2012/TheQueensDiamondJubilee2012.aspx The British Monarchy: The Queen's Diamond Jubilee 2012]\n* [http://www.jubileetribute.org/#&slider1=1 The Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust]\n* [http://www.diamondjubileebeacons.co.uk/ Official Diamond Jubilee Beacons website]\n* [http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/onlinereview2013/the-queens-realms/index.html The Prince of Wales and Duchess of Cornwall's Diamond Jubilee tours]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G7kRM3mh7qc&feature=endscreen Governor General of Canada David Johnston's Diamond Jubilee message]\n* [http://www.historymuseum.ca/exhibitions/past-exhibitions/a-queen-and-her-country3 Canadian Museum of History: A Queen and Her Country]\n* [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/60160/supplement/1 Loyal Addresses on The London Gazette]\n* ''[http://www.archives.gov.on.ca/en/explore/online/jubilee/index.aspx The Archives of Ontario Celebrates the Diamond Jubilee of Queen Elizabeth II]'', online exhibit on Archives of Ontario website\n\n{{Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Diamond Jubilee}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n\n[[Category:Elizabeth II]]\n[[Category:Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II| ]]\n[[Category:British monarchy]]\n[[Category:Events involving British royalty]]\n[[Category:Anniversaries]]\n[[Category:2012 in Australia]]\n[[Category:2012 in Canada]]\n[[Category:2012 in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:2012 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Monarchy in Australia]]\n[[Category:Monarchy in Canada]]\n[[Category:Monarchy in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:2012 in South Africa]]\n[[Category:2012 in Belize]]\n[[Category:2012 in Barbados]]\n[[Category:2012 in the Bahamas]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "date format audit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diamond_Jubilee_of_Elizabeth_II"}
{"title_page": "Book of Discipline (Quaker)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2009}}\n\nA '''Book of Discipline''' may refer to one of the various books issued by a [[Yearly Meeting]] of the [[Religious Society of Friends]], setting out what it means to be a [[Quaker]] in that [[Yearly Meeting]].  The common name for this book varies from one [[Yearly Meeting]] to another and includes ''Book of Discipline'', ''Faith and Practice'', ''Christian Faith and Practice'', ''Quaker Faith and Practice'', ''Church Government'' and ''Handbook of Practice and Procedure''.  Each Book of Discipline is updated periodically by each [[Yearly Meeting]] according to the usual practice of decision making within the [[Religious Society of Friends]].\n\n==Text and usage==\nThe contents of each book of discipline is agreed on by seeking unity among members of the authoring yearly meeting. Instead of voting or seeking an earthly consensus, the Meeting attempts to gain a sense of God's will for the community. Each member of the meeting is expected to listen to that of God within themselves and, if led, to contribute it to the group for reflection and consideration. Each member listens to others' contributions carefully, in an attitude of seeking Truth rather than of attempting to prevail or to debate. This process can be tedious and lengthy.  Nevertheless, this is thought to be the best way of reflecting the breadth of Quaker theology and practice, and is consistent with an intention that they be based in evolving personal experience and '[[inner light]]' rather than fixed [[creed]]s. The writings are not intended to represent strict rules which followers must agree with or adhere to, but may be used as a source of guidance or discipline. Since the majority of the Society remains within a Christian theistic tradition, this is typically reflected in the publication.\n\nExtracts from the book are sometimes read aloud in Quaker meetings for worship, or may be reflected upon individually.\n\n==History==\nThe Quakers are today almost the only survivors from the many religious groups that sprang up in the religious and social ferment of the English Civil War (1642\u20131649). They survived and flourished largely through the practical wisdom of a young man whose spiritual experiences and insights launched the movement. His name was George Fox. At the age of nineteen he entered a troubled period in which he found no spiritual help. Leaving home, he wandered for four years, consulting priests and non-conformist ministers. Having reached the point of near despair, he had a vivid spiritual experience, as he wrote in his Journal: \"When my hopes in all men were gone...then O then I heard a voice which said \"There is one, even Christ Jesus that can speak to thy condition\". And when I heard it, my heart did leap for joy.\"\n\nFeeling the call to preach he met a group of former Baptists, and together they called themselves \"The Children of Light\". Over the years, moving from the English Midlands into Yorkshire, Fox was accepted by a group of Seekers. As time went on they began to refer to themselves as \"Friends in the Truth\", and it is this that gives us the official name of the \"Religious Society of Friends\". The term \"Quakers\", which sometimes appears in brackets after the official name, comes from an insult used by a magistrate in Derby when he was sentencing some Friends for being non-conformist (Fox had bidden him to \"tremble at the word of the Lord\").\n\nOn 13 June 1652 George Fox addressed a crowd of about a thousand people on a hilltop called Firbank Fell in Northern England close to the English Lake District. This event is often considered to be the founding event of the Quaker faith. The rock on which he stood is referred to as Fox's Pulpit. Two weeks later in Ulverston, he met Margaret Fell while preaching in the church there. Margaret and her husband Thomas (a Justice of the Peace and later Member of Parliament) by the greatest good fortune took George Fox into their home, Swarthmoor Hall, and protected him, while the Valiant Sixty of newly converted Quakers ranged far and wide across England, spreading the good news of a simpler form of Christian faith. Some time after Thomas Fell died, Margaret and George were married.\n\nWhile other religious groups of the period faded away with time, Fox devoted himself in 1666\u20131668 to setting up a structure of meetings which has remained virtually the same up until the present day: local 'particular' meetings, grouped regionally into \"monthly meetings\", \"quarterly meetings\" above them, and an annual \"General Assembly of the Brethren\" (usually referred to as a Yearly Meeting) as the leading authority. There has been a national annual meeting of some sort in Britain every year since 1668.\n<ref>Alastair Heron \"The British Quakers 1647\u20131997\" Curlew Publishers, 1997</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\nThe earliest statement of Christian discipline was the ''[[Epistle (Quaker)|Epistle]] from the meeting of Elders at Balby'', in 1656.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qhpress.org/texts/balby.html |title=Balby Letter of 1656 |publisher=Qhpress.org |date=16 November 2001 |accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> This was a list of twenty advices as to how Friends should conduct themselves, formed following a meeting of prominent Seekers at Balby in Yorkshire, and is seen by many as the defining document founding Quakerism.\n\nThe ''Canons and institutions drawn up and agreed upon by the General Assembly or Meeting of the heads of the Quakers from all parts of the kingdom''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/2447177?lookfor=&offset=&max=228 |title=Canons and institutions [microform&#93; / drawn up and agreed upon by the General Assembly or Meeting of... &#124; National Library of Australia |publisher=Catalogue.nla.gov.au |accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> was produced following a meeting of leading Quakers in London in 1669.  This had been drafted by [[George Fox]], the name ''Canons and Institutions'' had been given to the publication by his opponents.  It contained general advices and regulations, and was the basis of future books of discipline, although the name was formally disclaimed by Friends in 1675.<ref>[http://www.wilmingtonyearlymeeting.org/faith/introduction.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080708135412/http://www.wilmingtonyearlymeeting.org/faith/introduction.htm |date=8 July 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe origins of the current book of discipline can be traced back to a manuscript in 1738 entitled ''Christian and brotherly advices given forth from time to time by the Yearly Meetings in London, alphabetically digested under proper heads''.  The first printed collection appeared in 1783 as ''Extracts from the minutes and advices of the Yearly Meeting of Friends held in London from its first institution'' (popularly known as the ''Book of Extracts'').  This was revised in 1801 and 1822 and 1833 (the last revision resulting in another change in title to ''Rules of Discipline'').  Up until this time, the publication was an alphabetical list of the main beliefs and practices of Quakers at the time.\n\nFrom 1861 the ''Rules of Discipline'' was divided into separate chapters on\n*''Christian Doctrine'' \u2013 concerning the Christian theology and beliefs of Friends;\n*''Christian Practice'' \u2013 concerning the lives and testimonies of Friends\n*''Church Government'' \u2013 concerning the organisation, structure and government of the Religious Society of Friends, instead of the alphabetical arrangement of topics.  This was revised in 1883, where it took the name ''Book of Christian discipline''.  Subsequently, the three chapters became three separate books, revised at various points over the next 50 years.\n\nIn 1921, a new publication ''Christian Life, Faith and Thought'' replaced the previous ''Christian Doctrine''.  This publication adopted a new approach of attempting \"to state truth, not by formulating it, but by expressing it through the vital personal and corporate experience of Friends\". Although much of this publication is in the form of prose drafted by a Revision Committee, this publication began the use of extracts which has subsequently been developed as an acceptable method of expressing the breadth of Quaker theology. In 1959 ''Christian Life, Faith and Thought'' and ''Christian Practice'' were revised, followed by a revision in 1967 of ''Church Government'', and the three were merged into one new volume entitled ''Christian faith and practice in the experience of the Society of Friends''.  The 1959 edition of ''Christian Faith and Practice'', whilst no longer used in Britain Yearly Meeting, is still a current book of discipline of Canadian Yearly Meeting.  ''Church Government'' and ''Christian faith and practice'' together made up the Book of Discipline.\n\nA new British revision was worked on from 1985, due to requests \"not from the centre but from local meetings and individual Friends, as well as committees\".<ref name=NotFromTheCentre>{{cite book|title= Quaker Faith and Practice|edition= 3rd|author=Britain Yearly Meeting|isbn=0-85245-306-X|page=14}}</ref> to reflect developments in society, language and belief. The new version was accepted by Britain Yearly Meeting in 1994, and appeared in print in 1995, in one volume.  This volume is almost entirely made up of an anthology of extracts from other sources, unlike earlier editions.  This edition saw the name change to its current form \u2013 ''Quaker Faith and Practice: The book of Christian discipline of the Yearly Meeting of the Religious Society of Friends in Britain''. The chapters on the structure and organisation of Britain Yearly Meeting have been revised several times since then to reflect organisational changes in Britain Yearly Meeting, and latterly to re-write the Chapter on 'Quaker marriage procedure' in connection with the Quaker approval of same-sex marriage. The rest of the book as currently exists has not been redrafted since 1994; however the process of doing so is currently beginning, as agreed by Britain Yearly Meeting in 2018.\n\nSome Quakers in Britain have suggested that future editions revert to having two volumes to the Book of Discipline: ''Church Government'' dealing with organisation, structure and government of the Yearly Meeting; and ''Faith and Practice'' dealing with the beliefs, testimonies and practices of Quakers in Britain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefriend.org/articledisplay.asp?articleid=2403 |title=The Quaker magazine |publisher=The Friend |accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> The Fifth edition as revised through 2013 is available online.\n\n===United States===\nVarious Yearly Meetings were founded in what is now the [[United States]] from the early days of Quakerism.  Each of these produced their own book of discipline, although each was based on the earlier disciplines of London Yearly Meeting.  These were revised at various points according to changes in beliefs and practices of Friends over time.\n\nConferences of Yearly Meetings in the later part of the nineteenth century, between the [[Joseph John Gurney|Guerneyite]] Yearly Meetings, who had accepted the [[Richmond Declaration|Richmond Declaration of Faith]], proposed formulating a ''Uniform Discipline'' for all the Guerneyite Yearly Meetings in the United States.  In 1897, [[New England Yearly Meeting]], [[Wilmington Yearly Meeting]], [[Indiana Yearly Meeting]], and [[Kansas Yearly Meeting]] jointly accepted ''The Constitution and Discipline for the American Yearly Meetings of Friends'' as their book of discipline, and this book was subsequently accepted as the book of discipline of [[California Yearly Meeting]], [[New York Yearly Meeting]], [[Western Yearly Meeting]], and [[Baltimore Yearly Meeting]] in 1901; and of [[Oregon Yearly Meeting]], [[North Carolina Yearly Meeting]], and [[Iowa Yearly Meeting]] in 1902. When [[Nebraska Yearly Meeting]] was founded in 1908, they too accepted ''The Constitution and Discipline for the American Yearly Meetings of Friends'' as their book of discipline.\n\nIn 1940, [[Evangelical Friends International#History|Five Years Meeting]] proposed that the 1897 ''Uniform Discipline'' be updated and revised.  The ensuing publication ''Faith and Practice'', was published in three volumes: (I) Faith and Life; (II) Organisation and Business Procedure; (III) Authorised Declaration of Faith.  However, controversies and disagreements between Yearly Meetings meant that not all Yearly Meetings accepted this book of discipline \u2013 some accepted only one or two volumes, and others made revisions or alterations to the text.  The publication was never formally accepted by Five Years Meeting, although some Yearly Meetings did formally accept a revised version as their own book of discipline.  Since then, each Yearly Meeting has revised their own books of discipline, and no longer use a ''Uniform Discipline''.\n\n====Philadelphia Yearly Meeting====\nPhiladelphia Yearly Meeting published their ''Rules of Discipline of the Yearly Meeting of Friends held in Philadelphia'' in 1806,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qhpress.org/texts/obod/ |title=The Old Discipline |publisher=Qhpress.org |accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> with paragraphs on each of the main practices and testimonies of Friends in that Yearly Meeting arranged in alphabetical order.  The title ''Faith and Practice'' was first applied to Philadelphia Yearly Meeting's book of discipline in 1955 and it was revised in 1972, 1979, and 1997, with minor revisions in 2002.\n\n==Current books of discipline==\n{{Expand list|date=April 2009}}\nThere are currently over 30 different versions in print, each by a different yearly meeting, some also available to be viewed on-line.  The names of the publications vary.  Most Yearly Meetings either have:\n*One volume called the ''Book of Discipline''\n*Two volumes, which together make up the ''Book of Discipline'':\n**One called either ''Church Government'' or ''Handbook of Practice and Procedure'' \u2013 which deals with how the Yearly Meeting is organised and governed;\n**The other book called either ''Faith and Practice'' or ''Faith, Life and Thought'' or similar title \u2013 which deals with the main beliefs, doctrines and testimonies of the Quakers in that Yearly Meeting.\n\n===Australia===\n[[Australia Yearly Meeting]] publishes two separate books in the tradition of Quaker books of discipline. The ''Handbook of Practice and Procedure'' gives a brief history of the Society and detailed instructions on how the Society in Australia is run.<ref name=\"aus_prac\">Australia Yearly Meeting (2005) [http://www.quakers.org.au/pubs_handbook4.shtml Handbook of Practice and Procedure] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070410234104/http://www.quakers.org.au/pubs_handbook4.shtml |date=10 April 2007 }}, 4th Edition</ref> ''This We Can Say: Quaker life, faith and thought'', first published in 2003, was written over a period of ten years from 1993, to express personally the living faith of contemporary Australian Quakers.<ref name=\"aus_say\">[http://www.quakers.org.au/old_pubs_twcs.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808175838/http://www.quakers.org.au/old_pubs_twcs.html |date=8 August 2007 }}</ref> It also includes the Britain Yearly Meeting Advices and Queries.\n\n===Britain===\n[[File:Quaker Faith And Practice.gif|thumb|The third edition of ''Quaker Faith and Practice'']]\n[[Britain Yearly Meeting]]'s current book of discipline is called ''Quaker Faith and Practice: The book of Christian discipline of the Yearly Meeting of the Religious Society of Friends (Quakers) in Britain''. The text of the first edition was originally approved by the Yearly Meeting of the Religious Society of Friends in Britain in 1994, and it has had four revisions since then, mainly because of changes in the structure of the Yearly Meeting. The fourth revision (giving rise to the 5th Edition, dated 2013) was in connection with the Quaker approval of same-sex marriage in the UK. It is often known simply as ''Quaker Faith and Practice'', or sometimes the (Christian) 'Book of Discipline' but this has become less common. The current version, therefore, (in June 2014) is the fifth edition. It is available in paperback, hardback and large print, and is also free to view online.<ref name=BYM_FandP>[http://www.quaker.org.uk/qfp ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080112132859/http://www.quaker.org.uk/qfp |date=12 January 2008 }}</ref> The book is only available from the Quaker Bookshop in Friends House, Euston, London, UK or from the online bookshop.<ref name=\"quakerbookshop\">{{cite web|author=Quakers in Britain |url=http://www.quaker.org.uk/bookshop |title=Quakers in Britain |publisher=Quaker.org.uk |accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe first chapter, Advices and Queries, originated from queries asked by London Yearly Meeting (the predecessor to Britain Yearly Meeting) to the quarterly meetings about the state of their meetings, and advices originated from the original ''Christian and brotherly advices given forth from time to time by the Yearly Meetings in London, alphabetically digested under proper heads''. Until 1994, there were separate ''General Advices'' and ''Queries'', which tended to be related to each other \u2013 the advices giving advice on Christian living, and the queries being questions which asked Friends how they were living their lives, and could be used for personal reflection or discussion in groups. There was a requirement that all the advices and queries were read in each meeting over the course of a year.  Since 1994, the advices and queries have been mixed together, so that each paragraph has both advices and queries within it. There is also no longer a requirement that they are read in each meeting, although some meetings do continue this practice.  This chapter is published as a separate free booklet and is published in both [[English language|English]] and [[Welsh language|Welsh]].<ref name=\"quakerbookshop\" />\n\n===Canada===\nThe books of discipline of Canadian Yearly Meeting are made up of three publications:\n* ''Canadian Yearly Meeting Organisation and Procedure'' (current edition published 2004) \u2013 which concerns the organisation, government and structure of Canadian Yearly Meeting, as well as chapters on membership, marriage procedures, etc.;\n* In 2010 Canadian Yearly Meeting published its own book of discipline which has replaced the 1967 edition of ''Christian Faith and Practice in the Experience of the Society of Friends of London Yearly Meeting'' (\"the blue book\"), although it remains a useful reference. The new book is titled ''Faith and Practice of Canadian Yearly Meeting of the Religious Society of Friends''.  \n* ''Advices and Queries'' \u2013 Canadian Yearly Meeting uses the same edition as Britain Yearly Meeting.\n\nIn 2000, Canadian Yearly Meeting appointed a Faith and Practice Development Committee to co-ordinate development of its own ''Faith and Practice'', published in 2010.<ref>[http://www.quaker.ca/Publications/discipline/index.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090527115415/http://www.quaker.ca/Publications/discipline/index.html |date=27 May 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Denmark===\n''R\u00e5d og Sp\u00f8rgsm\u00e5l'' (Advices and Queries) is the Advices and Queries of Denmark Yearly Meeting, being a Danish translation based on the 1994 ''Advices and Queries'' of Britain Yearly Meeting.\n\n===Central and Southern Africa===\nCentral and Southern Africa Yearly Meeting's book of discipline is called ''The Handbook of Practice and Procedure'', including chapters on structure, organisation and government of the Society of Friends and Quaker experience and concerns.  It also includes Central and Southern Africa's Advices and Queries as its final chapter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.geocities.com/Athens/Agora/1187/qhbindx.htm |title=C&SAYM HANDBOOK OF PRACTICE AND PROCEDURE. |publisher=Webcitation.org |accessdate=20 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091022122207/http://geocities.com/Athens/Agora/1187/qhbindx.htm |archivedate=22 October 2009  }}</ref>\n\n===Germany and Austria===\nQuaker communities were established in 1677 and 1678 in what is now Germany at Emden and Friedrichstadt (extinct in 1727).  English and American Friends organized a Quaker colony in Friedensthal (Peace Valley), which existed from 1792 until 1870 in what is now [[Bad Pyrmont]], a city in the district of Hamelin-Pyrmont, in [[Lower Saxony]] (Niedersachsen), Germany.  Land was donated for a meeting house in January 1791 and the Quaker Meeting House was built. In 1933, it was reconstructed and relocated from its original site to Bombergallee 9, Bad Pyrmont.  The German Annual Meeting (Deutsche Jahresversammlung) was organized in 1880.  The Germany Yearly Meeting (die Deutsche Jahresversammlung or DJV) resulted from the 1923 mergers of the German Annual Meeting with the Friends of Quakerism (Freunde des Qu\u00e4kertums) and, in 1925, the Federation of German Friends (Bund der deutschen Freunde) and serves as an umbrella organization for the small liberal Quaker presence in [[Germany]] and [[Austria]].  This body uses a translation of [[Britain Yearly Meeting]]'s current book of discipline  ''Quaker Faith and Practice: The book of Christian discipline of the Yearly Meeting of the Religious Society of Friends (Quakers) in Britain'' entitled ''Qu\u00e4ker\u2014Glaube und Wirken (das Handbuch der Qu\u00e4ker zur christlichen Lebensf\u00fchrung, \u00fcbersetzt aus dem Englischen)'', 2010, 468 pp., price:  \u20ac25.00 plus postage, {{ISBN|978-3-929696-44-8}}\n\n===New Zealand===\nIn 2003, the Quakers of New Zealand published ''Quaker faith and practice in Aotearoa New Zealand'', their first manual of Faith and Practice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://quaker.org.nz/quaker-faith-and-practice-in-aotearoanew-zealand |title=Quaker Faith and Practice in Aotearoa/New Zealand |publisher=quaker.org.nz |date=4 January 1998 |accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> The book is 22&nbsp;cm and following three pages of prefatory materials, there are 177 pages of text.  It is published by Yearly Meeting of the Religious Society of Friends (Quakers) of Aortearoa New Zealand, [[Auckland]], New Zealand and distributed by [http://quaker.org.nz/quaker-book-sales Quaker Book Sales].<ref>''Quaker faith & practice in Aotearoa New Zealand'' [http://www.worldcat.org/wcpa/oclc/54069503 OCLC 54069503].</ref>\n\n===Switzerland===\nFriends from Switzerland Yearly Meeting published ''Swiss Quaker Life, Belief and Thought'' in 2009.  It is an anthology of quotes on Swiss Quakers' lives, beliefs and thoughts, published tri-lingually in English, French and German.  It differs from other Yearly Meetings' books of discipline in not containing chapters on the structure and organisation of Switzerland Yearly Meeting. The ''us et coutumes'' (in French) or ''Bra\u00fcche'' (in German) is presenting the organisation of the Society.<ref>See official web site [http://www.swiss-quakers.ch/francais/us.html ''Us et coutumes''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110831014044/http://www.swiss-quakers.ch/francais/us.html |date=31 August 2011 }} and [http://www.swiss-quakers.ch/deutsch/us.html ''Bra\u00fcche''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110831020626/http://www.swiss-quakers.ch/deutsch/us.html |date=31 August 2011 }}. First time in 1947 as ''R\u00e8gles et usages'' (Switzerland Yearly Meeting archives).</ref>\n\n===United States===\nMany of the different [[yearly meeting]]s in the [[United States of America|United States]] have their own books of discipline, most of which are titled ''Faith and Practice''. Many of these are made available both in print and on-line.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pym.org/publish/fnp/otheryms.php|title=Faith and Practice: Other Yearly Meetings|publisher=Philadelphia Yearly Meeting|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061021142349/http://www.pym.org/publish/fnp/otheryms.php|archivedate=21 October 2006}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Conservative Yearly Meetings !! Meeting Formed !! Title !! Year of Adoption\n|-\n|  [http://www.iymc.org/ Iowa Yearly Meeting (Conservative)] ||  1863  ||  ''Faith and Practice''  || [http://iymc.org/documents/discipline1974/default.htm 1974], [http://iymc.org/documents/iymc_faith_and_practice_print_2012.pdf July 2012]\n|-\n| [http://ncymc.org/ North Carolina Yearly Meeting (Conservative)]|| ||  ''Discipline''  || 1869 (revisions in 1876, 1908, 1950, 1969, and 1979) [https://web.archive.org/web/20130330113813/http://ncymc.org/fpframes.html 1983],  [https://web.archive.org/web/20141107161647/http://ncymc.org/Discipline_Revision/index.html Material That Has Received First Approval]\n|-\n|[http://www.ohioyearlymeeting.org/ Ohio Yearly Meeting] || ||''Book of Discipline''|| [https://web.archive.org/web/20141017090612/http://www.ohioyearlymeeting.org/documents/discipline/ 2001] [http://www.ohioyearlymeeting.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/OYM-Discipline-20121.pdf 2001 as pdf, 33 pp.]{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [http://www.ohioyearlymeeting.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/DISCIPLINE-2013.pdf 2013 Discipline (57 pdfs)]\n|-\n!Evangelical Friends Church, International !! Meeting Formed !! Title !! Year of Adoption\n|-\n| Alaska Yearly Meeting || 1970 || ''Handbook of Faith, Practice & Discipline'' || [http://www.quakerinfo.com/alaskaymfp.pdf Revised in 1987 and adopted in 1988]\n|-\n|  [http://www.efcer.org/ Evangelical Friends Church \u2013 Eastern Region] || 1812<ref>First Ohio Yearly Meeting held 1812; 1971 name changes to Evangelical Friends \u2013 Eastern Region</ref> || ''Faith and Practice''<ref>{{cite book|publisher=Evangelical Friends Church, Eastern Region|title=Faith and Practice|url=http://www.efcer.org/Faithandpractice/}}</ref>||[http://www.efcer.org/media/1/9/Faith-and-Practice-2012-Portrait.pdf 2012 Faith and Practice], [https://web.archive.org/web/20140311184121/http://www.efcer.org/media/1/9/Faith-and-Practice-2013.pdf 2013 F&P and Discipline (116 pdfs)]\n|-\n|  [http://www.efcmaym.org/ Evangelical Friends Church, Mid-America Yearly Meeting] ||  1836<ref>Formed in 1836 as the Kansas Yearly Meeting; name changes in 1978 (Kansas dropped) and 2000,</ref>  ||  ''Faith and Practice''<ref>{{cite book|publisher=Evangelical Friends Church, Mid-America Yearly Meeting|title=Faith and Practice|url=http://efcmaym.org/faith_and_practice/main.php|access-date=8 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726015426/http://efcmaym.org/faith_and_practice/main.php|archive-date=26 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>|| [https://web.archive.org/web/20141107225443/http://www.efcmaym.org/faith-and-practice/ Faith and Practice: The Book of Discipline (Link to all five parts in pdf format.)]\n|-\n|  Evangelical Friends Church Southwest || ||''Faith and Practice'' || 2001, [https://web.archive.org/web/20120303135341/http://www.friendschurchsw.org/uploads/2011faithandpractice.pdf 2011 ''Faith and Practice'']\n|-\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20160205104955/http://nwfriends.org/ Northwest Yearly Meeting] ||  ||''Faith and Practice''<ref>{{cite web|title=What Friends Believe|publisher=Northwest Friends|url=http://nwfriends.org/what-friends-believe/|access-date=15 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218155453/http://nwfriends.org/what-friends-believe/|archive-date=18 February 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>||  2008, [http://nwfriends.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/faith-and-practice-2011-2012-08-20.pdf July 2011], [http://nwfriends.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/faith-and-practice-2011-2012-08-20.pdf July 2012 F&P (93 pdfs)]\n|-\n|  Rocky Mountain Yearly Meeting ||  1